http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-2&fd=R&url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/c/a/2007/05/31/GIANTS.TMP&cid=1116827440&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Giants rebound from tough loss Giants rebound from tough loss Henry Schulman, Chronicle Staff Writer Wednesday, May 30, 2007 (05-30) 20:43 PDT New York -- - You could argue from now until the next ice age whether Barry Zito was worth $126 million, but you cannot dispute that he was worth his weight in diamonds to the woebegone Giants on Wednesday night. One night after a loss that sucked the oxygen from their blood and the joy from their souls, the Giants needed a little nourishment and Zito gave them a seven-course feast. He blanked the New York Mets for seven innings, defining the term "stopper," in a 3-0 victory that ended his team's losing streak at four games. "It was awesome, outstanding," said shortstop Omar Vizquel, who contributed four excellent defensive plays. "I think he knew he needed to turn it on tonight and he did, in New York, against a good team. He wanted to show everybody out here what he was all about. It was a great outcome for him." Some pitchers say all wins are the same. Zito recognized this one was not, that after Tuesday's 12-inning balk-a-palooza he had to stand 11 feet high against 295-game winner Tom Glavine, because that is what an ace is supposed to do. "I take that seriously," Zito said. "In 2002 with Oakland I had a real good record after losses (13-1). That's something the team feeds off of. When we had a losing streak, the team could rely on me. It's an important role." Zito allowed six hits, walked one and struck out a season-high seven for his second consecutive victory and his second win against the Mets. He swore he does not want to pitch "with a vendetta against people," but here is a fact: Before the Giants sent the Brinks truck to Zito's driveway, he was negotiating with the Mets. A little birdie spread word that Zito no longer was an ace and no better than a middle-rotation starter, perhaps to drive his price down. Zito believed the birdie had "M-E-T-S" written across its chest. Commanding his curveball and rarely making Bengie Molina move his glove, Zito held Tuesday heroes Jose Reyes and Carlos Delgado hitless in five at-bats combined. No Met reached third base. After throwing 122 pitches, Zito gave way to Jack Taschner for a scoreless eighth, and Brad Hennessey fanned Delgado to start a perfect ninth for his third career save, a good audition should the Giants decide to try another closer. The vilified Armando Benitez was said to be unavailable with swelling in his right knee, which needed to be drained. Pedro Feliz drove in all three runs in rallies that began with two outs. He hit a bases-loaded single on a 3-2 pitch in the first inning that scored Rich Aurilia and Barry Bonds, who each had singled. In the third, Molina singled and scored from first on Feliz's triple off the center-field wall. Feliz had been 2-for-12 lifetime against Glavine. Feliz hit each ball when he was ahead in the count. Perhaps he is learning from Molina, who bats ahead of him and wears pitchers out. Molina saw eight pitches when he walked in the first inning to load the bases and 10 more when he singled in the third. "He is a grinder," manager Bruce Bochy said of his catcher. "He competes so well. He gets great at-bats and he never gives away at-bats. He battles all the time. We know about the clutch hits, and even when he doesn't get a hit, he knows how to build the count up and use all fields." Perhaps the best development for the Giants was Aurilia's 4-for-4 night, coming toward the end of what he described Tuesday as "one of the worst months I've had in a long time." He was 9-for-67 in May before facing Glavine. "I think I matched my last three-week total for hits tonight," Aurilia said. "I made a few adjustments in the cage before the game with the staff. There were a couple of things my teammates saw. It was great to actually implement it and have it work. Hopefully, I can keep it up." The team hopes Zito can keep it up, too. He has allowed one run in his last 14 innings to improve to 5-5. Vizquel faced Zito in the American League and was asked if the left-hander looks the same from behind now as he did when Vizquel used to face him from the batter's box. Vizquel thought for a second and said, "I see a bigger ass now." E-mail Henry Schulman at This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Sprawl clashes with warming in California Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Mo. Toddler Ruins Monks&#x27; Sand Design Gas station owner lowers price to $2.99 per gallon SAN FRANCISCO Officer called a &#x27;suspected&#x27; public danger New league looking to challenge the NFL SF Gate: Entertainment: Horoscope Bush Declares Self &#x27;Mega Decider&#x27; New documents ensure Dubya will rule... Digging biodynamic Restaurateurs look beyond organic in quest to cultivate... Dull, dull, dull, dull South S.F. transit village is a nothing in several... Whales disappear -- rescuers believe they&#x27;re back at sea Kids&#x27; rooms grow up Cute gives way to sophisticated designs, rooms that... PENINSULA / Stanford impostor also fooled people at Santa Clara University... SAN FRANCISCO / Youth mentor, dad of 3, shot dead in North Beach His... Bill would simplify changing names for partners, men Current law makes it... Pass it on -- Norris wants to keep Aces&#x27; legacy alive Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Putin: Missile Tests Are Response to US N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Listener Helps Save Ailing Disc Jockey Judge Will Release Letters in Libby Case See more from this dealer View All Top Autos &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.hamiltonspectator.com/NASApp/cs/ContentServer%3Fpagename%3Dhamilton/Layout/Article_Type1%26c%3DArticle%26cid%3D1180586559233%26call_pageid%3D1112274690688%26col%3D1112274690734&cid=1116812502&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Hamilton Spectator - Sports Index Letters to the Editor GH Athlete of the Year Letter to the Editor Vacation Stop & Start By Keyword (past 14 days) By Date (past 90 days) Jays' rally falls short Mark Blinch / Reuters ROUGH OUTING. Toronto Blue Jays pitcher Jesse Litsch, left, and Sal Fasano react to a play against the New York Yankees during the first inning of last night's game. Toronto's Litsch pounded early ending Jays' two-game win streak TORONTO (May 31, 2007) The Toronto Blue Jays found a way to make things interesting last night after reality kicked rookie Jesse Litsch right in the gut. Litsch, a mere 22 and the toast of the town two weeks ago when he pitched a gem in his big-league debut, was pounded for five runs and failed to escape the first inning. His teammates nearly rallied against the shaky New York Yankees, pulling within one a two-run shot by Matt Stairs in the seventh, but ultimately fell short in a 10-5 loss. Some more dubious on-field antics by Alex Rodriguez in the ninth gave things a nasty turn. The Yankees scored four in the inning, three of them after Rodriguez seemed to yell "Mine!" while running past third baseman Howie Clark as he settled under Jorge Posada's pop fly. Instead of an inning-ending out with the score 7-5, Clark flinched and dropped the ball, allowing another run to score. Shortstop John McDonald immediately began jawing at Rodriguez and had to be restrained by Clark. Manager John Gibbons ran out to argue the play with the umpires and later shouted at Rodriguez as he walked off the field. Jason Giambi followed with a two-run single that made it 10-5. It wouldn't be the first time Rodriguez pulled such a stunt on the field. In Game 6 of the 2004 ALCS versus Boston, he slapped at pitcher Bronson Arroyo's glove on a play at first base. The defeat ended a modest two-game win streak for the Blue Jays (24-28) before a crowd of 29,187 and temporarily stopped the bleeding for the nine-time AL East-champion Yankees. New York (22-29) had lost five straight and 13 of 18 coming into this one and woke up yesterday morning to find pictures of Rodriguez at his hotel with a woman that wasn't his wife splashed all over the New York Post under the headline, "Stray-Rod." It could have been another dagger for an already reeling team but they instead took out some frustration against Litsch (1-2), whose spot on the roster is in doubt with ace Roy Halladay set to come off the disabled list to start against Chicago. Contents copyright 1991-2006, The Hamilton Spectator. All rights reserved. Distribution, transmission or republication of any material from www.thespec.com is strictly prohibited without the prior written permission of . For directions on material reuse, website comments, questions or information send email to
