the first going for 62 minutes. The Australian failed to convert any of his four break points before Gaudio, who beat compatriot Guillermo Coria in a memorable five-set 2004 final, soon took a two-set lead. However if anyone was going to stage a comeback, it was Hewitt, and the 14th seed cut back on unforced errors in the third set which he took with breaks in the third and seventh games and then levelled the contest against a ragged Gaudio by snatching the fourth as the Argentinian's game imploded. Hewitt broke in the first and fifth games of the deciding set and took the match with a love service game after three hours and 28 minutes on Court Philippe Chatrier when Gaudio hit a lazy, tired forehand long. Hewitt had to come back from two sets down to beat Michael Russell in the first round of this year's Australian Open. His first such dramatic recovery came against Guillermo Canas in the fourth round at Roland Garros in 2001, and the second was in 2003 when he beat Roger Federer in a Davis Cup semi-final. Suicide bomber hits Falluja Hariri court 'ignores constitution' On the frontline in Sri Lanka Yemen army attack claims lives Thaksin 'accepts Thai politics ban' Euro qualifiers heat up Spurs first into finals United make double swoop Ducks go 2-0 up Euro qualifiers heat up Spurs first into finals United make double swoop Ducks go 2-0 up
