http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/nyregion/31albany.html&cid Albany Close to Agreement to Ease Ticket Resale Limits - New York Times Albany Close to Agreement to Ease Ticket Resale Limits Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 ALBANY, May 30 — Gov. and state lawmakers are close to reaching agreement on dismantling laws that limit the resale of tickets to musicals, plays, concerts and sports events, but concerns raised recently by the Yankees and Mets appear to have held up a final deal. Skip to next paragraph Nathaniel Brooks for The New York Times Gov. Eliot Spitzer met publicly with legislative leaders Wednesday for the fourth time, seeking to resolve issues before the session ends June 21. The Democratic-led Assembly passed a bill on Tuesday rolling back scalping restrictions, and the Republican-led Senate is expected to approve the bill later this week. The governor has supported the idea but has stopped short of endorsing the bill, partly to give the Yankees and Mets time to argue their case, people involved in the negotiations said. “Ticket scalping laws historically have not worked,” the governor said at an appearance on Wednesday morning. “I think permitting a free market to work its magic there is the smart approach.” The measure was supported by Broadway theater owners, licensed ticket resellers and some stadium and arena owners, who said they were losing profits to brokers, individuals and Web sites that can resell tickets at far higher prices. Consumer advocates, however, have opposed the bill, saying it would cause prices to skyrocket. The Yankees and Mets have expressed concern that holders of season tickets would resell single tickets without authorization from teams. Assemblyman Joseph D. Morelle, a Rochester Democrat who sponsored the legislation, said the Yankees wanted to be the only ones allowed to resell tickets to their games, a provision aimed at stopping season ticket holders from selling their tickets on Web sites like Mr. Morelle said he rejected the idea of letting the Yankees be the only authorized seller of their tickets because it would have defeated the purpose of the bill. “It would be unfair for us to say that we’re freeing up the secondary market while allowing producers to restrict the primary market,” he said. Officials for the Yankees and Mets did not return calls for comment. On Wednesday, the governor and legislative leaders held their fourth public meeting in four weeks to negotiate a number of issues they want to resolve before the end of the session on June 21. While the tone was more cordial than at previous meetings, the issues remain unresolved, including a proposal to expand DNA collection to all felonies and misdemeanors. One exception appears to be a bill requiring testing of people indicted on rape or sexual assault charges. Assembly Speaker said Wednesday that he would allow the bill to come to the Assembly floor before the end of the session. That greatly improves the chance that it will become law. It is supported by the governor and the Republican-led Senate and has a majority of Assembly members as co-sponsors. Currently, a conviction is required to compel an H.I.V. test. The measure has been sharply contested by some Assembly Democrats who are concerned about the civil liberties ramifications of testing suspects prior to conviction. Others believe that rape victims could get a false sense of security if suspects in their attacks test negative for H.I.V. Assemblywoman Nettie Mayersohn, a Queens Democrat and the chief sponsor of the bill in the Assembly, said victims and their doctors should be the ones to decide. “This is a decision that should be made by the woman and not by the legislators in Albany,” she said in a recent interview. The governor also vetoed three bills on Wednesday, including one that would have required contractors to post the prevailing wage rates. Mr. Spitzer argued that contractors who obey the law would be subject to unnecessary paperwork while those who do not pay the prevailing wage now would probably simply ignore the new requirement. The ticket scalping bill would allow tickets to be resold for whatever amount the market would bear. The bill also includes protections against consumer fraud. Under the existing anti-scalping law, which expires in June, licensed ticket resellers may charge up to 45 percent above the face value of tickets for events at large arenas. That law makes an exception for venues with fewer than 6,000 seats, including most Broadway theaters, limiting resale of their tickets to no more than 20 percent, or $5 over face value, whichever is greater. Until recently, that exception was supported by the League of American Theaters and Producers , a Broadway trade organization, whose members felt that an unfettered market would cause prices to go beyond the reach of all but the wealthy. But last fall, the league quietly reversed its position, arguing to a state consumer protection board that prices would not skyrocket if the ban was lifted and that the rise of sites on the Internet had already made it impossible to enforce. Steve A. Malito, a spokesman for a trade organization of licensed brokers that had lobbied to lift the ban for years, said the theater league’s change of heart had been pivotal. “It would appear that they now agree that this ultimately benefits the consumers,” Mr. Malito said. “We’re thrilled that they’ve switched their positions.” Consumer advocates said they thought the league had other motives. “Clearly, they think they can benefit financially with the repeal of anti-scalping law,” said Russ Haven, the legislative counsel for the New York Public Interest Research Group , which has opposed the repeal. Broadway has toyed in recent years with different ways to prevent losing ticket sales to brokers, such as reserving a portion of tickets to every performance and selling them at the box office as “premium tickets.” (The top ticket price to “Jersey Boys” is $121.50; a premium ticket costs $351.50.) By eliminating the caps on ticket resales, Mr. Haven said, the Broadway lobby had signaled that it could no longer beat ticket brokers and scalpers and was joining them. To crack down on street scalpers, the new law does ban the resale of tickets within 500 feet of any venue with 5,000 or fewer seats and within 1,500 feet of larger venues. However, it would allow theaters to open their own resale offices within that zone. In a statement, Charlotte St. Martin, the league’s executive director, praised the anti-fraud provisions in the bill and “the new buffer zone in the theater district that will prevent illegal ticket scalping in front of Broadway theaters.” Campbell Robertson contributed reporting from New York City. Next Article in New York Region (3 of 24) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Reassurance By Fed Chief On Loan Ills Break Seen In Logjam Over Trade Justices Hear Arguments About Pacts On Pricing OPEC Says It Will Not Increase Oil Production to Meet Rising Demand Prices (Fares, Fees and Rates) Next Article in New York Region (3 of 24) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France 50% off Times delivery. Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://news.cincypost.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070531/SPT05/705310328/1027&cid=1116770887&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Cincinnati Post - Who needs a bullpen? Editor of The Cincinnati Post Editor of The Kentucky Post Kentucky Post City Editor Who needs a bullpen? Starters on a roll as Reds win 3rd straight By C. Trent Rosecrans Reds starter Aaron Harang allowed only six hits in his complete-game performance Wednesday. His record is now 6-2. 6 pitches, then the old heave-ho Wednesday's game: Reds 4, Astros 3 Diamondbacks win duel of aging lefties A-Rod's bark bites Blue Jays Norris Hopper dives for home plate in front of Houston catcher Brad Ausmus with the eventual winning run in the sixth inning Wednesday night. Actress Ashley Judd kissed her husband, race car driver Dario Franchitti, after he threw out the ceremonial pitch. Following the seventh inning, Reds starter Aaron Harang told bench coach Bucky Dent - filling in for the ejected manager Jerry Narron - that he was going to finish Wednesday night's game with the Astros. It didn't matter that Harang had just given up his first two hits since the second inning and a run in the Astros' seventh inning. Wednesday night's game belonged to him. Harang gave up another run in the eighth, but retired the Astros in order in the ninth to give Cincinnati a 4-3 victory at Minute Maid Park. The Reds won their third game in a row and sent Houston to its 10th consecutive loss. Harang's outing was the third outstanding showing by a Reds pitcher in a row. Kyle Lohse started the run with a shutout against the Pirates on Monday, Matt Belisle went 7 2/3, allowing four hits and a run on Tuesday in Houston and on Wednesday, Harang allowed six hits and three runs (two earned) in his complete-game performance. None of the three walked a single batter in that stretch. "You want to do better than the guy the night before," Harang said. "We got on Belisle because he couldn't finish it off. It's been a fun time, we're throwing the ball well and rolling." Bronson Arroyo is next in line for the Reds against the 1-7 Woody Williams tonight. Williams' lone victory is against Cincinnati. The Astros are experiencing the malaise that had been infesting the Reds' clubhouse before the current mini-streak. Houston is one loss shy of the franchise record of 11 losses in a row set in August of 1995. The Reds, on the other hand, have won three in a row for the first time since the end of April and first day of May. Cincinnati's turned it around (for the time being, at least) with strong starting pitching and impressive defense, including a spectacular diving stop and throw by third baseman Edwin Encarnacion in the eighth inning. In the 12 games since Encarnacion was recalled from Class AAA Louisville, he has yet to make an error. "I try to do anything to help the team win games," said Encarnacion, who reached base twice Wednesday night on errors by Houston second baseman Craig Biggio. "That's one of the keys to win games, play solid defense and get good pitching." Another key has been good starts - in both the tops and bottoms of innings. Cincinnati leadoff man Norris Hopper has reached base in eight of his nine plate appearances since taking over the position for the injured Ryan Freel on Tuesday. Wednesday, Hopper led off the game with a double, which sparked a three-run outburst to give Harang a comfortable lead with which to work. Hopper then scored the eventual game-winning run in the sixth after he earned a two-out walk -his first walk of the season - and scored on shortstop Alex Gonzalez's double to make it 4-1. "I've been leading off all my life, so I'm pretty comfortable with that role," said Hopper. "With Gonzalez, (Ken) Griffey and (Adam) Dunn hitting behind you, if you get on base, you're going to score. So that's what I try to do. When you get on base, that puts a lot of pressure on the defense, and they've got to be on their toes. You never know when you're going to go for that (stolen) bag, or whatever." That's exactly why Harang was successful, catcher David Ross said. Harang allowed only two batters leading off an inning to reach base - Carlos Lee singled in the seventh and Biggio doubled to start the eighth. Both Lee and Biggio scored in those innings. "It's all about starting off innings, when you get the first batter out, it's a big load off your shoulders," Ross said. "That's when you can cruise a little bit. (Harang) seemed to get that first guy out every inning. It seems like in the past, when we're struggling, that leadoff guy gets on. Then the manager has a ton of things he can do, he can hit-and-run, he can bunt a guy over, he can send him. Then all the bloops we had, some of those are because we're holding the guy on first and it goes over the first baseman's head or something like that." That didn't happen against the Astros on Wednesday. After getting Biggio to lead off the game, Morgan Ensberg singled and then scored on Lee's two-out double. Harang retired right fielder Luke Scott to start the second before Adam Everett singled. Everett would be the last Houston base runner until Lee's seventh-inning single as Harang retired 14 Astros in a row. "You throw strikes and get ahead and good things happen," said Harang, who struck out seven batters. "I was throwing a pretty good sinker today and slider had a good, tight downward movement to it. I threw a couple of good changeups." Harang's gone eight or more innings in three of his last four starts and improved his record to 6-2 on the season. "That's why management was smart and locked him up for a bunch of years - they knew," Ross said of the off- season extension signed by Harang. "He's a good pitcher and he's not afraid. That's what I like, he doesn't change his game for a hitter. His game plan is to go after the zone, if you're going to beat him, you've got to go at him. He's a fun guy to catch because he's so aggressive." Pitching performances like that have also made it fun for the Reds - as has winning. Winning wasn't something the team didn't do much of this month, winning just nine games in May headed into the final day of the month. While still owners of the National League's worst record at 21-33, the Reds could move into a tie for fifth in the National League Central with Houston with a victory today and enter today 8½ games behind slumping Milwaukee. The Reds would also own a percentage-points lead over the Astros for avoiding the dubious title of the NL's worst team. "You can just tell the atmosphere in the locker room is way different than it was five days ago," said Hopper, whose average is up to .321. "Coming off a couple of wins, everyone's hustling and playing hard and that's all you can ask for." Search our site by keyword: Your Guide to the City: Letters to the editors The Enquirer. All rights reserved. Users of this site agree to the /Your California Privacy Rights (Terms updated March 2007) .Build 0: 15 ms (Misc)
