http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-4&fd=R&url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/breaking_news/breakingnews.php%3Fid%3D119131&cid=1116760279&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Bangkok Post Breaking News Hewitt rallies from two sets down to win Paris (dpa) - Australian Lleyton Hewitt rallied from two sets to love down for the fourth time in his career to stun 2004 champion Gaston Gaudio 4-6, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4, 6-2 on Thursday at the French Open. Hewitt, a former number one whose game is coming together again, is on the opposite career track of Argentine Gaudio, whose form has slid badly since his highlight Roland Garros title three years ago. The 28-year-old Argentine has had a misery season with reports of retirement also being considered. The 14th-seeded Hewitt may have hastened that process with his fight-back second-round victory in three hours, 28 minutes. On his back foot in the early stages against Gaudio, who came in with 21 Roland Garros wins, Hewitt dug in for the kind of tennis scrap that he appreciates. With Davis Cup captain John Fitzgerald looking on, the former US Open and Wimbledon winner got himself back into contention as he claimed the third set after two hours and 17 minutes of battle. It took another hour-plus for the Aussie to move through, piling on three love games in the deciding fifth set and advancing on the first of three match points to lift his record at the event to 21-7. Sixth seed Novak Djokovic had to overcome a bout of negativity before knocking out the lowest-ranked player remaining in the draw, reaching the third round 6-3, 3-6, 6-3, 6-1 over Laurent Recourderc. "I'm not so happy with my two performances here," said Djokovic. "But the positive thing is that I've won two matches, two rounds. "It was not easy, I'm favourite even in the next match (against Olivier Patience of France). So I'll try to do my best and start playing better." The Serb was joined as a winner by former Australian Open finalist Marcos Baghdatis, with the 16th seed defeating Dane Kristian Pless 7-5, 6-3, 6-4. "It was a tricky match today," said Baghdatis, based in the city where he learend his tennis. "The 11 a.m. start changed by rhythm of sleeping, waking up early in the morning. "In the first couple of games, I didn't feel good going on court. I was a bit stressed. Slowly, slowly I found the rhythm and the way to win. So that's the most important thing." Djokovic kept pace as he pulled level with Rafael Nadal on 37 season wins, the most on the ATP. Qualifier Recourderc, ranked 306, showed spirit but was ultimately overpowered by the young talent who cracked the Top five for the first time a month ago. Roland Garros was the venue of Djokovic's best Grand Slam showing when he reached the quarter-finals a year ago, retiring with a back injury after two sets against Nadal. He has also three titles so far this season - the same as Roger Federer and second behind Nadal on four. Djokovic fired five aces and broke six times as he advanced on a dry and partly cloudy day at Roland Garros after a week of rain interruptions. In women's play, the Serbian momentum was boosted by seventh seed Ana Ivanovic, who beat Sania Mirza of India 6-1, 6-4. Swiss 14th seed Patty Schnyder moved through to the third round over Kateryna Bondarenko of the Ukraine 6-3, 6-2. The Post Publishing Public Co., Ltd. 2006 Printed display ad enquiries to:
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-2&fd=R&url=http://www.salem-news.com/sports/may312007/ducks_Senators_053107.php&cid=1116235930&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Pahlsson Goal Gives Ducks 2-0 Stanley Cup Lead - Salem-News.Com Sports - May 31, 2007 - 9:14 am Salem-News.com is a locally-owned news service for Salem - Oregon's capitol city and the region surrounding it. Salem-News.com is the Publisher of Frontline-News Pahlsson Goal Gives Ducks 2-0 Stanley Cup Lead The Senators never were able to mount much of an offensive challenge in Game 2, being out-shot 31-16 in the game. ANAHEIM, Calif. - Sammy Pahlsson, a finalist for the Selke Trophy as the NHLâ€™s top defensive forward, was the offensive hero for Anaheim Wednesday night, scoring the lone goal of Game 2 of the Stanley Cup Final as the Ducks blanked the Ottawa Senators, 1-0, to grab a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series. Pahlsson took advantage of a neutral-zone turnover by Ottawaâ€™s Dany Heatley to gain the Senatorsâ€™ zone with some speed. Racing past Daniel Alfredsson, Pahlsson snapped a shot from the dot of the right circle through the legs of defenseman Joe Corvo and past the stick side of goalie Ray Emery for the goal at 14:16 of the third period. â€Well, the goal was a turnover,â€ Pahlsson said. â€œI skated down the wing and stepped once inside and shot it through the legs of the defenseman and somehow, it went in.â€ There was no somehow about it. The shot was a big-time effort that slipped inside the far post. â€That line from the beginning of the year have been able to give us quality minutes,â€ Ducks coach Randy Carlyle said of the Pahlsson, Rob Niedermayer, Travis Moen unit. â€œAnd as you know in the playoffs, everybody steps up the defensive aspect of the game at least 20 to 25 percent. And always, people separate themselves on the offensive side. Itâ€™s nice to see that these three players are getting rewarded for hard work. â€The one thing about those guys, the play the tough minutes and a lot of time the spotlight has not been directed toward them. Right now, theyâ€™re earning that.â€ Losing the game was a bitter pill for Emery, who was fabulous in defeat and was deserving of a better fate. After a 3-2 loss in Game 1, Emery said he would be better, and he was. The Senators, who put some pressure on the Anaheim goal late, never were able to mount much of an offensive challenge in Game 2, being out-shot 31-16 in the game. â€It was a great shot,â€ Senators coach Bryan Murray said of Pahlssonâ€™s game-winner. â€œHe got Corvo turned around. He tried to do something with the stick, got spun, and he used Corvo as a screen and hit inside the post. Great shot. Great play on his part.â€ Now, the Senators have to battle history as well as the Ducks. Of the 30 home teams who have won the first two games of the Stanley Cup Final since the series became a best-of-seven affair in 1939, 29 have gone on to capture the Cup. The Sens will now call upon the ghosts of the 1971 Montreal Canadiens, who came back from the 0-2 deficit to win in seven games. Goalie J.S. Giguere was his indomitable self for the Ducks, getting to every shot that came his way. He has allowed just two goals in two games of the Final, while Emery has surrendered four goals in two games. Giguere was at his best during a multiple-save flurry during a 5-on-3 advantage for Ottawa. â€I just wanted to make sure that I would approach it with a lot of energy,â€ Giguere said. â€œI thought I was able to do the first save and guys were on the rebound right away. So, we got pretty fortunate that we were able to get out of that one with no goals.â€ Pahlsson is making quite a name for himself in this Final series. Known as a defensive whiz, his line, along with Niedermayer and Game 1 hero Moen, has made the Sensâ€™ top line of Alfredsson, Heatley and Jason Spezza disappear. â€Well, you know, we obviously want to focus on that top line and our checking line has done a great job of being physical against them,â€ Anaheim defenseman Chris Pronger said. â€œMaking them work inside on the puck and making them play defense. It's the best way to counteract offensive players.â€ â€Weâ€™re definitely counting on a couple of guys to be big-time players for us,â€ Murray said of his top scorers. â€œAnd they played much better tonight. But they didnâ€™t create much in the way of offense. Iâ€™m hoping when we get home, we can do a little juggling and it will come. â€But yeah, Iâ€™m concerned,â€ Murray continued. â€œThey have to help us win games on the road, as well as at home.â€ â€We've been scoring to this point and we're expected to score goals,â€ Spezza said. â€œIt's not a lack of effort. We're trying. We're getting pucks. We did a little better job of getting pucks on net and deep today. We didn't score those early goals. We know we have to be better, though.â€ The Senators now hope home cooking pays some dividends, returning to Ottawa for Game 3 Saturday night (8 p.m. ET, NBC, CBC, RDS, NHL Radio) and then again on Monday night as they try to get back into the series. â€Well, it's disappointing to not get a win down here,â€ Senators defenseman Chris Phillips said. â€œBut we can't hang our heads. There's a lot of pride in this room and we're going home now. We've got two games at home to even out the series.â€ â€We've kind of done our job,â€ Pronger said. â€œWe've won our two home games, and let's face it, you're supposed to win your home games. Now it's in their court. We're going to expect, obviously, a tougher environment in their building, and certainly their crowd will be behind them and cheering them on. So it will be a difficult atmosphere for sure.â€ Emery kept the Senators in the game in the second period as Ottawa was out-shot 14-4 in that period and 26-11 over the first 40 minutes. The second period began like it was in a lull after the physical and fast first 20 minutes, but as the clock ticked off the seconds, the Ducks got their second wind and began to press the advantage around Emery. Rob Niedermayer saw a backhand shot stopped by Emery and Todd Marchant grabbed the rebound and dominated the remainder of the shift. Emery snapped out a right pad at 11:40 to deny a testing drive by Corey Perry. Emery then made another key stop on Rob Niedermayer at the 10:00 mark. The Emery show continued with 6:54 left in the second as the Senators goalie made a huge save on Perry and the ensuing stuffer from Rob Niedermayer. With defenseman Tom Preissing off for tripping at 18:04, the Ducks had the man advantage and Emery made a nice save and clear on a point shot from Chris Pronger. The hits just kept coming in the scoreless first period almost as if Game 1 never ended. So, too, did the parade to the penalty box that made both coaches unhappy in Game 1. Shots in the first were 12-7 for the Ducks as both goalies made several key saves, especially on power plays, to keep the period scoreless. Ottawaâ€™s Mike Comrie was boxed for boarding at 2:17 and the Senators were able to kill off the penalty without too much difficulty. Anaheimâ€™s Drew Miller was called for interference at 5:40, another man-advantage that didnâ€™t prove especially troublesome. Anton Volchenkov threw a thundering hit on Corey Perry at 8:05, but was called for boarding, opening the door for some testing shots by the Ducks. First, Ryan Getzlaf was denied off a slick feed from Teemu Selanne. Moments later, Getzlaf was stropped again by Emery who clamped his glove on the rebound. Emery then got his right shoulder on a point drive shot from Pronger and then threw out his right pad to deny Selanne late in the power play. The Ducks dodged a huge bullet when Shawn Thornton was called for charging at 12:31 and was followed to the box by Pronger for slashing at 13:24, giving the Senators a 5-on-3 edge for 1:08. In that span, the Senators threw everything at Giguere, who responded with some tremendous save, including multiple stops on Alfredsson and Mike Comrie. The crowd roared as Pronger returned to the ice to kill off the remainder of the penalty time. â€We have to stop taking penalties like that, especially going down five-on-three,â€ Giguere said. â€œWe canâ€™t afford to do that every game. Itâ€™s going to end up costing us some goals eventually.â€ Anaheim finished off the remainder of the first on the power play after Mike Fisher was called for roughing Corey Perry at 18:06, a power play that carried over to the second period. Spurs Roll Past Jazz, into NBA Finals Pahlsson Goal Gives Ducks 2-0 Stanley Cup Lead Former Salem Resident Mike Ketler Selected for Linfield Award Warrior Women and Men Add More Basketball Recruits Six Oregon State Softball Players Earn Academic Honors Leave a comment on this story. Copyright &copy; 2006 Salem-News.com news tips & press releases
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/mca/grizzlies/article/0,1426,MCA_475_5563334,00.html&cid=1116821789&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Memphis Commercial Appeal - Memphis' Source for News and Information: Grizzlies Subscribe to the paper Iavaroni has been groomed for top for several years It's not listed on his resume, but one of Marc Iavaroni's duties as the Phoenix Suns' top assistant coach was keeping head coach Mike D'Antoni from being ejected by the referees during games. Iavaroni will be named the Grizzlies head coach today. Associated Press file photo Iavaroni played with such legends as Julius Erving when he was with the Philadelphia 76ers. Iavaroni's work ethic and enthusiasm are unquestioned. By Marlon W. Morgan ORLANDO -- Because Marc Iavaroni has worked under such coaches as Pat Riley, Mike Fratello and most recently as the lead assistant coach to Mike D'Antoni with the Phoenix Suns, D'Antoni isn't quite sure what to expect when Iavaroni calls his own plays for the first time during the 2007-08 season. Iavaroni is expected to be announced as the Grizzlies new coach at a 2 p.m. news conference today. ''He's been in all kinds of different systems,'' D'Antoni said. ''He'll have to have his own players, but he'll have his own stamp on it. It'll be interesting to see.'' One thing D'Antoni is certain about, Iavaroni, 50, is more than ready for his first head coaching gig. Iavaroni, who has had other interviews in recent years, was one of the hottest assistant coaches on the market this season, with his name mentioned with several other coaching vacancies. ''I'm really, really elated for him,'' D'Antoni said. ''I think it's great. He's ready. He'll be a great coach. It's a good situation and I hope he does well. He's ready to go. He's been ready to go for a couple of years. The opportunity finally presented itself. Rightly so, he jumped all over it.'' Iavaroni is the candidate Grizzlies president of basketball operations Jerry West had targeted since Fratello was fired in late December. Although West would not confirm Iavaroni's hiring, he did say the Suns assistant would be a great addition to the Grizzlies. ''I just think he's a great, great candidate,'' West said. ''As a matter of fact, I thought he was the best one out there. That's my personal opinion and it's only my opinion. I've always been a fan. I think he's someone, if we're fortunate enough to get him, it'll be a good thing for us.'' Former NBA player and Denver Nuggets general manager Kiki Vandeweghe used to work with Iavaroni at Hall of Fame coach Pete Newell's big man's camp. They also played against each other during Iavaroni's seven years in the NBA. He, too, believes Iavaroni will be a good fit in Memphis. ''He's a great competitor,'' Vandeweghe said. ''I would think he would do a great job. Marc is a very smart basketball guy and has a lot of enthusiasm. He'll work very hard.'' D'Antoni said Iavaroni's strengths include his work ethic, attention to detail and his teaching abilities. He went on to say that Iavaroni's abilities, combined with the Grizzlies' young talent, which includes Pau Gasol, Rudy Gay, Hakim Warrick, Kyle Lowry, Alexander Johnson, Tarence Kinsey, and the fourth pick, in next month's draft, should be a nice mix. D'Antoni quickly pointed out the Suns were one of the youngest teams in the league three years ago. Iavaroni was instrumental in helping develop that talent, among them being All-Star Amare Stoudemire, into one of the top teams in the NBA. ''You have to have talent in this league to be successful, and they have the makings of a good team. Marc will help that alone. There'll always be some growing pains, but he'll do a terrific job. ... It takes time like anything else, but he'll do great with it.'' Iavaroni's hiring leaves the Grizzlies with one other vacancy to fill, replacing current president of basketball operations Jerry West, whose last day is June 30. Vandeweghe has interviewed with Grizzlies majority owner Michael Heisley. He said he has not had any further conversations, but remains interested in the job. ''As far as I know, they're still going through some diligence,'' Vandeweghe said. Another person believed to be a candidate is Suns vice president of basketball operation David Griffin, who works under D'Antoni, also Phoenix's executive vice president of basketball operations and general manager. ''He would be another good candidate,'' D'Antoni said of Griffin. ''He's another guy that's very smart basketball-wise. He's been great.'' When asked why the Grizzlies opted to hire a coach before a general manager, West replied, ''We've got a president of basketball operations. Things will be taken care of. There's a lot of things you guys don't know that go on, and you don't need to know until they're announced.'' -- Marlon W. Morgan Browse or search for print ads Find local sales and online deals! View special sections published by The Commercial Appeal Place your ad securely online 24 hours a day! Legal Notices, Property Values, Threat Advisory, Sex Offenders Search Copyright 2007 - commercialappeal.com is an Other E.W. Scripps sites:
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.metronews.ca/storyCP.aspx%3Fpg%3D./m053093A.xml&cid=1116778987&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Lowe tosses seven scoreless innings as Dodgers blank Nationals 5-0 WASHINGTON (AP) - Derek Lowe did a little bit of everything for the Dodgers. Lowe pitched seven scoreless innings, reached base three times and scored a run to help Los Angeles shut out the Washington Nationals for the second straight game, 5-0 on Wednesday night. Lowe (5-5) gave up three hits, struck out five and walked two while allowing only one batter past first base. He combined with relievers Jim Beimel and Rudy Seanez on a four-hitter. "The final line score looked good, but it was a struggle," Lowe said. "The outs weren't coming easy. Early in the game, the stuff wasn't there, so you kind of have to grind it out." Lowe said it took some time to find his stuff, but that he felt more comfortable after the first few innings. He retired nine if a row at one point from the third through the sixth innings. "As the game went on, it seemed like I got a little bit better," Lowe said. "Today was just a day where I was fortunate to make one good pitch per at-bat." Washington manager Manny Acta didn't seem to think Lowe had very much trouble. "He's pretty tough," Acta said. "He's got to be off his game for you to do any damage and he wasn't." Lowe also helped at the plate. He entered the game with a .105 batting average but singled once, walked twice and scored a run, reaching base in all three plate appearances. The Dodgers haven't given Lowe much support at times this season, scoring three runs or less in five of his first 11 starts. But two of Lowe's at-bats led to runs. "I tell you what, Derek was good at the plate, too," Los Angeles manager Grady Little said. "He had a couple of big walks, a base hit that contributed to some of the run scoring. It was good to see him come away from there with a win. Maybe that will get him off onto a roll." Los Angeles opened the three-game series Tuesday with a 10-0 victory and got help from starting pitcher Brad Penny at the plate in that contest. He went 2-for-2, and the Dodger starters are 3-for-3 with two walks and a sacrifice in the first two games. Lowe took care of the first seven innings, and Beimel worked the eighth and Seanez pitched the ninth. Nationals starter Mike Bacsik (1-1) allowed six hits and four runs - two earned - in six innings. The Dodgers took a 1-0 lead in the fifth. Luis Gonzalez led off with a double and moved up when Russell Martin of Chelsea, Que., grounded out. Andre Ethier lined an RBI double and after Lowe walked, Rafael Furcal singled home a run. Martin hit a two-run homer in the sixth for a 4-0 lead. The Dodgers got a break when Nationals shortstop Cristian Guzman misplayed Jeff Kent's one-out grounder, and Martin's two-out homer gave Los Angeles a pair of unearned runs. "I think pitching has been holding us together this year," Martin said. "(But) hitting's going to come along. We've got some guys that hit for a lot of years, and we've got some young guys who can do it, too." Lowe got a one-out walk in the fifth against reliever Ray King and later scored on Nomar Garciaparra's infield single for a 5-0 lead. The Nationals' recent offensive problems continued as they didn't even threaten. They last scored a run in the eighth inning Sunday in a loss in St. Louis. This was the first time the Nationals have been shut out in consecutive games since May 16-17, 2006, against the Chicago Cubs. Notes: Furcal has a 15-game hitting streak, tying his career best. ... Los Angeles improved to a season-best 10 games over .500. ... The Nationals are just 7-18 against teams outside the NL East. They are 14-14 against the NL East. Â© The Canadian Press, 2007 Letters to the Editor
