tate Assembly has voted for the bill, and the Senate is expected to follow suit. Governor Spitzer could sign the measure by tomorrow, when the state's old anti-scalping law expires. Under the proposed rules, the state would stop capping prices for tickets sold on the secondary market. Scalpers would still be banned from selling tickets within 1,500 feet of large arenas like Madison Square Garden and Yankee Stadium. Smaller venues would get a similar 500-foot buffer zone. Brokers who sell large numbers of tickets would still need to get a license. But for the first time, it would be entirely legal for average fans to scalp their seats on the Internet. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. here for recent web links from The Channel 3 News. News Scripts from the past week Click here for the latest medical information from Live Weather Camera from WCAX-TV More local stories from All content &copy; Copyright 2001 - 2007 WorldNow and WCAX. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-3&fd=R&url=http://www.telegram.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070531/NEWS/705310678/1009/SPORTS&cid=1116832398&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Worcester Telegram & Gazette News _recent_courtrecords.inc and only courtrecords_recent_courtrecords.inc exists. --> Thursday, May 31, 2007 Dice KO’d in Sox defeat Four-run sixth costs Matsuzaka By Phil O’Neill TELEGRAM &#38; GAZETTE STAFF Cleveland’s Grady Sizemore is congratulated by teammate Ryan Garko after his two-run homer off Boston starter Daisuke Matsuzaka during the sixth inning. ( The Indians shelled Daisuke Matsuzaka and ended Boston’s season-high five-game winning streak with an 8-4 decision last night, but the Red Sox still finished May with a sparkling 20-8 record and, needless to say, maintained their huge lead in the AL East. Cleveland clipped Dice-K for two runs in the fifth and chased him with a four-run sixth highlighted by Grady Sizemore’s two-run home run into the visitors’ bullpen that gave the Indians a 6-2 lead. Matsuzaka (7-3, 4.83) gave up six runs on 12 hits in 5-2/3 innings in absorbing his first loss since April 17. He blanked the Indians for four innings on four hits before losing his touch. The Japanese import struck out four and didn’t walk anyone, throwing 106 pitches. But the 12 hits were a season high for any Sox pitcher. “I don’t think he located his fastball the way he has and the way you need to,” manager Terry Francona said. “He made a great pitch to get out of (fifth), but this lineup can hurt you. Even when he got outs, I thought he was misfiring.” Asked about his fastball command, Matsuzaka — speaking through an interpreter — said it wasn’t only his fastball, but all his pitches that gave him trouble. He said the stomach illness that forced him out of his last start after five innings in Texas (10-6 victory) wasn’t a factor. “I felt better right away, so it didn’t have any effect,” he said, smiling while saying he didn’t know what caused it. “I knew they (Indians) had a good-hitting lineup, and I tried my best to avoid extra-base hits. I tried to make adjustments in the game, but wasn’t able to. It’s a challenge. I don’t want to be a burden to my teammates. I hope to achieve a level of consistency.” Cleveland starter Paul Byrd (6-1, 3.57) earned the win, allowing two runs (one earned) on nine hits over six-plus innings. Byrd struck out only one batter, but threw 25 first-pitch strikes to 27 batters. Sixty-one of his 77 pitches were strikes. Byrd extended his streak of consecutive innings without walks to 43. “He threw a ton of strikes, it was about 80 percent at one time,” Francona said of Byrd. “We knew he wouldn’t walk anyone. You have to hit him to beat him. He is not going to give you anything.” Former Red Sox catcher Kelly Shoppach had a career-high four hits, including a solo home run, against his old teammates as Cleveland rattled 18 hits, tying Atlanta’s season high against Boston May 19. Travis Hafner had three hits, while he and Sizemore had two RBIs apiece. Mike Lowell, Dustin Pedroia and Jason Varitek had two hits each for Boston. The Sox threatened mightily in the seventh, loading the bases with none out on singles by Varitek, Alex Cora and Pedroia against Byrd, but the Cleveland bullpen came on to snuff out the threat. Right-hander Tom Mastny retired Coco Crisp when third baseman Casey Blake caught his foul pop at the edge of the visitors’ dugout. Mastny then struck out the sizzling Kevin Youkilis. Left-hander Aaron Fultz came on to retire David Ortiz on a soft liner to third after Big Papi brought the crowd of 37,091 to its feet with a blast down the right-field line that would have been a game-tying grand slam had it stayed fair. Cleveland added a pair of runs off reliever J.C. Romero in the eighth to push its lead to 8-2. Shoppach greeted Romero with a first-pitch homer off the Sports Authority sign in left, and Travis Hafner doubled home another run. Lowell belted a two-run homer off Roberto Hernandez in the eighth to cut Boston’s deficit to 8-4. The round-tripper was Lowell’s team-leading 10th of the season. Trot Nixon’s ground-rule double started the four-run sixth. David Dellucci followed with a double and Josh Barfield and Shoppach singles before Sizemore unloaded his ninth homer of the season, prompting Francona to bring on Kyle Snyder. Boston took the lead with an unearned run in the second inning. J.D. Drew reached on second baseman Barfield’s fielding error, scooted to third on Lowell’s wall double, and scored on a groundout to first by Varitek. After almost taking out the cameraman atop the left-field grandstand with a loud foul, Manny Ramirez doubled to right and took third on a wild pitch by Byrd in the fourth. He scored on Drew’s grounder to short, making it, 2-0, Boston. The Indians finally broke through against Matsuzaka in the fifth, scoring twice to tie the game at 2-2. Doubles by Sizemore and Hafner following a single by Shoppach were the key hits. Dice-K whiffed Ryan Garko on a 3-2 slider to get out of the inning. “We wanted to win that game, but we’ll take our nap (today’s off-day) and lace ‘em back up (tomorrow),” Francona said of the upcoming Yankee series. Add your comments to this article Add your comments to this article (required, but will not appear on the page) - Manufacturer has an immediate position ... TOWN PLANNER, TOWN OF WARREN The town of Warren (est. 5,000 population) ... Exp’d bindery operator needed for Westboro printing Co. FT ... COUNSELOR (FT) Certified - to provide Case Management ... for busy HVAC Co. Min. 2yr field exp. Comp. pay ... Light warehouse work, CDL license required. Clean RMV. $40, ... Busy office seeks organized, detail-oriented, self- ... CDL Class A. Small local trucking company looking for ... TRUCK OPERATORS HYDRO EXCAVATOR Class A & B CDL, air and tanker ... (M / F) and REPAIR TECHS - Must be able to install ... More great jobs at Worcester Telegram & Gazette Corp. Order the Telegram