http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19i-0&fd=R&url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp%3Fymd%3D20070530%26content_id%3D1995391%26vkey%3Dnews_mlb%26fext%3D.jsp%26c_id%3Dmlb&cid=1116806396&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News MLB.TV: Live and On-Demand MLB.TV Mosaic Help Blog Player News and Notes Home Run Beat the Streak Staples Easy Fantasy Report Fantasy News and Notes Text Messaging – Alerts & More Manage Services – Mobile Dashboard MLB 2007 Mobile Game DHL Delivery of the Day 05/30/2007 9:39 PM ET Notes: Players hold meeting Piniella also sits down behind closed doors with Cubs' brass By Carrie Muskat / MLB.com "We want to win bad in here. Sometimes you have to step back. Sometimes you can try too hard," Cubs first baseman Derrek Lee said Wednesday. (Jeff Lewis/AP) Yanks snap slide with big win over Jays Tribe pound Dice-K in finale Weaver shaky but Angels rally D-backs sweep behind Johnson Zito dominant as Giants blank Mets A-Rod defends controversial shout Lowe, Dodgers blank Nationals Young brilliant; Greene powers Padres Shop for official Cubs gear Watch the Cubs on MLB.TV Come out to Wrigley Field in 2007 CHICAGO -- The Cubs, unexpectedly under .500 at this point in the season, held a 30-minute players only meeting before Wednesday's game, endorsed by manager Lou Piniella. "I think it's good," Piniella said Wednesday. "I talked to Derrek Lee about it last night after the ballgame. He talked to me about it, and I said I thought it would be a pretty good idea." "It's obvious," Lee said Wednesday. "We're not playing well. [Tuesday] night wasn't a good game at all. We have to find a way to make it better." On Tuesday, the Cubs lost, 9-4, to the Florida Marlins in a game Piniella said "might be our worst game of the year." Sloppy baserunning, untimely walks by relievers, and a lack of clutch hits all contributed to the loss, the seventh in the last nine games for the Cubs. "I don't think we're playing the way we should," third baseman Aramis Ramirez said. "What's happened this season nobody expected because of the lineup we have, the pitching we have, the money they spent and we're below .500. That's unacceptable. Hopefully we can turn things around today." "We want to win bad in here," Lee said. "Sometimes you have to step back. Sometimes you can try too hard." After Tuesday's game, catcher Michael Barrett, who was picked off at second base for the third out of an inning, said he needed to play smarter baseball. Unfortunately for the Cubs, every baserunning blunder is magnified when the team loses. "You're going to make mistakes," Lee said. "It's as simple as that. When you're not scoring runs, you have to bear down a little more." "Obviously, if the team was playing really, really well, there wouldn't be a meeting," Piniella said. "You don't have meetings if you're on an eight-game winning streak. Sometimes, it's good for the players to talk about things without the manager or coaches." The players weren't the only ones who met behind closed doors. Piniella had a nearly two-hour session with team president John McDonough, Crane Kenney, who is on the board of directors, general manager Jim Hendry and assistant general manager Randy Bush. Piniella called it a "constructive" meeting. "Everybody's on the same page," Piniella said. "Everybody wants to straighten things up and win baseball games. It's good to see. It has been a little frustrating. Everybody's on the same page and we'll just go forward." The Cubs entered Wednesday's game 22-28 and six games behind the Milwaukee Brewers in the Central Division. What's been troubling is that the team is 2-12 in one-run games, and the bullpen is 4-13. However, the team is third in the National League with a .267 average, seventh in ERA, and third in fielding. Statistically, they shouldn't be under .500. "We've lost a lot of tough games late in the game," Piniella said. "You start winning those games, you get more confident that you can win them. You've got to tack on runs. Those are important. Then, when you have leads, obviously you want to hold onto them. It's been a combination. "These kids are all trying. It's been frustrating, frustrating for everybody. A lot of times we've shot ourselves in the foot running the bases. Everybody needs to relax and do what they can do and not try to overdo." Roster moves were not discussed at the management meeting. "I've got the right mix out there," Piniella said. "It's just a question of getting the job done. I haven't asked for any more pitching, one way or another. I've got five starters and bullpen kids and some are experienced, and some are young. I'm fine with it all. I think our pitching basically has done a very representative job. We've let some games get away, but what are you going to do?" Cliff Floyd batted fourth on Wednesday for the first time. He was inserted between right-handed hitters Lee and Ramirez. "We talked about doing this a while back," Piniella said. "We'll try it and see what it looks like." "I think it's a good idea," Ramirez said. Floyd, one of the veterans on the team, said he's one of the players who needs to relax to turn things around. With one out in the ninth inning, the Cubs down 9-4, and the bases loaded Tuesday, he struck out. "We have a good team," Floyd said. "We have to believe in ourselves when we go out on the field. Like [Tuesday] night, that situation, I swung as hard as I could every time. I haven't done that in the last two weeks. I'm trying to do too much. Even if I hit a grand slam, we're still down by one. You beat yourself up about the whole at-bat. Then our star [Lee] does the same thing. That's our superstar right here. You get out of your element. For what?" It's a matter of being more patient, relaxing, and getting the job done, Floyd said. "We have to go out there and believe we can win from the first at-bat or first pitch of the game, and see how that works," he said. "If you put pressure on yourself, nothing will come out of it." Moving Floyd into the No. 4 spot could be the first step. Piniella has longed for a set lineup. "I've tried my [best] to play everybody and give everybody opportunities," he said. "It's getting to the point where we're going to have to get set. I can't do it at every position. We have to get to a point where we can get as set as we can possibly be. Just play the people who are getting the job done the best. "I've tried to be as fair and play everybody," Piniella said. "I've gotten to the point where the guys who are doing the best job are the ones who will get the most playing time. That's all I can do. I can't do any more." Because the bench is so important in the NL, Piniella has tried to give everyone playing time. The positions that are set are left field with Alfonso Soriano, first base with Lee, and third base with Ramirez. "We'll try to get as set as we can," Piniella said. "I might have to play different people at one or two positions. I don't know what else we can do. We've tried just about everything." Jason Marquis took the loss in Tuesday's game, his first since his second start of the season. He had won five straight decisions. "I just didn't make pitches when I needed to," Marquis said. "I've got to bear down when the situation gets tough like that." Marquis heard Barrett's comments and knew the catcher had shouldered the blame for the loss. "Mistakes like that are going to happen," Marquis said. "That's not the only reason we didn't win the game -- there were a lot of other reasons. Michael's a no-excuse guy. I don't think that was the turning point. "Everybody wants to live up to the expectations, especially on an individual basis. We have a lot of talent in this clubhouse and we're just not dealing right now. Everybody's trying to take it on themselves and trying to carry the team. It's tough to do that and do it by yourself. We just have to get things clicking on all cylinders." Barrett was not in the lineup Wednesday. "I'm just giving him a day off," Piniella said. Thursday also is an off-day. ... Wade Miller flew to Philadelphia to have his shoulder examined. He has made three Minor League rehab starts. The right-hander underwent arthroscopic surgery on his shoulder in September 2005. ... University of Illinois coach Ron Zook will sing during the seventh inning stretch on Saturday. The singers for Friday and Sunday are to be determined, although Ron Santo will sing one of those days. John Webb gave up four runs on seven hits over five innings in Iowa's 6-2 loss to Portland. Geovany Soto had two hits to extend his hitting streak to 11 games. ... Kevin Hart gave up two runs on seven hits over four innings in Tennessee's 5-4 loss to West Tenn. ... Daytona had Tuesday off. ... Robert Hernandez gave up two runs on six hits over five innings in Peoria's 9-3 loss to Cedar Rapids. Blake Lalli hit his first professional home run to lead off the ninth. He has hit in three straight starts. After an off-day Thursday, Carlos Zambrano will open the Cubs' three-game series against the Atlanta Braves on Friday. First pitch is scheduled for 1:20 p.m. CT, and the game will be broadcast on Comcast Sports Net. Zambrano is coming off a win over the Dodgers in which he gave up two runs on eight hits over 7 2/3 innings. is a reporter for MLB.com. This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs. Register | Log In Help | Contact Us &copy; 2001-2007 MLB Advanced Media, L.P. All rights reserved. The following are trademarks or service marks of Major League Baseball entities and may be used only with permission of Major League Baseball Properties, Inc. or the relevant Major League Baseball entity: Major League, Major League Baseball, MLB, the silhouetted batter logo, World Series, National League, American League, Division Series, League Championship Series, All-Star Game, and the names, nicknames, logos, uniform designs, color combinations, and 