http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/story/75076.html&cid=1116777936&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Way too much Guerrero | TheNewsTribune.com | Tacoma, WA Saves you time. Saves you money. Makes you smarter. The News Tribune, Tacoma, WA - Thursday, May 31st, 2007 9:14 AM BLOG: The Prep Blog Wall Street Journal Sunday Letters to the editor BLOG: Inside the Editorial Page Nation & World Photos Bars & night life BLOG: Bring the Noise With the Strykers in Iraq Inside the Editorial Page Online in the South Sound Riding Around the Sound Open House: Real estate Today's full text obituaries Place an In Memoriam Way too much Guerrero Slugger torches Hernandez, M&#8217;s as Angels take two of three LARRY LARUE; The News Tribune Published: May 31st, 2007 01:00 AM Vlad Guerrero points skyward after his three-run homer in the fifth inning. Guerrero was 3-for-5 and scored twice to lead an offense that banged out 11 hits as the Angels won the series, 2-1. CHRIS PIZZELLO/THE ASSOCIATED PRESS Seattle starting pitcher Felix Hernandez didn&#8217;t have his best stuff Wednesday, allowing seven runs in six innings of a loss to L.A. ANAHEIM, Calif. &#8211; Both teams considered this something of a statement series, the chance to tell the other something it didn&#8217;t want to hear. So when the Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim beat the Seattle Mariners on Wednesday, 8-6 &#8211; taking two games in this three game series &#8211; the message came across loud and clear. We have Vlad Guerrero and you don&#8217;t. Considering Guerrero began the night batting .542 with three home runs and eight RBI against Seattle this season, one might have suspected the Mariners already knew that. Then the Angels turned their right fielder loose on Felix Hernandez, and beat the Seattle ace on a night when the Mariners scored six runs. What happened? Guerrero happened. The 2004 American League Most Valuable Player singled, doubled and hit a game-breaking three-run home run against Hernandez, who saw his earned run average leap from 2.87 to 4.10. Far worse, from the Mariners&#8217; standpoint, the Angels&#8217; victory represented a two-game swing in the standings. Had they won, the Mariners would have flown home 31/2 games out of first place. Instead, they&#8217;re 51/2 back today. &#8220;We had a good trip, we went 6-4, but we had the chance to make it a great trip tonight and couldn&#8217;t,&#8221; manager Mike Hargrove said. &#8220;The way you beat this team is to get Reggie Willits and Orlando Cabrera out &#8211; the two guys hitting in front of Guerrero. &#8220;The last two nights, we couldn&#8217;t do that.&#8221; &#8220;Tonight was a battle, the hardest battle I&#8217;ve had to get through this year,&#8221; Hernandez said. What did Felix think of Guerrero? &#8220;He&#8217;s the best hitter in the game, the best I&#8217;ve ever faced,&#8221; he said. All night, it was a game of attack and counterattack, and solid young starters Hernandez and Jered Weaver were almost helpless to stop either offense. The Mariners got a run in the first inning, when Jose Guillen&#8217;s two-out single scored Raul Iba&#241;ez. The Angels countered with four runs in their half of the first, three coming on a Gary Matthews Jr. home run. And so it went, most of the evening. &#8220;I made a couple of mistakes in the first, a couple of bad pitches, and one of them was a three-run home run,&#8221; Hernandez said. &#8220;After that, I tried to hold it there, and our guys came back.&#8221; The Mariners pecked away but missed key opportunities. They scored twice in the fourth inning to make it 4-3 &#8211; but left the bases loaded when neither Jose Vidro nor Iba&#241;ez could push runs across. In the fifth, Seattle got a double from Ben Broussard, a two-out RBI double from Adrian Beltre and an RBI single from Yuniesky Betancourt, who was then caught stealing. That produced a 5-4 Seattle lead, and Hernandez &#8211; who hadn&#8217;t allowed a run since the first &#8211; appeared to have settled in on the mound. &#8220;I thought he rebounded real well after the first,&#8221; Hargrove said. &#8220;He put up zeros in the second, third and fourth innings.&#8221; Before Hernandez got an out in the fifth inning, that lead was gone. Willits walked, Cabrera singled and there he was, the man the Seattle pitching staff cannot seem to get out when it matters. Hernandez got ahead of Guerrero, who foul tipped what would have been strike three in and out of catcher Kenji Johjima&#8217;s glove. Given another pitch, Guerrero got a fastball up &#8211; and drilled it into the right field pavilion. &#8220;It was supposed to be in and it was over the plate,&#8221; Hernandez said. &#8220;He hit it way back.&#8221; Seattle tried to recover, and Iba&#241;ez doubled home a run in the sixth to make it 7-6, but after that the Angels&#8217; bullpen shut the Mariners down without a hit. One last chance arose in the ninth inning against closer Francisco Rodriguez, who walked Vidro to open the inning. Rodriguez then struck out Iba&#241;ez, struck out Guillen on a pitch in the dirt and struck out Broussard on another low pitch. &#8220;I can&#8217;t tell you how tough he is out there,&#8221; Vidro said of Rodriguez. &#8220;He can throw you a pitch right down the middle, then throw what looks like the same pitch &#8211; and it just breaks straight down. &#8220;I went up there taking pitches because we needed a baserunner to have a chance, and even taking those pitches was hard. He&#8217;s awfully tough.&#8221; Among the Mariners&#8217; 10 hits was a fourth-inning single by Ichiro Suzuki, extending his hitting streak to a career-best 23 consecutive games &#8211; one short of Joey Cora&#8217;s team record. He would have liked it to come in the second inning, when the Mariners opened up with back-to-back singles, then watched as Betancourt, Jose Lopez and Ichiro failed to move the runners up, let alone score them. Up next for the Mariners Today through Sunday at Safeco Field, Seattle DateFirst pitchRangers pitcherMariners pitcherTV Today7 p.m.Padilla (2-7, 5.77)Baek (2-2, 4.60)FSN Friday7 p.m.Millwood (2-4, 6.62)Washburn (5-4, 3.22)FSN Saturday7 p.m.Loe (1-4, 6.17)Batista (5-4, 5.72)FSN Sunday1 p.m.Tejada (4-5, 5.75)Feierabend (0-1, 5.40)FSN Scouting report: Texas comes in having lost seven of its past eight games, and anything that could go wrong for the Rangers has. The pitching staff has a 5.16 earned run average, and players like Michael Young (.248) and Hank Blalock (five home runs) are seriously underachieving. Sammy Sosa. Like him, hate him, never think of him, he comes into this series with 598 career home runs &#8211; not something one gets to see every day. Seattle leads the season series this year 3-1, but lost 11 of 19 games against the Rangers last year. To beat the Rangers, you merely have to hold them to six runs or fewer. In games when they score seven runs or more, this team is 13-2. When they score fewer than seven, they&#8217;re 6-31. Car museum might alter first phase Cue choirs! New bridge set to open July 15 Three more from Fort Lewis die Domestic violence: &#8216;Act Now&#8217; Couple killed on Highway 7 Appeals court rules against ferry workers Fife&#8217;s farming roots remembered Do donations from tribes affect politics? Send a winner out in style this Saturday MLS for the Northwest? Here come the Sonics, Oklahoma Way too much Guerrero Sharapova shoulders opening win Lleyton Hewitt advances at French Open NBA title could elevate James to stuff of legend No. 2 pick for Kobe? No thanks Fresh Wild Waves on the horizon Car museum might alter first phase New online store caters to oversize shoppers A pricier T-bone this summer? &#8216;All-cap&#8217; keeps funds from being too specific Fed appears content to leave interest rates alone, May 9 minutes suggest Qatar Airways orders 20 more Airbus A350s, but 787 still far ahead Top three Glaceau execs to buy $180 million worth of Coca-Cola