http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-3&fd=R&url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/2007/05/29/4217163-sun.html&cid=1116768880&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ CANOE -- SLAM! Sports - NHL - Northern exposure Tue, May 29, 2007 QUOTE OF THE DAY Bettman eyes Winnipeg or Quebec City over Southern Ontario Commissioner Gary Bettman was intrigued with idea of the NHL returning to Winnipeg in the future. (AP File/Paul Sakuma) ANAHEIM -- Winnipeg over Waterloo? That certainly appeared to be the inference delivered yesterday by NHL commissioner Gary Bettman, who seemed to suggest that the possibility of an NHL franchise returning to Manitoba or Quebec City is more realistic than the addition of another team to the southern Ontario market. In fact, the NHL commissioner seemed to sour on the notion of another team landing in the Toronto area. "It's not something I've given any thought to," Bettman said. "... I frankly think -- and I live in the New York/New Jersey metropolitan area -- that it's tough for all the clubs to get media attention, particularly when they're having tough years on the ice. "There's some real downside to having multiple teams in one market." In other words, the commissioner's message seems to be: If Blackberry magnate Jim Balsillie wants to move the Nashville Predators, the NHL would rather they go to Winnipeg than Waterloo, the home of the Research In Motion CEO. Balsillie's recent purchase of the Predators must still be rubber-stamped by three-quarters of the owners. A vote could come next month. Either way, Bettman warned that all the talk regarding a potential franchise relocation of the Preds is premature. "I met with Mr. Balsillie last week and I specifically asked him whether or not he had specific plans or intentions with respect to moving this franchise and he told me that he did not," Bettman said. "So I think there has been entirely too much speculation in terms of what comes next." The previous time an American-based team moved to Canada was when the Atlanta Flames moved to Calgary in 1980. "With respect to a franchise returning to Canada, that's something that intrigues me," the NHL commissioner said. Bettman was asked why he thought it might work in Winnipeg the second time around "The combination of a salary cap and revenue sharing," he said. "Markets that couldn't afford to compete now can be more competitive. Instead of having teams with payrolls of $20 million US and teams with payrolls at $80 million, we now have a $16-million range within which everybody has to be. "We also have revenue sharing. Some teams can get double-digit in revenue sharing in any given year." Bettman was commissioner of the league when the Quebec Nordiques moved to Colorado in 1995-96 and when the Winnipeg Jets moved to Phoenix a year later. "We haven't studied Quebec City or Winnipeg or anywhere else in Canada, but the notion that if it could work to put a franchise back in a place where one was lost, feels good -- provided we don't wind up in a situation where we've created a prescription for another failing franchise. "So intrigued? It's obviously something I've thought about in terms of trying to make right something that one point in our history went wrong." How has the officiating been in this year's NHL playoffs? OK, but a few missed calls Disastrous, they should all be fired
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4i-0&fd=R&url=http://en.epochtimes.com/news/7-5-30/55909.html&cid=1116813826&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Epoch Times | Hambrecht, Google Exec Reportedly Forming Rival To NFL executive Tim Armstrong plan to launch a competitor to the National Football League next summer, The New York Times Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party 2007 Divine Performing Arts Organ Harvesting in China Hunger Strikes for China Good Stories From China Epoch Times Reporters Jailed in China The Real Story of Jiang Zemin Hambrecht, Google Exec Reportedly Forming Rival To NFL Lamont Reid of Hamburg grabs Michihiro Ogawa (L) of Dusseldorf during the NFL Europe game between Hamburg Sea Devils and Rhein Fire Dusseldorf at the AOL Arena on May 6, 2007 in Hamburg, Germany. (Alexander Hassenstein/Bongarts/Getty Images) CHICAGO—Well-known investment banker Bill Hambrecht and Google Inc. executive Tim Armstrong plan to launch a competitor to the National Football League next summer, The New York Times The league—to be named the United Football League—already boasts billionaire Mark Cuban, who owns the National Basketball Association&#39;s Dallas team, among its owners, the paper said. Hambrecht, Google and Cuban were not immediately available to comment. The plan is for eight teams to begin preseason games in August 2008, according to the paper. The UFL would be the latest in a series of leagues to compete with the NFL since the 1970s, including the World Football League, the United States Football League and most recently the XFL—all of which failed. An NFL spokesman declined to comment. David Carter, executive director of the USC Sports Business Institute said the effort should not be dismissed, but it will be an uphill battle to establish the new league. "The NFL is clearly so very powerful that they&#39;ve done a fantastic job of being able to fend off upstart leagues by ensuring that there are never enough open or underserviced markets available to make a start-up league successful," he said. Google V.P. of Advertising Tim Armstrong (Scott Gries/Getty Images) "On the surface, if history tells us anything, it can&#39;t possibly work," Carter added. "But—this is going to sound like Yogi Berra—history was a long time ago and now the landscape has changed. The right people properly capitalized should never be taken for granted." Success for the UFL may not mean long-term existence as a league, but a place for some of its teams as expansion members in the NFL, Carter said. Hambrecht, the founder of WR Hambrecht + Co., and Armstrong have each pledged $2 million, the paper said. The plan is to establish teams in markets where the NFL does not have one, including Los Angeles, Las Vegas and Mexico City, according to the paper. Cuban is considering taking the Las Vegas franchise. Mark Cuban, owner of the Dallas Mavericks, reportedly also owns a franchise in the new UFL. (Brian Bahr/Getty Images) Each owner will put up $30 million for an initial half-interest in a team, with the league owning the other half, the paper said. The UFL will eventually sell shares to the public so that the league, owner and fans each own a third of each team. Hambrecht told the paper he believes the initial public offering would raise, on average, another $60 million per team, giving each about $90 million in working capital. He expects any potential owners to be wealthy and able to absorb losses for up to five years, and the new league is open to a smaller television deal with a cable networks such as USA, TNT or Comcast&#39;s Versus, according to the paper. The story said the UFL could easily fall apart and pointed out billionaire hedge fund manager T. Boone Pickens recently abandoned his intention to buy a team. Pickens was not immediately available to comment. Copyright 2000 - 2007 Epoch Times International
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-4&fd=R&url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story%3Fsection%3Dsports%26id%3D5355391&cid=1116829994&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ 7Online.com: New York poised to ease ticket scalping regs - 7 On Your Side - Alerts and Recalls - Driving While Young - What's Bugging You - Behind the News - Did You See... - News from Our Schools - Personal Traffic Alerts - Live Traffic Reports Video on Your Phone Business to Business Events Links Mentioned on TV - News and Local Shows - Protect Our Children - Be Part of Your Park - News Team Bios - Jobs at ABC7 - Our Privacy Policy - Web Site Index About Digital TV and HDTV Advertise on This Site Contact the Newsroom - Email 7 On Your Side - New York poised to ease ticket scalping regs (New York - WABC, May 31, 2007) - The days of seeking out ticket-scalpers in the shadows, ducking into alleys and dodging police for that elusive Yankees-Red Sox seat are fading fast. New York is poised to become the latest state to ease or eliminate decades-old restrictions on scalping. For the first time, it would become entirely legal in the state for average fans to scalp their seats on the Internet. And, for better or worse, they could sell those tickets at whatever price the market is willing to bear. The state assembly approved the changes Tuesday. The Senate is expected to follow suit, and Governor. Eliot Spitzer could sign the measure by Friday, when the state's old anti-scalping law expires. "If you have something to sell, you should be able to sell it for what it is truly worth," said Sean Pate, spokesman for the online ticket broker StubHub Inc., which lobbied hard for the change. Some old regulations would stay in place. Scalpers would still be banned from selling tickets within 1,500 feet of large arenas, like Madison Square Garden and Yankee Stadium, and within 500 feet of smaller venues. Large-volume brokers would still need to get a license, too. It's those brokers who have Russ Haven of the New York Public Interest Research Group worried. Haven argues that lifting the price caps will only prompt greedy opportunists to snap up every available seat, and then jack up prices. "I think this is a bum deal for consumers," Haven said. "As it is, seats to popular events are often selling for 10 times their face price...It may be that there will be some portion of tickets that go for less than face value, but that's not what they're all banking on." Teacher, aide accused of raping students Police make arrest in Ronkonkoma murder Police searching for suspects in Newark more of Today's Headlines Teacher, aide accused of raping students PA to study flight delays, improve customer service Pedestrian reports being shocked walking over grate Eyewitness News Video on Demand News, Weather, Entertainment: Watch it Here! Get Eyewitness News Text Alerts School Closings, Breaking News, Sports Scores, More... Find out fast on your cell phone or PDA. Need to contact us? Find about an ABC7 news story, send us a story, or drop us a line. About DTV and HDTV WABC on your Wireless Send Your Digital Pictures Advertise on this Site Copyright &#169;2007 ABC Inc., WABC-TV New York.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-2&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/grizzlies/2007-05-31-iavaroni-coach_N.htm&cid=1116821789&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Grizzlies hire Suns assistant Iavaroni as head coach - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Buy and sell tickets to premium and sold out events Search by events or regions: Looking to sell tickets quick? Scenes from the NBA conference finals Check the NBA Index First-round views of the action Scenes from the second round Follow all the postseason action Grizzlies hire Suns assistant Iavaroni as head coach By Doug Haller, The Arizona Republic The Suns' offseason maneuvering began Wednesday with an expected transaction: Marc Iavaroni is leaving for greater opportunity. The Memphis Grizzlies have hired the popular Suns assistant as their head coach. Suns coach Mike D'Antoni, reached by phone, didn't find the news surprising. Iavaroni, a 14-year NBA veteran as a player and coach, has been a top coaching candidate for some time. He was strongly considered for past openings in Milwaukee and Portland and was considered the early front-runner in Memphis. "That's the thing," D'Antoni said. "Anyone who's an assistant aspires to be a head coach, and Marc's definitely paid his dues. ... I don't think there's any question (he's ready)." Iavaroni, who was unavailable for comment, spent the past five years with the Suns, the last three and a half as D'Antoni's lead assistant. During his time in Phoenix, he helped develop Suns center Amar&#233; Stoudemire and displayed a passion for defense, especially in the post. He also had a lead role in the team's postseason preparation, filling the locker room whiteboard with as much strategy, instruction and motivation as possible. "I don't think anybody has worked harder or prepared more for this opportunity," Suns assistant coach Phil Weber said. "Last year, Marc was talked about in some situations, but this year there was a lot of momentum behind him. I think it's a great opportunity for him." Iavaroni reportedly has agreed to a three-year deal to help revive the Grizzlies, who finished this past season with the league's worst record. Injuries were a constant headache, and as a result the team missed the playoffs for the first time in four seasons. Memphis is a team in transition. In December, ownership fired Mike Fratello and replaced him with Tony Barone Sr. In April, Jerry West announced he would vacate his post as president of basketball operations once his contract expires July 1. Memphis will pick fourth in the June 28 draft. For now, D'Antoni isn't concerned with filling Iavaroni's spot, adding that no timetable has been set to add a replacement. "We're just happy for Marc," he said. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
