http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-2&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/hewitt-finds-the-will-to-win/2007/05/31/1180205433136.html&cid=1116760279&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Hewitt finds the will to win - Sport - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. Hewitt finds the will to win Australia's Lleyton Hewitt finds another backhand winner in his stunning comeback against Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Lleyton Hewitt kept his French Open campaign alive last night with a stunning come-from-behind win over Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Down two sets to love, the Australian pulled out one of his trademark fightbacks to defeat the 2004 French champion 4-6, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4, 6-2 on centre court. The Australian is now on track to meet claycourt master Rafael Nadal in the fourth round if he can overcome Finland's Jakko Nieminen, seeded 20, who had an easy 6-1, 6-1, 6-4 win against Frenchman Mathieu Montcourt. Hewitt wore down Gaudio over three hours 28 minutes, finding his range in the third set after a slow start. His best result for the French Open was making the quarter-finals in 2001 and 2004. Last year, he made it through to the fourth round. It's been a good start to the French Open for Australians, with Samantha Stosur's liking for a challenge and cool head under pressure securing her a place in the French Open third round for the first time, uncharted territory in which she will encounter Czech No. 6 seed Nicole Vaidisova. Stosur was struggling in the third set of her second-round match against Maria Kirilenko, but came back from a rain delay to immediately convert a crucial break point and calmly complete a 6-1, 3-6, 7-5 victory over the Russian. "This tournament's always been hard for me and I'm just really, really happy to be in the third round for the first time," said Stosur, who is due to meet Vaidisova tonight (Melbourne time). "Hopefully, it won't stop here." Stosur, the No. 27 seed, went into the match having equalled her best performance at Roland Garros by making the second round, which she also achieved in 2005. But she was determined to go at least one better. "It was a very tight match and at the end, I think I got a little bit tired," the Australian said. "I knew she was kind of feeling the same thing, so it was just a matter of being out there and really moving my feet, really just enjoying the challenge. "In the end, I came up with the right shots at the right time and won." Vaidisova has played Stosur three times, all last year, and the 18-year-old world No. 10 from Prague has won every time. But the 30th-ranked Stosur has recent form on clay, having beaten then-top seed Amelie Mauresmo in the second round of the Italian Open last month. And now that she has started to enjoy playing on clay, she doesn't want to stop. "I've played Nicole a handful of times, never actually beaten her, so it will be fun to go out there and play her again," Stosur said. "Third round, I'll just go out there and enjoy it and play the way I play." The first round of these rain-hit championships was finally completed yesterday, producing an unwanted record for American men, none of whom progressed to the second round of a grand slam tournament for the first time since the Open era began in 1968. Robby Ginepri was the last of the nine to bow out, losing from two sets to one up against Argentina's Diego Hartfield. World No. 1 Roger Federer was none too pleased with proceedings, either, slamming officials for scheduling his second-round match to start and finish in murky conditions. Federer, who needs a Roland Garros title to complete the full set of majors, finished his 6-1, 6-2, 7-6 (10-8) win over French wildcard Thierry Ascione just before 9.15pm (Paris time), with Court Suzanne Lenglen almost in darkness. "When we shook hands, I told him I couldn't see him any more, it was so dark," Federer said. "The conditions were shocking. I know they want to get the matches over and done with but what I don't like is that they know I'm the favourite and they think I should win in straight sets. 'Let's get Roger's match over and done with, then he's happy, he has a day off.' But what if it doesn't turn out this way? I would be very upset. I already wasn't happy playing so late." Nor were the locals pleased, with hopes of a first French Open men's singles title since Yannick Noah nearly a quarter-of-a-century ago in tatters. French veterans Sebastien Grosjean, Arnaud Clement and Fabrice Santoro all failed to make it past the first round, to the dismay of the partisan Parisian crowds. And matters got distinctly worse when French No. 1 Richard Gasquet had a nightmare against Belgium's Kristof Vliegen, booed off centre court after losing 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, 6-1. Gael Monfils and doubles expert Michael Llodra gave the crowds something to cheer, while Mauresmo, who is short of practice having missed two months after an appendix operation, defeated American Laura Granville 6-0, 7-5. Second seed Maria Sharapova saw off the challenge of another Frenchwoman, Emilie Loit, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) in one hour 50 minutes. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! Hewitt finds the will to win Australia's Lleyton Hewitt finds another backhand winner in his stunning comeback against Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Simoni wins mountain stage, Di Luca keeps lead No way, Jose &#151; didgeridoo man had wrong Telstra New series on track, says chief 'Betrayed' mum pays out on Lion Notting Ducks take early lead over Senators in final Swifts unlikely to repeat French connection We're to blame for rule change &#151; ex-ump Russo All-rounder Ron Archer a precocious talent all round Eye for an eye &#151; $9344 plunge now in limbo California doesn't give flying Ducks too much thought Flying Phoenix demolishes weary Swifts Loren lands in Oz Fans greet movie legend wi