http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-5&fd=R&url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/05/30/ap3772503.html&cid=1116827440&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Zito Outpitches Glavine As Giants Win - Forbes.com Zito Outpitches Glavine As Giants Win 05.30.07, 9:50 PM ET Barry Zito outpitched Tom Glavine over seven sharp innings and the San Francisco Giants beat the New York Mets 3-0 Wednesday night to snap a four-game losing streak. Pedro Feliz drove in three runs and Rich Aurilia tied a career high with four hits for the Giants, who bounced back from a difficult loss in the series opener against New York. The Mets won 5-4 in 12 innings Tuesday night when Armando Benitez balked in the tying run and surrendered a game-ending homer to Carlos Delgado. Paul Lo Duca had two hits for New York, which had won four straight. Glavine went seven innings but was denied in his second attempt at career win No. 296. Lo Duca led off the seventh with a double for his 1,000th career hit but Zito retired the next three batters, striking out pinch-hitter Julio Franco to end the inning. Zito (5-5) turned in his second consecutive strong outing after struggling in back-to-back starts earlier this month. He gave up 13 runs and 12 hits in 10 innings in outings at Colorado and Oakland, then allowed one run in seven innings in a win over Houston in his last start. He struck out a season-high seven against the Mets, holding them to six hits and one walk. Jack Taschner tossed a perfect eighth and Brad Hennessey got three outs for his second save. Barry Bonds returned to the lineup for the Giants, went 1-for-3 with a walk and remains 10 shy of breaking Hank Aaron's career record of 755 homers. He was booed lustily each time he came to the plate. Bonds entered with a .329 batting average and four homers in 100 career plate appearances against Glavine, according to the Elias Sports Bureau. He hit a two-out single to center against him in the first inning to put runners on first and second. After Bengie Molina walked, Feliz grounded a two-run single into left field. Bonds bounced into a double play in the third before Molina singled to right to extend his hitting streak to 11 games. Feliz then tripled off the wall in right-center to make it 3-0. Glavine (5-3) intentionally walked Bonds in the fifth and got him to groundout to first to end the seventh on his 122nd and final pitch of the game. He allowed nine hits, walked two and struck out four. Mets reliever Guillermo Mota was activated after serving the 50th and final day of his suspension for testing positive for a performance-enhancing substance. He relieved Glavine to start the eighth and received a mixed reaction of boos and cheers from the home crowd. Notes:@ Giants SS Omar Vizquel made two slick, barehanded plays in the first four innings. ... The Mets optioned RHP Ambiorix Burgos to Triple-A New Orleans to make room for Mota on the roster. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-0&fd=R&url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/2007/05/31/2007-05-31_other_barry_has_a_blast.html&cid=1116827440&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Bonds quiet as Zito helps shut out Mets Other Barry has a blast Bonds quiet as Zito helps shut out Mets DAILY NEWS SPORTS WRITER Thursday, May 31st 2007, 4:00 AM Barry Zito, pursued by Mets as a free agent in the offseason, delivers seven scoreless innings as Giants are first team to shut out Mets in 2007. Shea fans have rude reception for Barry Bonds but later let returning Guillermo Mota off easy. Read Adam Rubin's Surfing the Mets Blog Read fan blog Subway Squawkers With Barry Bonds making his first Shea start of the season, convicted performance-enhancer Guillermo Mota joining the Mets after a 50-game suspension and Tom Glavine seeking win No. 296, new Giant Barry Zito seemed destined for undercard status last night. But after dozens of looping curveballs and changeups that "never seemed to get there," according to David Wright, Zito wasn't playing second banana to anyone. Backed by three early runs - all driven in by Pedro Feliz and all scored with two out - the lefthander threw seven scoreless innings, dooming the Mets to their first shutout loss of the season, 3-0, in front of 41,395. Glavine, who allowed three runs and nine hits in seven innings, deserved a better fate, a theme that is getting all too familiar - and frustrating - to the 41-year-old who is 5-3 with a 3.44 ERA. "I don't really feel like I've pitched a bad game all year," said Glavine, who has thrown at least six innings in 11 of his 12 starts. "If you told me I had a 12-game stretch coming like this, I'd take my chances that I'd have a better record than I do. "You hope it evens out." For that to happen, the Mets will have to be more productive than last night, when they had only six hits and went 0-for-7 with runners in scoring position. "We couldn't hit at all against Zito," said Carlos Beltran, who doubled in the first but was stranded. "Everything was working for him. They scored a few runs early and we couldn't get back. You can't sit on one pitch. If he feels like throwing five curveballs in a row, he can." Zito (5-5) allowed all six hits and walked one. He struck out seven, five of them looking at his big curve, which was generally clocked around 72 mph. The Mets, vulnerable last season to lefty starters, looked that way again last night, but their record this season against southpaw starters is still a robust 11-4. Zito owns two of the four wins against the Mets. While Bonds and Zito were both booed last night, Mota got a mixed reaction when he came in to start the eighth. There was another bullpen drama - the Giants used righty Brad Hennessey to close the game instead of ex-Met Armando Benitez, who balked twice and gave up a walk-off homer to Carlos Delgado in blowing Tuesday's game. The Giants scored twice in the first, but Glavine believed he was making effective pitches. "Chopper off the plate, a semi-line drive to center and a grounder in the hole. There's not a lot I can do," Glavine said. "It's one of the single most frustrating things you deal with as a pitcher. You keep making pitches, sooner or later things will get better." Sandwiched into that sequence, Glavine walked Bengie Molina on a 3-2 pitch. Feliz followed with a two-run single that snuck under Jose Reyes' glove. In the third, the Mets turned a 3-5-3 double play because Wright had moved near second base in a shift against Bonds that made Wright the only infielder on the left side of second. Bonds hit a grounder to Delgado, who started the DP. But the Giants scored a run on Feliz's triple. Glavine stuck around to throw 122 pitches, the same total as Zito, and a whopping number in this era of pitch counts. But he was working on an extra day's rest and will have another extra day before his next turn. While Glavine said he wouldn't have gone out for the seventh without those cushions, he also admitted that he wanted to stay in because he believed the Mets would score. "It was a beautiful night," Willie Randolph said. "There was nothing taxing about how he was going out there." Mota pumped in return to action Nothing doing against lefty who got away Reyes' dream: Steal home Some can't bear to watch Barry Sign up to receive daily newsletters Buy an Ad link Use of this website signifies your agreement to the &copy; Copyright 2007 NYDailyNews.com. All rights reserved.
