http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-4&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/golf/4849842.html&cid=1116756580&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Is Mickelson ready to challenge Woods? | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices May 31, 2007, 3:06AM Is Mickelson ready to challenge Woods? By RUSTY MILLER AP Sports Writer &copy; 2007 The Associated Press DUBLIN, Ohio &mdash; Masters champion Zach Johnson is here. So are eight of the top 10 players in the world. Yet all anyone seems to notice is the looming duel between Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson. Both were peppered with questions about a potential showdown in this week's Memorial Tournament. Woods is No. 1 on the planet by acclaim, not even close. But that doesn't stop everybody from trying to speculate about who could sneak up and steal his crown. "I've had different guys make different runs," Woods said after Wednesday's pro-am at Muirfield Village Golf Club. "It was (David) Duval and then probably Phil and Ernie (Els), Vijay (Singh), Goose (Retief Goosen) &mdash; a combination of those guys throughout the years." With Mickelson coming off a big win at The Players Championship three weeks ago, some are saying he may be primed to challenge Woods at the Memorial and then in two weeks at the U.S. Open at Oakmont. Mickelson isn't so sure. "It's flattering &mdash; to me, anyway," he joked of the comparisons between him and Woods. "Probably not to him, but it's flattering to me." It seems that every time Mickelson gets a big win &mdash; the Masters in 2004, the PGA Championship in 2005, the Masters again in 2006 &mdash; it gets Woods' attention. A year ago, for instance, Mickelson won at Augusta and was in position to take his second major in a row before hitting that hideous drive on the final hole that cost him the Open at Winged Foot. Still grieving the loss of his father, Woods wasn't a factor there, but then turned around and won the last two majors, the British Open and PGA. With Woods facing impending fatherhood and the changes that can bring, now could be the time for Mickelson to finally challenge for the top spot in the world. Woods doesn't seem to be conceding anything, though. "As long as I'm up there in the conversation, I'm doing all right," Woods said. "I keep pushing myself pretty hard, regardless. I always try and get better. You can't stay stagnant in any sport. You've always got to keep getting better because you know the guys are training harder, they're finding their game, they're in the gym, you're getting better athletes playing the game. So you've got to keep getting better." Mickelson, leading the tour in putting average, knows how difficult the task is. "It's a tough feat. I mean, we're talking about probably the best player of all time," he said. Memorial Tournament founder Jack Nicklaus was asked if anyone is capable of pressing Woods. "All I know is that Tiger is dominating what's going on. And when he plays and when he's playing well, he is really difficult to beat," Nicklaus said. "We can say that the guys today can't finish and Tiger is the only guy that can play, or we can say that the guys today are really, really good and Tiger is just way above them. We never will have an answer for that." Either way, Mickelson is not giving up. He's lost weight, is halfway through restructuring his swing and is optimistic heading into the Memorial &mdash; a tournament Woods has won three times. Mickelson has never finished in the top three. "A lot of great players have won this tournament. I have not," he said. "It's one of the tour events that I would very much like to win." The field mirrors that of a major. Nine of the top 10 money-winners are on hand, along with former Memorial winners Els, Jim Furyk, Singh, Tom Lehman and Paul Azinger. Johnson, still on a victory lap after winning the Masters in April and the AT&T Classic two weeks ago, burns to remain in such elite company. "This is one of my favorite places to be," said Johnson, who tied for second at the Memorial a year ago, two shots behind winner Carl Pettersson. "Golfwise, I absolutely love it. If you find a complaint here, it's hard." Sorenstam's back - literally this time Is Mickelson ready to challenge Woods? Woods-Mickelson is a rivalry renewed Sorenstam's back - literally this time Woods-Mickelson rivalry picks up steam again Woods-Mickelson is a rivalry renewed Golf Notebook: Masters plan is off track ON GOLF: Tiger past halfway to Nelson's 11 Woods becomes larger than life Golf Notebook: Open setups can be trials by fire ON GOLF: Look for new, improved tour On golf: Woods and Old Course a match made in heaven PRO GOLF NOTEBOOK: Furyk adds to playoff flops Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-0&fd=R&url=http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/cs-070530smith,1,4016385.column%3Fcoll%3Dcs-home-headlines&cid=1116735035&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Trade that won't happen on ChicagoSports.com ChicagoSports.com's blog of current events. Sam Smith on pro basketball Get your Bulls on View from the Fans CS.com blog: What's Goin' On Trade that won't happen The flip-flopping soap opera of Kobe Bryant will end where it began Which star would fit best with the Bulls? San Antonio advances to NBA finals Send a question to the Tribune's Cavs finally show some drive James bad fit for U.S. team Don't look now, but this stinks Blazers, Sonics big winners A Chicago spelling bee Sam Smith's NBA mailbag Boylan gets 2nd interview with Pacers Higgins may follow MJ to Charlotte Former Bull Porter dies after beating Chicago Bulls gear at the ChicagoSports.com Team Fan Shop. See the Bulls in action! Kobe Bryant is being traded to the Bulls. No, wait, Kobe Bryant is not being traded to the Bulls. being traded to the Bulls. No, he's not being traded to the Bulls. That's the big problem with this story. By the time you're reading this, Bryant could have asked to be traded or not traded from the Lakers six more times. This is what I know for sure: Kobe Bryant is not being traded this summer, not to anyone, no matter what he says. The Lakers will trade for someone. My guess is Jermaine O'Neal, but if that doesn't happen, or if it does and it doesn't work out, it's not inconceivable Bryant could be with the Bulls in 2008-09. On a personal level, I have to thank Bryant because this allows me to pay less attention to the miserable Eastern Conference finals going on in Detroit and Cleveland. That's the reason, I think, Bryant had a basketball breakdown this week. He has been watching someone named "Booby" Gibson become a hero for the Cavaliers and Utah's Deron Williams skip the five-year waiting period for induction into the Basketball Hall of Fame and Derek Fisher, his old teammate who couldn't break down a man with a cane off the dribble, and some guy on the Spurs with a name and looks like Fabio being celebrated and he's at his window screaming, " I'm home because I'm playing with Smush Parker and Kwame Brown. Aaaggghhh!!!" This is why we really love these guys and this game. To recap, Bryant's breakdown began last week when a Los Angeles Times reporter called to ask how things were going, and Bryant reiterated his position that he's unhappy with the team and wants the Lakers to make some big moves this summer. Given that Los Angeles doesn't have an NFL team and it still doesn't know what to make of baseball and Jack Nicholson doesn't go to those games anyway, the Times basically devoted a special section to the story. So then an ESPN reporter called, and now Bryant was into it. He offered a less-than-supportive vote of confidence for general manager Mitch Kupchak and said he wanted former general manager Jerry West back to run the team because, geez, Kupchak got us Smush Parker and Kwame Brown. West is retiring from the Memphis Grizzlies next month and didn't help matters by saying he always had been a Laker. Ooops. West, who handpicked Kupchak as his successor, quickly said he's not going anywhere. Then Bryant did his first crossover and said he was merely trying to help. "I would love for [West] to be a part of this," Bryant said. "But it's not something where I demand he comes here. All I can do is offer my thoughts. I love being a Laker. I want to retire a Laker. I want to fix this, or at least help any way I can. "I haven't demanded a trade, I haven't asked for a trade, I haven't said anything like that. That's not something I even want to think about." Then there was an anonymous quote in the Times on Tuesday that Bryant was responsible for forcing the trade of Shaquille O'Neal. Angered by that, Bryant went on local radio in Los Angeles to denounce the Lakers, saying the front office was a mess and it had misled him about plans to refurbish the team. Wednesday morning, still simmering, Bryant bubbled over and upped the volume on ESPN radio by saying he wanted to be traded, knocking Lindsay Lohan and Paris Hilton out of the headlines for a few hours.Reports had his agent informing the Lakers there was nothing they could do to change his mind and he had begun contacting teams, including the Bulls. A few hours later, after a conversation with Phil Jackson and undoubtedly a meditation session and some chanting, Bryant was quoted by the Los Angeles Daily News as saying: "I can only hope they do something, because I don't want to go anyplace else. I want to stay here. Phil said, `Let us try to work that out, figure things out.' That made me feel a lot better. Phil is a guy I leaned on all season for clarity and hope. When Phil and I talked, it was an emotional conversation. I want to stay here. This is my team. I love it here." Copyright & terms of service
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-0&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/31/AR2007053100038.html&cid=1116754239&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Small Ball Leads To O's Big Sweep - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Small Ball Leads To O's Big Sweep Orioles 3, Royals 0 Washington Post Staff Writer Thursday, May 31, 2007; Page E08 KANSAS CITY, Mo., May 30 -- Corey Patterson showed the Kansas City Royals that he was bunting on the first pitch, but that didn't matter. They knew anyway. "Everybody knew I was doing it, in the whole park," Patterson said. Erik Bedard and Gil Meche had allowed only zeros for seven innings, making it clear this game would not be won by mashing the ball. The extra rest of a 1 hour, 36 minute rain delay does Erik Bedard some good as he pitches eight innings for the first time this season. (Charlie Riedel - AP) Erik Bedard goes eight innings as Baltimore gets its first of the season with a 3-0 win over the Royals to complete a road sweep. Brian Burres has been 'sneaky' in his success. The Orioles' brass must break its decade-old habit of blaming a manager for losses and hold its players accountable. Box score: Orioles 3, Royals 0 | Enhancing a Legacy Save & Share Article So third baseman Esteban German was creeping, then charging down the line, but that didn't matter either. Not the way Patterson runs, and not the way he bunted in the eighth inning, a play that set up Jay Payton's game-winning RBI single and, after a two-run insurance homer by Nick Markakis in the ninth, a 3-0 victory for the Baltimore Orioles on Wednesday night. It took a while (rain delayed the start of the game 1 hour 36 minutes) and placed some undue stress on Bedard, who pitched a season-high eight innings, allowed four hits and won for the first time since April 18. "That's a long time ago," he said. After it all happened, though, the Orioles completed a sweep of the Royals and moved to one game under .500 at 26-27 -- their best record since May 11 -- having won five straight. Despite the late-game offensive heroics, Bedard was the star. He has experienced frustration adjusting to the life of an ace, having to face the league's best pitchers every start. His teammates knew of his winning drought, and they wanted to get him a win. In the end, really, he got it himself. "He sucked it up for us real good," Manager Sam Perlozzo said. "I'm sure the lack of wins is probably on his mind a little bit." Payton won the game when he sharply grounded a low slider to the left side. The pitch may have been out of the strike zone, Payton said, and he got out in front of it. But he smacked it hard enough so it skidded through the infield, just under Tony PeÃ±a Jr.'s glove. Pinch runner Freddie Bynum jogged home from third with the game's first run. "He's just a competitor," Perlozzo said. "He bears down and likes being the guy." But first, Patterson's speed allowed it to happen. He dug in against Meche in the eighth, after Ramon Hernandez walked and Bynum replaced him. Patterson took the first pitch after squaring, then nudged the second toward German. German charged almost as Meche wound up. Patterson flew out of the batter's box before the ball even landed and sprinted to first. It was a routine sacrifice bunt, but it wasn't, not how Patterson runs. German pounced on the ball and rifled it to first. Patterson beat the throw without question. Rather than the expected result, a man on second with one out, the Orioles had two men on with no out. The difference allowed Brian Roberts to lay down another bunt, this one less harrowing for Kansas City, but just as effective for the Orioles. Payton followed with his game-winner. "I love playing the game," Payton said. "That's what it's all about, trying to win." The Orioles hadn't given Bedard much, but it was enough. He pitched his best game this season, going deeper than he had before and striking out five, including his last batter. After that, he pumped his fist, a rare show of emotion. "No runs, eight innings," Bedard said. "I was happy." "I know Erik a little bit better," Perlozzo said. "I'm around him a lot. He's a lot more competitive than you think." After Bedard plowed through each inning, he had to sit in the dugout and watch Baltimore's hitters flail, which was nothing new for him. In his previous seven starts, the Orioles had scored 11 runs while he was in the game, which comes to 2.2 runs per nine innings. Bedard won none of those despite a combined 3.43 ERA. It seemed like it might happen again, as Bedard matched Meche inning for inning. He was matched up with another team's best pitcher. Late into Wednesday night, there was none better than Bedard. A-Rod, Yankees Snap 5-Game Losing Streak Bedard Throws Down Aces As Orioles Win Beckett Impressive in Return for Red Sox Guthrie's Good Work Is Rewarded Guthrie Pitches Orioles Past Royals 6-2 Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this site. Please review the governing commentaries and discussions. You are fully responsible for the content that you post. &copy; 2007 The Washington Post Company Refinance Rates As Low As 2.9% - FREE QUOTES! $300,000 Mortgage for $965&frasl;mo! Refinance & Save $1,000's! Be Prepared. Fight Identity Theft! Equifax.com. $425,000 Loan for only $1,417&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! $599,000 Loan for only $1,997&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! Cool Gadgets, Great Deals, Visit CircuitCity.com Try Email Marketing with Constant Contact dell_ran = Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000); doc