http://www.twincities.com/sports/ci_6024127&cid TwinCities.com - Walk puts finishing touch on the Twins' 6-run rally Working Q & A Walk puts finishing touch on the Twins' 6-run rally White Sox worn out in three-game sweep Article Last Updated: 05/31/2007 12:01:40 AM CDT A happy Torii Hunter, center, is mobbed by teammates after walking on four pitches with the bases loaded in the ninth inning to send the winning run home as the Twins beat the White Sox 7-6 Wednesday. (JOHN DOMAN, Pioneer Press) Torii Hunter didn't know what to do. He had just drawn a walk-off walk, something new for the normally swing-hungry hitter. He started toward first base, turned back toward home and wondered about the protocol. "I didn't know whether to cheer or go down the first-base line," Hunter said after the Twins' 7-6 victory over the Chicago White Sox on Wednesday at the Metrodome. "I saw the ump looking at me like, 'You need to come touch first base.' " Winning with a walk is the latest way the Twins' suddenly stout offense has found to start climbing the ranks in the American League Central. In a three-game sweep of the divisional rival White Sox, the Twins hit home runs and doubles, sacrifice flies and bunts. They drew walks, worked counts and twice won with comebacks. This is not the team that decided buzz cuts were the remedy for its struggles, but this is a still a team with buzz cuts. Earlier this week, Boof Bonser said he would like to grow his hair a bit longer. Now his team has won four straight series, and Bonser doubts his locks will be lengthened any time soon. During the Twins' six-game homestand, they scored 42 runs on 69 hits. Hunter knocked in his 45th run, second in the AL. Justin Morneau improved his home run total to 16 and is only three behind Alex Rodriguez's league-leading 19. "It comes with confidence," Twins manager Ron Gardenhire said. "Guys start getting confident, and that's what happens. We talk about it all the time. We talk about working the counts, but it comes obviously with a confident group." Wednesday, starter Scott Baker left his team in a 6-1 hole heading into the bottom of the third inning, but those once-overwhelming deficits no longer seem so menacing. Minnesota climbed back with single after single - only one of the team's seven hits was for extra bases (Hunter's two-run double in the third) - and the bullpen was flawless, holding Chicago hitless in six innings. "That was straight Piranha right there," said Hunter, who went 2 for 4 with three runs batted in and is batting .318 for the season. The Twins' sweep put them one game ahead of Chicago in the AL Central and boosted their home record to 15-14 and their overall mark to 27-25. For Michael Cuddyer, it seems like another year but the same story. "It seemed like at the same point last year, when we went into Milwaukee and won that series, we just took off after that," Cuddyer said. "I don't know if it was the atmosphere in Milwaukee that kind of rejuvenated us, but it seemed to have done it again this year. We're starting to play better baseball now, and hopefully we can sustain. "We have the same type of mentality that we had last year where we feel like we can win every game no matter if we're up, no matter if we're down, no matter what inning it is, we feel like we have a chance to win every game. It's a great feeling. I'm glad we finally got that feeling back because to be honest with you, we didn't have it two weeks ago." Before starting the series-winning streak in Milwaukee, the Twins had won only one of their previous nine series. Now 9-3 since being swept by Cleveland, they travel to the West Coast for six games before a normally successful time of the season begins - interleague play. After playing 12 games against divisional opponents in May, the Twins won't see an AL Central team again until June 29. Last season, they dominated the National League, going 16-2 in the midst of their turnaround. Things could be different this season. The Twins take on the Brewers and New York Mets, two of the best teams in the NL, along with perennially tough Atlanta and a young, scrappy Florida club. No matter the opponent, Gardenhire said his team would continue to focus on winning each series. "Right now, we have a confident offensive team that can make some things happen," he said, "slap the ball around, take good at-bats and come up with some big hits, and we're doing those things. You just have to continue that process." Kelsie Smith can be reached at ksmith@pioneerpress.com. The Pioneer Press is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Please note: It may take several minutes before your comment appears. (From the last 24 hours) Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking State alleges conspiracy in Milwaukee bribery scandal; defense says... Minnesota gas prices dip slightly No Powerball winner, jackpot goes to $25 million Minnesota authorities hunt for missing sex offender (From the last 24 hours) Wisconsin priest tells church organist she can't sell sex toys More than a ton of pot seized in Dakota County bust Typo made her rich - for 2 months A church built on faith, beer St. Paul teacher accused of sexual contact with student 3M Settles Battery Patent Suit Against Matsushita Minnesota authorities hunt for missing sex offender Campfire restrictions eased in Superior National Forest Minnesota gas prices dip slightly State alleges conspiracy in Milwaukee bribery scandal; defense says it was street slang No Powerball winner, jackpot goes to $25 million Truck's cargo: hard candy and $3 million in pot Walk puts finishing touch on the Twins' 6-run rally Mauer: 'I'm pretty frustrated' Pahlsson's goal is all Ducks need 'TNT' tour takes off outstate Feeling unloved, goalie wants out Hot hitters go extra yard for payback Oversanitized baseball could stand more dirt About the Real Cities Network MNG Corporate Site Map
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp%3Fymd%3D20070530%26content_id%3D1996073%26vkey%3Drecap%26fext%3D.jsp%26c_id%3Dmlb&cid=1116770887&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News MLB.TV: Live and On-Demand MLB.TV Mosaic Help Blog Player News and Notes Home Run Beat the Streak Staples Easy Fantasy Report Fantasy News and Notes Text Messaging – Alerts & More Manage Services – Mobile Dashboard MLB 2007 Mobile Game DHL Delivery of the Day 05/31/2007 12:40 AM ET Harang completes the job for Reds Ace records sixth victory of '07; Cincy wins third straight By Jim Carley / Special to MLB.com Norris Hopper has gone 6-for-8 in two games since taking over for injured leadoff hitter Ryan Freel. (AP) Reds notes: Wise brings no baggage &#149; Harang strikes out seven &#149; Reds score three in the first &#149; Narron gets ejected &#149; Encarnacion's diving stop &#149; Castro's diving stop Astros bats stay cold as skid continues Astros notes: Struggles baffle White Yanks snap slide with big win over Jays Tribe pound Dice-K in finale Weaver shaky but Angels rally D-backs sweep behind Johnson Zito dominant as Giants blank Mets A-Rod defends controversial shout Lowe, Dodgers blank Nationals Young brilliant; Greene powers Padres &#149; Harang strikes out seven &#149; Reds score three in the first &#149; Narron gets ejected &#149; Encarnacion's diving stop Reds notes: Wise brings no baggage HOUSTON -- There was a time when Aaron Harang did not relish facing the Astros. But those days are long gone now. Harang became the Reds' first six-game winner by going the distance in a 4-3 victory over Houston on Wednesday. It was Cincinnati's third straight win. Harang is 6-0 over his last seven starts against Houston, which has lost 10 straight games. "A couple of years ago, I couldn't get a ball by them," said Harang, who tossed his first complete game of the season. "I remember that well." In 2004-05, Harang started nine games against Houston and was 1-5. But the last two seasons, he's unbeaten against the Astros. "I don't know what it is," Harang said. "I don't know if I'm throwing different or not. "I just go out and try to be aggressive. It doesn't matter who I'm facing. I just try to throw strikes and make them put the ball in play." Harang allowed two earned runs on six hits while striking out seven. He retired 14 straight after allowing a second-inning single to Adam Everett. "Harang was outstanding," said Reds manager Jerry Narron, who was ejected in the first inning for arguing balls and strikes. "He has given us good outings almost every time out this year. With your No. 1 guy, that's what you're looking for. It was nice to see us play some good defense behind him too." Harang (6-2) was getting his slider past the Astros all night. "That's what [pitching coach] Dick Pole said, that my slider was real tight," Harang said. "I was able to throw it down in the zone. "I went [to bench coach] Bucky [Dent] after the seventh and told him I could finish it. I figured I have an extra day off this week, so I could run the pitch count up a little [to 105]. And they were swinging early a lot." Harang impressed his teammates. "He did a phenomenal job," center fielder Norris Hopper said. "He was just doing his thing, and they couldn't get to him." The Reds jumped to a 3-0 lead in the first inning, although they lost Narron in the process. Narron saw six pitches before being thrown out by home-plate umpire Bill Welke. Hopper, who went 3-for-4, led off the game with a double and scored on Alex Gonzalez's single. An RBI double by Ken Griffey Jr. drove in Gonzalez. Griffey scored on Adam Dunn's single. It was Dunn's 500th career RBI. Hopper has gone 6-for-8 since taking over the leadoff spot Tuesday from the injured Ryan Freel. "He just puts the bat on the ball," Narron said of Hopper. "It's great to see somebody step in and do the job for us like that. I'm happy for the guy. He has put in a lot of time in the Minor Leagues to get here." Said Hopper: "I feel real good, but it's only a couple of games. I've been waiting on this chance all year to show what I can do. Any time you get an opportunity, you have to give it your best shot. It's easy leading off when you have guys like Gonzalez and Griffey and Dunn behind you. I just have to get on base and let them knock me in." The Reds have matched their longest winning streak of the year, having last won three straight during the first week of the season (April 5-7). "That's the way we should be playing," Gonzalez said. "We know we are better than we've been playing. When you're struggling, you're struggling, and you just have to forget about it. But we've got a good team, and I think we're coming out of that [slump] now." "You can just tell the atmosphere is way different in the locker room," Hopper said. "Everybody's working hard and working together, and that's all you can ask for." is a contributor to MLB.com. This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs. Register | Log In Help | Contact Us &copy; 2001-2007 MLB Advanced Media, L.P. All rights reserved. The following are trademarks or service marks of Major League Baseball entities and may be used only with permission of Major League Baseball Properties, Inc. or the relevant Major League Baseball entity: Major League, Major League Baseball, MLB, the silhouetted batter logo, World Series, National League, American League, Division Series, League Championship Series, All-Star Game, and the names, nicknames, logos, uniform designs, color combinations, and slogans designating the Major League Baseball clubs and entities, and their respective mascots, events and exhibitions. Use of the Website signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy (updated 03.22.05)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/topics/sports/story.html%3Fid%3D9d06c004-48d6-4bc8-824d-8abed1cd869d&cid=1116768880&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Bettman intrigued about new Canadian team Jump to: canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio A Shopper's Secret Diary A Shopper's Secret Diary What's Hot and What's Not What's Hot and What's Not Ask a Shopping Question Ask a Shopping Question Unsure of how to feature? Click me to Bettman intrigued about new Canadian team NHL commissioner, Gary Bettman speaks during a press conference before the start of Game One of the 2007 Stanley Cup finals between the Anaheim Ducks and the Ottawa Senators on May 28, 2007 at Honda Center in Anaheim, California. Photograph by : Jeff Golden/Getty Images Ken Warren, CanWest News Service Published: Tuesday, May 29, 2007 ANAHEIM, Calif. -- National Hockey League commissioner Gary Bettman called the prospect of adding another Canadian team "intriguing" on Monday. During his state-of-the-league address before Game 1 of the Stanley Cup final, Bettman addressed issues from weak TV ratings to a drop in NHL coverage from traditional media outlets, but his most interesting comments dealt with Jim Balsillie's tentative agreement to purchase the Nashville Predators from Craig Leopold for $220 million US. Balsillie, owner of Waterloo, Ont.-based Research in Motion, maker of the Blackberry electronic communication device, has made no secret of his desire to move an NHL team to Ontario. Earlier this season, Balsillie offered $175 million US for the Pittsburgh Penguins, but later withdrew that offer. While Bettman danced around the particulars of the pending sale, the terms of the lease between the Predators and the city of Nashville would allow an owner to move the franchise next year if the team's paid attendance doesn't top 14,000 during the 2007-'08 season. The Predators averaged 13,815 fans this season. Bettman deflected questions on whether the league's board of governors would allow a relocation of the franchise - such a move would require approval from 75 per cent of the league's governors - and the possibility that Balsillie would try to put the club in Kitchener-Waterloo, Ont. What Bettman did open up about was the potential for the NHL to return to either Winnipeg or Quebec City. The Winnipeg Jets moved to Phoenix in 1996, becoming the Coyotes, one year after the Quebec Nordiques moved to Denver and became the Colorado Avalanche. "When we had the chance to go back to Minnesota, we did because it made sense, the right ownership, the right building situation," Bettman said. "The market was strong and vibrant. We haven't studied Quebec City or Winnipeg or anywhere else in Canada, but the notion that, if it could work to put a franchise back in a place where it was once lost, feels good. It intrigues me, it's intriguing." Bettman tempered his remarks by pointing out the league wouldn't return to any market unless its officials were satisfied all conditions were in place to ensure success. Winnipeg has only a 15,000-seat arena for the Manitoba Moose of the American Hockey League, and that is generally considered too small to house an NHL team, in part because the arena couldn't generate enough revenue to sustain a big-league franchise. The Nordiques left Quebec City because they couldn't find an owner willing to build a new arena to replace the aging Colisee. Balsillie eyes lease for Copps Coliseum A company owned by Canadian billionaire Jim Balsillie has entered into an exclusive agreement to negotiate... Free agents wary of Preds Column: Leipold left with profit Vote: Is Hamilton NHL-worthy? Predators stats and bios Stellar Emery not enough for Sens In the end, Ray Emery couldn't stop them all, though he tried and deserved a lot better than his fate... Full NHL playoff coverage Gallery: Stanley Cup action Turnovers did Sens in FIA clears McLaren team in Monaco investigation Formula One's governing body cleared the McLaren 