http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-4&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/sports/baseball/31mets.html&cid=1116827440&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Overrated? Not Zito, as Giants Blank Mets - New York Times Giants 3, Mets 0 Overrated? Not Zito, as Giants Blank Mets Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 The guy named Barry stepped into the batter’s box last night, and the booing started almost immediately. The chants came a few seconds later. “Overrated! Overrated!” the crowd screamed. Skip to next paragraph Barton Silverman/The New York Times Barry Zito improved to 5-5. He went seven innings and gave up six hits, a walk, struck out seven and lowered his E.R.A. to 4.21. Keep up with the latest news on the on The Times’s baseball blog. Go to the Bats Blog » Times Topics: The Yankees Times Topics: The Mets Barton Silverman/The New York Times Rich Aurilia was forced out on a ball hit by Barry Bonds in the third. David Wright, who had shifted near second, completed the double play. Sitting on the bench, might have chuckled. However briefly, the fans’ disdain rerouted toward one of his teammates. Barry Zito, the left-hander who spurned the ’ free-agent offer last off-season for $51 million more, a longer contract and the chance to continue living in Northern California, had apparently rankled some folks at Shea Stadium. Then Zito went out and produced a dominant pitching performance — seven scoreless innings in the Giants’ 3-0 victory — which probably bothered them even more. Overrated? Not last night. “Obviously, he was great,” Manager Willie Randolph said after the Mets were shut out for the first time this season. Almost in the next sentence, Randolph said the same thing about his left-handed control specialist, , who remained stuck at 295 career victories. He and Zito shared eerily similar pitching lines: Over seven innings, each threw 122 pitches, 77 for strikes, but the difference came in how they handled runners on base. Zito (5-5) stranded all six base runners, while Glavine, a pitch away from ending the inning each time the Giants scored, allowed them to rally with two outs and no one on base. He allowed two runs in the first and one in the third — Pedro Feliz drove in all three — then, buoyed by an extra day’s rest, stayed in long enough to hope the offense would awaken. It never did. “When their guys are hitting ground balls, I’m doing my job,” said Glavine, who scattered nine hits. “I’m just not getting the results. There’s nothing I can say to make people understand when you go out there, do what you want to do, make the pitches and you don’t get the results. It’s one of the single most frustrating things.” In 12 starts, Glavine has five victories and a 3.44 earned run average. He acknowledged afterward that considering the way he has pitched this season, he might have expected another victory here or there. But, he added, he understands that things have a way of evening out. “Three hundred is so far away right now that it’s not even part of the equation,” Glavine said. Unlike in their last meeting, Glavine kept Bonds in the park, holding him to one hit in four plate appearances. Bonds singled, grounded into a double play, was walked intentionally and grounded out, and his single contributed to the Giants’ two-run first. After falling behind, 1-2, Bengie Molina drew a walk, loading the bases for Feliz, who grounded a two-run single past In all, Glavine needed 30 pitches to set down the Giants, continuing an unsettling trend. He has not pitched a scoreless first inning since May 8, in San Francisco, and he threw more than 29 pitches in the first for the third consecutive start. “More than anything else, it’s a streak of bad luck,” Glavine said. “I’m going to give up runs at some point, they’ve just been coming too soon.” With Zito pitching, any runs were too much. On a glorious 76-degree day, Zito strolled into the Giants’ clubhouse before the game wearing a knit cap and a fleece jacket. The attire had no effect on his mood. Cool, calm and collected as always, Zito won his second start against the Mets this month and, a few players said, looked even better this time around. When he missed, he missed down. He complemented a fastball that did not exceed 87 miles an hour with a slow curve, a slower curve and an even slower curve. Of his seven strikeouts, six came on a curveball, and Mets hitters could not adjust when he jammed them with cutters. “He’s got this late movement,” said , who had one of the Mets’ six hits. The Mets put runners on base in each of the first five innings, including the first two batters in the second, then wasted Paul Lo Duca’s leadoff double (his 1,000th career hit) in the seventh. Zito finished off his evening by striking out pinch-hitter Julio Franco looking at a menacing 66-m.p.h curveball. “It’s always great coming to New York,” said Zito, who, as a member of the , pitched nine times at Yankee Stadium. “You get all these trash-talking fans saying everything they can think of to me in the outfield. That’s what makes this place special.” Asked if heard anything original, Zito said: “Not creative at all. Just blatant expletives at me. That’s all.” Staying true to his pregame promise, Willie Randolph inserted Guillermo Mota, fresh off his 50-game suspension for violating baseball’s policy on performance-enhancing drugs. He received a mixed reaction from the crowd of 41,395, although the fans clapped and welcomed him into the dugout after he pitched an uneventful eighth inning. Mota pitched a perfect ninth, too. “It’s nice to be back,” Mota said. ... On May 17, when Moises Alou was placed on the disabled list with a strained left quadriceps, he vowed to return May 28, the first day he was eligible to come off. That day has come and gone, and Alou said he was frustrated that the injury had taken longer than expected to heal. “I guess what I did was more serious than what we thought,” Alou said. “It’s something that I thought wouldn’t take that long, and I don’t know what set me back.” The earlier projection that Alou could return by the weekend seems a little premature, he said, and a more reasonable guess is that he will be activated toward the middle of next week. Alou was more optimistic about his pending return Sunday in Florida, but he tried running Monday and still felt discomfort. Next Article in Sports (3 of 26) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. METS NOTEBOOK; Bonds Sits One Out as the Beat Goes On METS 5, GIANTS 4; Down to Last Out, the Mets Aren&#8217;t Down at All Mets&#8217; Lineup Is Preparing for Mastery and Mystery METS 6, MARLINS 4; Sosa Rebounds as Mets Sweep Marlins Next Article in Sports (3 of 26) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France "The Amazin's," 80-page Commemorative Newspaper and Box Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SPORT/05/31/nba.spurs.reut/&cid=1116539054&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ San Antonio advance to NBA finals  - CNN.com San Antonio advance to NBA finals (Reuters) -- The San Antonio Spurs advanced to the NBA finals with a crushing 109-84 victory over the Utah Jazz on Wednesday. Tim Duncan and Tony Parker each scored 21 points, helping the Spurs clinch the Western Conference series 4-1 and book a place in the NBA finals for the third time in five seasons. The Spurs will play either the Detroit Pistons or the Cleveland Cavaliers in the finals, which start on June 7 in San Antonio. The Pistons and Cavaliers are tied 2-2 in the Eastern Conference finals. "It's great," told reporters. "Last year we had a tough finish. To come back this year, to put the team back together, to have a healthy year myself and to go through three really, really good teams. It's great to get back here." San Antonio were leading Utah 16-11 in the first period when they embarked on a streak that set the tone for the game. Parker scored seven consecutive points to push the advantage to 23-11 and Duncan dunked on an alley oop. Bruce Bowen connected on a three-pointer before Parker drove for another basket and in less than three minutes the Spurs had a 19-point lead. "Tonight we played great, everybody from the starting five, from the bench, everybody made shots," Parker told reporters. "I think we won that game in the first quarter, and we kept the lead the whole game." The Spurs, who have defeated the Jazz 19 consecutive times in San Antonio, led 34-15 after the first quarter and 55-39 at the half. That advantage grew to 83-56 going into the fourth. Andrei Kirilenko led the Jazz with 13 points. Deron Williams, who played with a sprained left foot, and Matt Harpring had 11 each. Carlos Boozer was held to nine points and 12 rebounds. Guard Derek Fisher missed the first half while returning from New York where is daughter is undergoing treatment for an eye condition. He was 0-3 from the floor. The finals will be the Spurs' fourth appearance in nine seasons. They won the NBA title in 1999, 2003 and 2005, but lost in the second round of the 2004 playoffs and the Western Conference semi-finals in 2006. They have seven days to prepare for another tilt at the title. . All rights reserved.This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Next story in World Sport Ex-spy: UK involvement in murder Andrei Lugovoi -- the man British authorities accuse of poisoning a former Russian spy in London last year -- told reporters Thursday he wasn't behind the e ... Workers find dead baby in coolbox KLM plane hits turbulence, 16 hurt Panda Xiang Xiang dies in forest Russia missile test signal to U.S. Spain sues over shipwreck booty Putin: Test missile signal to U.S. Crashed chopper site secure Rival leaders to hold talks Suicide bomb kills 25 in Iraq Court to prosecute for PM's murder Al Qaeda's 'project' in Lebanon Officers cleared in stoning death China markets tumble 6.5% China's wheel of change San Antonio's Tony Parker and actress Eva Longoria celebrate the clinching victory. Click Here to try 4 Free Trial Issues of Time! How To Get CNN &copy; 2007 Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company. All Rights Reserved. under which this service is provided to you. External sites open in new window; not endorsed by CNN.com Pay service with live and archived video.
