http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-6&fd=R&url=http://www.ktvu.com/mlb/13418933/detail.html&cid=1116768078&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ St. Louis Cardinals (21-29) At Colorado Rockies (25-28), 9:05 P.m. - MLB News Story - KTVU San Francisco St. Louis Cardinals (21-29) At Colorado Rockies (25-28), 9:05 P.m. (Sports Network) - The St. Louis Cardinals try to string back-to-back wins together on the road for the first time in nearly two months this evening, when they wrap up a four-game set with the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field. St. Louis became the last NL team to reach double digits in road victories on Wednesday, as Albert Pujols and Jim Edmonds homered on two straight pitches to highlight a five-run fifth inning in the Cardinals' 8-4 win. Scott Rolen finished 2-for-5 with two RBI for the Cardinals, who snapped a seven-game road losing streak and improved to just 10-16 away from home this season. Edmonds finished 3-for-5 for St. Louis, which is just 3-11 this month on the road and has not won back-to-back away games since it won four in a row from April 8-11. Todd Wellemeyer (1-1) allowed three runs on seven hits with a walk and three strikeouts over five-plus frames in the first start of his major league career. Brad Hawpe and Matt Holliday homered for the Rockies, who saw their first seven-game win streak since September 6-12, 1998 come to an end. Jason Hirsh (2-5), who is winless in his last seven starts, gave up eight runs on 10 hits with two strikeouts and two walks in 4 2/3 innings for Colorado. Getting the call for the Cardinals tonight will be right-hander Brad Thompson, who has won two of his last three starts. Thompson improved to 3-1 on the year after he surrendered three runs and 10 hits in 5 1/3 innings Saturday against the Washington Nationals. Thompson, who is pitching to a 4.72 earned run average on the year, has yet to receive a decision against the Rockies in five career outings. His only other start against Colorado came back on May 8, when he allowed a run on six hits in five innings of his team's 4-1 win. Colorado will counter with veteran Aaron Cook, who is 4-1 with a 4.11 ERA. Cook won his fourth straight decision Saturday against the San Francisco Giants, giving up a run and five hits in his first complete game of the season. All the news was not great for the Cardinals on Wednesday, as they learned that catcher Yadier Molina will miss four-to-six weeks with a fractured left wrist. Molina, who is hitting .273, left Tuesday's game in the fourth inning after being hit by a foul tip an inning earlier. The Rockies have split their six meetings with the Cards so far this year, though St. Louis won seven of nine against Colorado last season. Copyright 2007 Courtesy of Indians, Tigers Set To Renew Rivalry In Cleveland The Cleveland Indians try to put more distance between themselves and the Detroit Tigers when the AL Central rivals kick off a four- game series this evening at Jacobs Field. San Diego Padres (30-22) At Pittsburgh Pirates (23-29), 7:05 P.m. Reds Try To Add To Houston's Problems Price Could Be Right For Devil Rays In Next Week's Draft Marlins Hope To Carry Momentum Into Milwaukee Cards Aim For Rare Road Win Streak In Finale With Rox Orioles Try To Extend Win Streak Versus Streaking Angels Mariners Return Home To Take On Struggling Rangers Dodgers Shoot For History In Washington Padres Try To Keep Pace In NL West In Finale With Bucs San Francisco Giants Tickets Are you surprised the St. Louis Cardinals won the World Series? Sign up to receive daily sports headlines. Click here for the privacy policy By using this site, you accept the terms of our Visitor Agreement Click here for advertising information.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-5&fd=R&url=http://www.sportinglife.com/tennis/news/story_get.cgi%3FSTORY_NAME%3Dtennis/07/05/31/TENNIS_French_Men.html&cid=1116760279&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ HEWITT RALLIES FOR VICTORY: Sporting Life - Tennis | Tennis News, Tim Henman, French Open Live, Roland Garros, Rafael Nadal, Roger Federer, Justine Henin, Serena Williams, Jelena Jankovic, Ana Ivanovic, Andy Murray, Tennis News, Tennis Scores, ATP & WTA Tennis News, Scores, & Updates HEWITT RALLIES FOR VICTORY Subscribe to RSS Feed By Steve Douglas, PA Sport, Paris Lleyton Hewitt came from two sets down to win a marathon second-round match with former champion Gaston Gaudio at the French Open today. The Australian, seeded 14th and one of the dark horses for the title, is known for his fighting spirit and he needed it as he claimed a 4-6 3-6 6-2 6-4 6-2 win in almost three-and-a-half hours on Philippe Chatrier court. Gaudio, the 2004 champion, looked in control when two sets up but Hewitt then launched an all-too-familiar fightback and forced the Argentinian into a raft of errors. After seeing himself pegged back level at two sets all, Gaudio trudged back to his seat as he was broken again in the opening game of the decider. Hewitt, who has not gone further than the quarter-finals at the French Open, had no further problems and set up a third-round clash with Jarkko Nieminen. The Finn, seeded 20th, thrashed France's Mathieu Montcourt 6-1 6-1 6-4 on Court 3. Marcos Baghdatis found it just as straightforward as he raced through his second-round clash. The Cypriot defeated Denmark's Kristian Pless 7-5 6-3 6-4 on Court 1 to reach the third round at Roland Garros for the first time in three attempts. He will now face Jan Hajek, who beat fellow Czech Bohdan Ulihrach in five sets. Baghdatis, seeded 16th, made his name in the tennis world by reaching the final of the Australian Open last year, before losing to Roger Federer. Meanwhile, Serbia's Novak Djokovic, the sixth seed, secured a four-set victory over Frenchman Laurent Recouderc. The 20-year-old Djokovic, a quarter-finalist at Roland Garros last year, won 6-3 3-6 6-3 6-1 on Suzanne Lenglen court. Click here to send us your sporting feedback RAFA JUST TOO GOOD SERENE PROGRESS FOR WILLIAMS NO PROBLEM FOR MARIA SHAHAR PEER-LESS IN PARIS BATTLING QUALITIES DELIGHT DOGGED HEWITT ROUTINE STUFF FOR FERRER Sports News & Entertainment Club On The Park Epsom Derby Free Bets Royal Ascot Free Bets &copy; 2007 Sporting Life UK Ltd, All Rights Reserved. Email the Editor / Sign Up Three winners from three bets last week - sign up now! Free £20 Matched Bet! Day Five - May 31 Day Four - May 30 Day Three - May 29 Day Two - May 28 Day One - May 27 Safin Suffers As Seeds Fall Henman Falls At The First The best results from google, Ask Jeeves, Yahoo! and more
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-3&fd=R&url=http://www.boston.com/sports/hockey/articles/2007/05/31/high_flying_ducks_take_2_0_lead&cid=1116235930&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ High-flying Ducks take 2-0 lead - The Boston Globe High-flying Ducks take 2-0 lead It can be no comfort to the Ottawa Senators, now down, 2-0, in the Stanley Cup finals, that the Anaheim Ducks have turned the rink into a minefield. DUCKS 1, SENATORS 0 High-flying Ducks take 2-0 lead Anaheim's Corey Perry needs some ice after he's dropped by Mike Fisher (center). (MARK J. TERRILL/ASSOCIATED PRESS) By Fluto Shinzawa, Globe Staff | ANAHEIM, Calif. -- It can be no comfort to the Ottawa Senators, now down, 2-0, in the Stanley Cup finals, that the Anaheim Ducks have turned the rink into a minefield. Last night at the Honda Center, everywhere the Senators seemed to skate, they plowed into booby traps and barbed wire set by the mischievous Ducks and general Randy Carlyle, whose tactics have given his club a two-game advantage in the best-of-seven series. "The biggest thing for us is that we're getting really good back pressure," said Anaheim checking-line wing Rob Niedermayer. "We're not giving them too many odd-man rushes. That lets our D stand up and not give them the line too much. If you give them the blue line, they're going to make pretty skilled plays out there. That's been the key for us." To counter Ottawa coach Bryan Murray's No. 1 line, Carlyle has sent out Niedermayer and fellow checkers Travis Moen and Samuel Pahlsson, and blue-line studs Chris Pronger and Scott Niedermayer, asking his players to fill the roles they've been given. Last night before 17,258, the checking line did that -- and more. Pahlsson, the former Boston centerman swapped out of town for distant memories Andrei Nazarov and Patrick Traverse, scored to power his club to a 1-0 win. It wasn't enough that Pahlsson threw a game-high four hits. Or that he helped limit Ottawa's top line -- one that's begging for a breakup upon the Senators' return to Scotiabank Place -- for six shots. Or that he won 10 of 12 faceoffs, while counterpart Jason Spezza, who's sputtered on the big stage, lost 13 of 16 draws. On top of that, Pahlsson gained control of a third-period neutral-zone Ottawa cough-up, looped around, and took off. Pahlsson shook off a backcheck by Ottawa captain Daniel Alfredsson and carried the puck down right wing, stopping short at the faceoff dot. Using Joe Corvo as a screen, Pahlsson snapped a wrist shot through the defenseman's legs and past the blocker of goalie Ray Emery at 14:16. "Great shot," said Murray. "Good play on his part." As much as the center's timely score propelled the Ducks to a second straight win, it was Pahlsson and his teammates' defensive commitment that limited the Senators to 16 shots and resulted in Anaheim counterattacks. Murray, aware that Anaheim's checking line was giving his gunners fits, juggled his lineup to get his stars away from Carlyle's defensive pests. To start the game, Murray sent Mike Fisher out with Alfredsson and Peter Schaefer, and the gritty centerman set the tone by walloping Scott Niedermayer against the boards during the opening shift. But aside from several spare shifts, Alfredsson took his usual right-wing position alongside Spezza and Dany Heatley, who nearly clicked during a five-on-three power play (the second time in two games the Senators have enjoyed a two-man advantage) in the first period. Ottawa had a handful of sparkling scoring chances during the 67-second five-on-three. Winger Mike Comrie, stationed at the right post, stared down an open net but couldn't get his stick untangled. Alfredsson uncorked a pair of shots from the point that thudded off goalie Jean-Sebastien Giguere, who came far off his line to cut down the shooting angle. But Giguere's best stop of the power play came on the rare occasion that Ottawa's signature play -- Spezza sending a cross-crease pass to Heatley -- actually clicked. Heatley parked himself at the post and thought, after taking a pass from his centerman, that he had some open net. Giguere, however, shifted from right to left to stone Heatley's stuff. "I thought I was able to [make] the first save and guys were on the rebound right away," said Giguere. "We got pretty fortunate to get out of that one with no goal. We've got to stop taking penalties like that. We can't afford to do that every game. It's going to end up costing us some goals eventually." Giguere made one final game-saving stop. Alfredsson, stickhandling in the left corner, fed Spezza in front. The center gathered the pass and got off a quick shot, but Giguere, stationed correctly and in perfect butterfly position, stopped Spezza's attempt with 4:20 remaining in regulation. But Giguere's teammates made even bigger saves. Late in the third, with Giguere out of position after stopping a Corvo blast, Schaefer settled the rebound and spotted open net. Schaefer's shot, however, went wide when another ex-Bruin, defenseman Sean O'Donnell, got a piece of the puck with his stick. Then in the final minute, when Emery (30 saves) went off for an extra attacker, Alfredsson wound up and ripped a slapper from the point. The shot never got through to Giguere, as Moen hit the deck and blocked Alfredsson's cannon. "It's nice to see the three players getting rewarded for all the hard work," said Carlyle of Moen and his linemates. "They play tough minutes. A lot of times the spotlight has not been directed toward them. Right now, they're in it." Fluto Shinzawa can be reached at &copy; Copyright 2007 Globe Newspaper Company. All Globe stories since 2003 are now FREE E-mail to a friend The New York Times Company
