http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.urbanacitizen.com/main.asp%3FSectionID%3D4%26SubSectionID%3D8%26ArticleID%3D144002%26TM%3D33406.54&cid=1116770887&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Houston’s Adam Everett (28) prepares to slide as Cincinnati catcher Chad Moeller waits for the ball in the second inning on Tuesday. HOUSTON (AP) - Scott Hatteberg hit a solo home run in the eighth inning and Matt Belisle struck out a career-high eight Tuesday night to lead the Cincinnati Reds to a 2-1 victory over Houston, the Astros' ninth consecutive loss. Belisle (5-4) allowed only two hits after Adam Everett's RBI triple that was nearly an inside-the-park homer. Belisle, a native of Austin, Texas, threw 102 pitches in 7 2-3 innings, his longest outing since a complete-game victory over Pittsburgh on April 28. Adam Dunn knocked in a run with a sacrifice fly for the Reds, who won on the road for the third time in their last 12 games away from home. David Weathers got Carlos Lee to ground into a game-ending double play with the bases loaded in the ninth to pick up his 10th save. Jason Jennings gave up three hits with three strikeouts in his first start for Houston since April 8. Jennings was on the disabled list with tendinitis in his right throwing elbow. Chad Qualls (4-2) replaced Brad Lidge to start the seventh and took the loss. The Astros have lost nine in a row for the first time since September 1996. They lost to the Reds for just the third time in 10 meetings. Craig Biggio doubled with two outs in the second and scored the Astros' only run. Everett hit a sinking liner to center and the ball skidded past Norris Hopper when he couldn't make a diving catch. Hopper chased down the ball and hit Brandon Phillips with a relay throw as Everett rounded third. The throw home to Chad Moeller was high, but the catcher swiped the sliding Everett for the out at the plate. Jennings retired nine in a row after giving up three hits and walking two in the first two innings. He struck out Moeller and Belisle to end the fifth and was finished after 79 pitches. Rick White relieved to start the sixth and gave up a double to Hopper and a single to Hatteberg. Left-hander Trever Miller came on and walked Ken Griffey Jr. to load the bases. Lidge, who hadn't pitched since bruising his knee in San Francisco on May 21, replaced Miller and struck out Phillips. Dunn then flew out to deep center to score Hopper and tie it at 1. Belisle retired 11 consecutive Astros, four on strikeouts, after Morgan Ensberg's two-out single in the third. Lee ended the streak in the seventh with a one-out single to left, but Hunter Pence grounded into an inning-ending double play. With one out in the eighth, Hatteberg hammered Qualls' 2-0 pitch into the Astros' bullpen in right center. It was Hatteberg's fifth homer of the season and his second in three days. He hit career homer No. 100 against Pittsburgh on Saturday. Belisle got the first two outs of the eighth and was relieved by left-hander Jon Coutlangus, who struck out Jason Lane. Notes: Hopper led off and started in center field, both effects of his collision with Ryan Freel on Monday. The Reds placed Freel on the 15-day disabled list before the game. "Ads published on this site are not for republication in print or web media without the expressed written consent of both the advertiser and The Brown Publishing Company." , All Rights Reserved
