http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-1&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/bb/4849656.html&cid=1116770887&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Astros' losing streak reaches an imperfect 10 | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices May 31, 2007, 12:53AM Harang hangs another loss on streak with 6-hitter Copyright 2007 Houston Chronicle The Astros' Craig Biggio is closing in on the 3,000-hit club. July 2 vs. Philadelphia. Jose de Jesus Ortiz Fan blogger Chip Bailey Ensberg discusses new arrangement at 3B Berkman discusses Bonds' HR chase Berkman talks about staying near .500 Slideshow: Clemens reacts to Astros critics Complete interview with Clemens Clemens on his Yankees return Berkman: Where else would Rocket go? Biggio: Astros have to move on Oswalt: Rosters change; Astros have to play as team Lidge: Yankees were frontrunner Garner on Albers win Hunter Pence on his first career grand slam Astros end up seeing Reds Timeline: Follow Astros in '07 Timeline: Review Astros in '06 Perhaps the Astros are setting us all up for their most miraculous turnaround yet. Either that or baseball fans in Houston are in for a long, miserable summer at the ballpark. The season slipped a little closer toward becoming a certified disaster Wednesday night when the Astros again struggled to score and plunged to their 10th consecutive loss, 4-3 to the Cincinnati Reds at Minute Maid Park. The defeat dropped the Astros (21-31) to 10 games under .500 and one game ahead of the last-place Reds in the National League Central. It's their longest losing streak since they dropped a club-record 11 consecutive games from Aug. 17-28, 1995. "That's how many? Ten? And really in crappy fashion," manager Phil Garner said. "We have not hit the ball. We went a bunch of times without scoring runs when (Roger Clemens) was pitching, and I called that stupid, but this is bordering on stupid now, too. This is really ridiculous." The Astros have given up more runs (72) during their losing streak than they have hits (71). They managed just six hits, including two doubles, against Reds starter Aaron Harang, who needed only 105 pitches to throw his ninth career complete game. Harang retired 14 in a row in one stretch and sent down the final six batters he faced, retiring the Astros in order on seven pitches in the ninth. "It's a pretty frustrating time for us," said second baseman Craig Biggio, who made two errors. "I've seen a couple of guys struggle a little bit, but not as many as we have right now, and that's frustrating. We need to get this monkey off our back and get a 'W' and hopefully get more guys contributing and pitching in and doing the little things to win baseball games." The Astros fell behind 3-0 in the first inning before many in the crowd of 31,904 had found their seats. Considering how poorly the offense has been performing, the hopes for a comeback were bleak. Somehow, the players remain positive. "I'm coming out each day more and more fired up," third baseman Morgan Ensberg said. "I recognize this is a flat-out dogfight, this is a battle, and I refuse to give in. I'm not going to lie down. I'm going to go out there and do absolutely everything I can to do something positive." The first three Reds hitters reached and scored against Astros starter Wandy Rodriguez (2-5), who labored through five innings. Norris Hopper doubled and scored on Alex Gonzalez's single, and Ken Griffey Jr. drove home Gonzalez with a double and scored on Adam Dunn's single to make it 3-0. "I started really rough, but I tried to fight back and keep the game close so we could tie it," Rodriguez said. "The first inning I had a few bad pitches, but I came back and was able to hit my spots." Carlos Lee recorded his 46th RBI of the season in the bottom of the first with a double to score Ensberg. Cincinnati took a 4-1 lead in the sixth when Hopper scored from first on a Gonzalez double, though it appeared shortstop Adam Everett had a shot to throw him out at the plate with his relay throw. "I was a little surprised," Garner said. "I thought we were going to get him." Harang (6-2) had retired 14 in a row, including striking out the side in the fifth, before Lee led off the seventh with a single. Hunter Pence reached on an error, and Everett singled to center one out later to score Lee and get the Astros within 4-2. But the Astros couldn't get closer in the inning as pinch hitters Mike Lamb and Orlando Palmeiro both popped out to short. The Astros sliced the deficit to 4-3 in the eighth. Biggio led off with a double to right — his 2,974th career hit — and scored on Berkman's sizzling grounder to short that Gonzalez was surprisingly able to stop. That was one of three balls the Astros struck hard late in the game but right at Reds defenders. "Every night I come to the ballpark thinking this is the night we're going to throw together 20 hits and 55 runs, and sooner or later you're going to catch up," Garner said. "We played things aggressively during the game. We've done it all year, no different than we've done in this stretch. We've tried to play aggressive, and it hasn't worked for us. There's nothing else we could have done tonight." Astros' losing streak reaches an imperfect 10 McCann-do attitude triggers Braves' win Guillen welcomes firing after latest White Sox loss NL: D-Backs' Johnson in fine form in return from injury AL: A-Rod's big mouth helps Yanks win ASTROS NOTES: Jennings recovers nicely NL NOTES: Cards' Molina has broken wrist Astros' losing streak reaches an imperfect 10 Reds 4, Astros 3 Skidding Astros bring road woes home Astros frustrating road trip ends with 1-run loss Reds choke rally, send Astros to 9th consecutive defeat Reds extend Astros' skid to nine Reds finish sweep of Astros with win in 11th ASTROS NOTES: Jennings recovers nicely Astros' bat support helps Pettitte win while struggling Rally gives Astros first winning streak in 2 weeks Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
