http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.metronews.ca/storyCP.aspx%3Fpg%3D./s053134A.xml&cid=1116377593&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Derby winner Street Sense skipping Belmont to prepare for other races LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) - Kentucky Derby winner Street Sense will skip the Belmont Stakes so trainer Carl Nafzger can prepare his colt for the Travers Stakes and Breeders' Cup Classic later this year. Nafzger said he talked to owner James Tafel for two hours Wednesday night before deciding against a rematch with Preakness winner Curlin in the final leg of the Triple Crown. "The competitive side said 'Go,' the logical side said 'No, no, no,"' Nafzger said. Nafzger said they will aim toward the summer and fall schedule that features the Travers and Breeders' Cup. "Mr. Tafel said let's not chase spilled water," Nafzger said. "We spilled our water during the Preakness. We got beat. We got outran." Street Sense and jockey Calvin Borel appeared headed to the Belmont to chase the Triple Crown when he took the lead deep in the stretch at the Preakness, only to have Curlin and jockey Robby Albarado slip by at the wire. So with the opportunity of being the first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978 gone, Tafel wants his colt to chase the possibility of becoming the first horse to win the Derby, the Breeders' Cup Juvenile, the Travers and the Breeders' Cup Classic. The Travers is Aug. 25 at Saratoga. The Breeders' Cup Classic is Oct. 27 at Monmouth Park. Nafzger said there was a concern that Street Sense wouldn't have time to get properly prepared for the Travers if he ran the 1Â½-mile Belmont. The horse will be able to rest and compete in one or two races between now and the Travers, including possibly the Jim Dandy. "I know there's disappointment we're not going to the Belmont," Nafzger said. "But somewhere we want to make another stand." Â© The Canadian Press, 2007 Letters to the Editor
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-4&fd=R&url=http://blogs.thatsracin.com/kathyspitstop/2007/05/nascar_consider.html&cid=1116821771&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Kathy's Pit Stop: NASCAR considering changing testing rules NASCAR considering changing testing rules Goodyear, NASCAR and COT, Oh my! Mears gets his first win With Jr. leaving, who will drive the #8 next year? Like it or not - COT goes full-time in 2008 NASCAR needs to have a meeting with Montoya Harvick wins his first All-Star Challenge AT&T wins lawsuit against NASCAR Dale Earnhardt Jr. and team nailed for penalty NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series In the pits with Tia Add me to your TypePad People list Subscribe to this blog's feed &laquo; Goodyear, NASCAR and COT, Oh my! NASCAR considering changing testing rules NASCAR seems to be rethinking its testing policy according to an Associate Press . Whether it has anything to do with Goodyear's asking or Roush's complaints really doesn't matter, they have obviously realized that teams are getting around their testing rules and want to do something about it. "It appears that we've got teams that want to test more and teams that want to test less, and teams that test on tires that are not made by our tire supplier," Robin Pemberton, NASCAR vice president of competition, told The Associated Press on Wednesday. "So we're going to start looking at a lot of different things, from eventually lifting the test ban completely, or get as restrictive as we cannot let teams test anywhere at any time, or land somewhere in between." I guess the biggest question will be, which direction will NASCAR go? They came up with the testing rule to supposedly help the smaller teams compete against the larger teams that have more money to spend on testing, but the larger teams have obviously found a way around it and still be within the rules. They are not buying tires from Goodyear and they are testing at non-NASCAR sanctioned tracks, something NASCAR has no control over. They could lift the testing rules completely and allow the teams to test at any track they want, any time and use Goodyear tires. They could add more testing dates to the schedule. Or, they could become even more restrictive and make the teams sign a contract with NASCAR that they cannot test anywhere except at the NASCAR sponsored test sessions or use any other tires other than Goodyear. It's difficult to say which way NASCAR will go with this. Hopefully they'll take input from teams to see what they think and actually take what they say into consideration before making a decision. Your thoughts? How do you think NASCAR will change testing? May 31, 2007 in TrackBack URL for this entry: Listed below are links to weblogs that reference NASCAR considering changing testing rules "Kathy's Pit Stop Classic" Archives
