http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-1&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/sports/basketball/31spurs.html%3Fref%3Dsports&cid=1116539054&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Veteran Spurs Reach Final, Ending Younger Jazz&#8217;s Run - New York Times Spurs 109, Jazz 84 Veteran Spurs Reach Final, Ending Younger Jazz’s Run Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 SAN ANTONIO, May 30 — The celebration began shortly after 11 p.m. Fabricio Oberto, a relative unknown in 49 states, left the AT&T Center court to a raucous and sustained standing ovation. When the wave began circling the arena minutes later, it was clear that delirium had taken hold of the city. Skip to next paragraph Tony Parker, shooting past Deron Williams, had 21 points, including an early burst that set the tone for the Spurs. They have grown accustomed to hoisting championship banners here, and the mere anticipation of another one had fans ready to do the river dance across the Riverwalk. The Spurs crushed the , 109-94, on Wednesday to win the Western Conference finals in five games. is now four victories away from claiming his fourth championship in nine years. "It feels great to be back," Duncan said. Duncan, who led the team to titles in 1999, 2003 and 2005, was at his casually dominant best Wednesday night, with an effortless 21 points in 28 minutes. Tony Parker, a member of the last two title teams, had 21 points, including a first-quarter burst that set the tone for the night. The Spurs now have a week to prepare for either the , who are tied at two games apiece in the Eastern Conference finals. The finals open here next Thursday. Aside from a 26-point rout in Game 3, the Jazz — a team of mostly postseason neophytes — had a tough time matching the Spurs' ferocity and focus. They trailed for all 48 minutes Wednesday, falling behind by double digits in the first 8 minutes of the game. The deficit was 19 points by the second quarter. The Jazz never got closer than 16 in the second half. "They came at us really hard," Utah Coach Jerry Sloan said, "and we lost faith as far as anything we wanted to do. They destroyed our will to want to play." Deron Williams' playoff coming-out party ended with a thud. Limited by injury (a sprained foot) and foul trouble, Williams scored just 11 points and had 2 assists in 23 minutes. His pick-and-roll partner, power forward Carlos Boozer, also fizzled with the season on the line, finishing with 9 points. A pair of rising stars, Boozer and Williams also ended the night furious with their teammates. Without naming individuals, they accused some players of giving up. "It is sad to say that," Boozer said, "because where we are, we are in the Western Conference finals, and we have guys that have vacation plans." There were several possible culprits. Gordan Giricek scored just 5 points in 21 minutes, and none in the first half. Center Mehmet Okur, a key scorer all season but a no-show in this round, had 8 points and 3 rebounds. Andrei Kirilenko, the starting small forward, had 13 points and 5 rebounds. "There are definitely some guys not on the same page," Williams said. Williams spent the final 9 minutes 25 seconds of the third quarter on the bench with four fouls. Boozer was out for the final 5:06 of the period, also with four fouls. The Spurs' lead grew from 16 to 27 after Williams sat down. Despite the stakes, Sloan did not put either of his young stars back in the game until the start of the fourth quarter, with the Jazz trailing by 83-56. So Utah's surprising, occasionally thrilling playoff ride came to an end. The Jazz had not been to the playoffs in four years and were not expected to make it this far. But with Williams and Boozer developing into a dominant young tandem, Utah should be playing in May for many years to come. "We're still young and we're still learning, but that's no excuse," Williams said. "Some guys need to find where their heart's at." The Jazz was missing a key starter at tip-off — guard Derek Fisher was en route from New York, where he had taken his 11-month-old daughter for a doctor's appointment. Tatum Fisher is being treated for a rare form of cancer in her left eye. The last time Fisher made the trip to New York with Tatum, on May 9, he arrived back in Salt Lake City just in time to rally the Jazz to a victory over the Golden State Warriors in Game 2 of the conference semifinals. By the time Fisher jogged onto the court at halftime, at about 9:24 p.m. Central time, Utah trailed by 16 points. The Jazz certainly needed a jolt of inspiration, or whatever Fisher could provide. He missed his first attempt, a 3-pointer from the left side, and did not score in the third quarter. Giricek replaced Fisher in the starting lineup and went scoreless in the first half. The reserve guard Dee Brown also stepped in and scored just 1 point, as the Jazz fell behind by as many as 23 points. Parker had 11 points in the first 10 minutes of the game, matching the output of the entire Jazz starting lineup in the first quarter. Williams, who found stardom in this postseason, could not match Parker's frantic production. He had 7 points and 3 fouls in the first half. Utah, in many respects a younger, less-seasoned version of the business-like Spurs, made a strong impression in this postseason. The Spurs provided one tough lesson after another about what it takes to get to the top. "I have tremendous respect for this team, as long as they have Duncan and Popovich and those people," Sloan said before the game. "You know, they get everything going with the players they have. I thought they would be awfully difficult to play against." Next Article in Sports (6 of 27) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. All the Right Moves to Annoy the Jazz SPURS 91, JAZZ 79; Spurs Take Control as Jazz Starts to Lose It A Twosome Reminiscent of the Stockton-Malone Era JAZZ 109, SPURS 83; Jazz Proves That the Spurs Are Only Human Next Article in Sports (6 of 27) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Martha Graham and Dancers - 1990 Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
