http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-2&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/basketball/spurs-into-finals-as-jazz-fails-to-hit-right-note/2007/05/31/1180205426395.html&cid=1116539054&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Spurs into finals as Jazz fails to hit right note - Basketball - Sport Welcome to The Age. Spurs into finals as Jazz fails to hit right note San Antonio Spurs guard Tony Parker drives past Utah Jazz forward Andrei Kirilenko during the first half of their NBA clash. THE San Antonio Spurs have advanced to the NBA finals with a crushing 109-84 victory over the Utah Jazz. Tim Duncan and Tony Parker each scored 21 points, helping the Spurs clinch the Western Conference series 4-1 at San Antonio and book a place in the NBA finals for the third time in five seasons. The Spurs will play either the Detroit Pistons or the Cleveland Cavaliers in the finals, which start on June 7 in San Antonio. The Pistons and Cavaliers are tied 2-2 in the eastern conference finals. San Antonio was leading Utah 16-11 in the first period when they embarked on a streak that set the tone for the game. Parker scored seven consecutive points to push the advantage to 23-11. Bruce Bowen connected on a three-pointer before Parker drove for another basket and in less than three minutes, the Spurs had a 19-point lead. "Tonight we played great, everybody from the starting five, from the bench, everybody made shots," Parker said. "I think we won that game in the first quarter, and we kept the lead the whole game." The Spurs, who have defeated the Jazz 19 consecutive times in San Antonio, led 34-15 after the first quarter and 55-39 at the half. That advantage grew to 83-56 going into the fourth. Andrei Kirilenko led the Jazz with 13 points. Deron Williams, who played with a sprained left foot, and Matt Harpring had 11 each. Carlos Boozer was held to nine points and 12 rebounds. Guard Derek Fisher missed the first half while returning from New York, where is daughter is being treated for an eye condition. He was 0-3 from the floor. The finals will be the Spurs' fourth appearance in nine seasons. They won the NBA title in 1999, 2003 and 2005, but lost in the second round of the 2004 play-offs and the western conference semi-finals in 2006. They have seven days to prepare for another tilt at the title. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! Spurs into finals as Jazz fails to hit right note San Antonio Spurs guard Tony Parker drives past Utah Jazz forward Andrei Kirilenko during the first half of their NBA clash. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Simoni wins mountain stage, Di Luca keeps lead No way, Jose &#151; didgeridoo man had wrong Telstra New series on track, says chief 'Betrayed' mum pays out on Lion Notting Ducks take early lead over Senators in final Swifts unlikely to repeat French connection We're to blame for rule change &#151; ex-ump Russo All-rounder Ron Archer a precocious talent all round Eye for an eye &#151; $9344 plunge now in limbo California doesn't give flying Ducks too much thought Flying Phoenix demolishes weary Swifts Loren lands in Oz Fans greet movie legend with flowers as she arrives for a film festival. Britney's ex to fund own second album and star opposite Keanu Reeves. Who gave Lohan alcohol? Officials ponder whether Lindsay Lohan, who is underage, was served alcohol in LA bars. Lock up the crackberry? Unique (and extreme) ways to get away from work for the hols. ALL MEN ARE LIARS Is this the only way to give up smoking? Weapons of seduction - II SAM AND THE CITY TV How far would you go to get laid? Sleepless world record attempt amusingly goes wrong. TODAY'S TOP 10 ARTICLES Big-spending mayor goes for broke TV news boss to spend weekends in jail Beware the psycho boss, the new enemy within Icy blast heralds winter Dr Karl's IR prescription? Man bites, and chews, dog in 