http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-2&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html%3Fid%3D16a0d071-46da-43cc-9097-7f04336ea606%26k%3D10210&cid=1116768880&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Bettman 'Pegs interest in Canada canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter canada.com where perspectives connect in The Vancouver Sun Jobs in Vancouver working.com 10 year archive in FPinfomart See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter Road to 2010 Olympics Find a job at working.com Find a car at driving.ca Find an apartment at renting.ca Find real estate at homes Find great stuff at shopping Selling? Place an ad Meet a match at Connecting Headlines marked with a are exclusive to subscribers. Update credit card information Send us a news tip B.C.'s 'luckiest' lotto retailers Six retailers across the province have won more than $500,000 apiece playing the... Teachers from B.C. muzzled in China B.C.'s greenhouse gases drop as the economy booms The Vancouver man who 'owns the Internet' Schwarzenegger, Campbell to sign green agreement No prescription needed for contraceptive pill (9:06 am) Bettman 'Pegs interest in Canada NHL commissioner 'intrigued' by more Canadian teams By Cam Cole, Vancouver Sun Published:Â Tuesday, May 29, 2007 ANAHEIM, Calif. - The U.S. television package isn't perfect, Rick Tocchet may or may not be welcomed back to the National Hockey League after paying his debt to society for his involvement in a gambling ring, and Nashville's corporate community - not the fan base - is to blame for the plight of the teetering Predators franchise. But of all the hot-button topics addressed by NHL commissioner Gary Bettman at his annual Stanley Cup state-of-the-league session Monday, by far the most intriguing was his admission that he is ... well, "intrigued" by the possibility of more Canadian franchises in the future. Specifically, his reference to Winnipeg - a clear softening of his previous position on the Manitoba capital, which the NHL abandoned in 1996 - sounded very much like an invitation to get serious. NHL commissioner Gary Bettman speaks at a news conference Monday in Anaheim, Calif. Email to a friend "I am intrigued in the sense that I don't like franchise relocation - I think my record on that is clear to everyone in this room," Bettman said, two hours before Game 1 of the Stanley Cup final commenced at the Honda Center. "So, for example, when we had a chance to go back to Minnesota, we did because it made sense: the right ownership, the right building situation, the market was strong and vibrant. We haven't studied Quebec City or Winnipeg or anywhere else in Canada, but the notion of putting a franchise back in a place where one was lost feels good ... provided we don't end up in a situation where we've created a prescription for another failing franchise." Most of the speculation about BlackBerry founder and billionaire Jim Balsillie's pending purchase of the struggling Nashville franchise - which still hasn't received NHL approval - has been that he intends to move the team as soon as possible, and the guess is that Kitchener-Waterloo, Ont., which has no suitable building at the moment, would be his preferred location. Or if not there, somewhere in southern Ontario. But there is also movement afoot to convince the NHL that there is now viable ownership in Winnipeg, though that would likely have to involve a partnership of the Asper family, which has the money if it has the desire to spend it, with the current owner of the Manitoba Moose, Mark Chipman, who controls the new MTS Centre. Bettman referenced an editorial in Monday's National Post (owned by CanWest Global Communications Corp. which is controlled by the Aspers) in which it was suggested that if relocation to a city in Canada is being considered, the NHL owes it to Winnipeg. "It's obviously something I've thought about, to try to make right something that at one point in our history went wrong," said Bettman. "Now, we left Quebec City and Winnipeg because there was no new building, no prospect of a new building and no one wanted to own the teams there." However, he said, "we've been getting lots of expressions of interest." As for Kitchener or Hamilton or ... "I was talking about cities we left. That's where the intriguing notion comes from," Bettman said. "I haven't given a thought to anywhere else." The parameters for a team in Canada have changed since the '90s, Bettman said, "because with the [salary cap] partnership we have with players, and the revenue sharing, while it's something we haven't studied, it seems to me more likely than it was three-four-five years ago." Â© Vancouver Sun 2007 John Mayer acts out a bizarre ... Privacy czar warns web users to be wary Students cruising online networking... Deaths may be linked to diabetes drug Health Canada says the deaths ... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
