http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-0&fd=R&url=http://www.hoopsworld.com/article_22150.shtml&cid=1116735035&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Beer: Kobe Beef | HOOPSWORLD.com | NBA News and Information | powered by Basketball News Services May 31st, 2007 - 08:51:54 May 31, 2007, 01:30 Break up to make up that's all we do First you love me then you hate me That's a game for fools When I come home from workin', you're on the phone Talkin' about how bad I treat you, now tell me I'm wrong You say it's me who argues, I'll say it's you We have got to get together or baby, we're through Break up to make up, that's all we do First you love me then you hate me That's a game for fools - "Break Up To Make Up" Welcome to the Real World: Los Angeles. Try as they might, even MTV wouldn't dare create a reality show plotline similar to what transpired over the radio airwaves Wednesday afternoon. Nobody would buy it. First Kobe and the Lakers are broken up. Then they are back together. Then they are back on the rocks. What's next? Will Kobe be on the front page of tomorrow morning's New York Post canoodling with Jerry West? By the time this article gets posted, who knows whether Kobe will be flirting with Jerry Buss, or fighting with Mitch Kupchak. He might be batting his eyes at Phil Jackson, or threatening to blacken the eye of a certain "Laker insider." Either which way, one thing seems fairly certain: Kobe Bryant will remain a member of the Los Angeles Lakers for at least two more seasons. The Lakers are simply not going to trade him. They have no reason or motivation to do so. And Kobe has 88.6 million reasons to honor his contract. The Laker organization would never even consider such a drastic move unless Kobe flat-out refused to play the 2007-2008 season in a purple and gold uniform. At the end of the day, money talks, and we know what walks. (Besides, they never call traveling in the NBA). And from the Lakers perspective, it would be fiscally irresponsible to trade the most marketable player in the NBA. Kobe's jersey was once again the NBA's top-seller this year; his #24 even outsold Yao Ming’s jersey in China The Lakers charge a king's ransom for their overpriced seats and the reason then can get away with it is due in large part to Kobe Bryant's star power. You think Jack Nicholson and Denzel Washington are showing up if Kobe Bean Bryant isn't in the building. Fat chance. Last time I checked, there were a few other entertainment options in and around LA. Kobe has proven he can do no wrong in certain fan's eyes; he has a die-hard contingent of supporters that will cheer for him no matter what. That fact has already been established. Thus, as of 12:20 pm EST Wednesday afternoon, I would have bet my co-op that Jerry Buss and the Lakers would never, ever trade Kobe. Then, however, I heard Mr. Bryant's interview with Screamin' A. Smith on ESPN Radio in New York. Kobe was in full-out attack mode. It was as if he caught Raja Bell hitting on his wife or found out one of his teammates was thinking about taking a last-second shot. Kobe was incensed. He lambasted the Lakers front-office, insinuating that he had been lied to, deceived, hood-winked, and bamboozled. (All this from an organization that pays him $20 million a season to play hoops and stood by him during the infamous Colorado incident.) It appeared Kobe was putting his foot down. He was mad as hell and he wasn't going to take it anymore. Claiming that there was "no other alternative," Kobe demanded the Lakers trade him. And whether you consider it a positive or a negative character trait, we all know that Kobe is extremely determined, pig-headed even, when he sets his mind on something. The Black Mamba was spitting venom. Would he be stubborn enough to force a trade from the LA? For the next hour, cell-phones were blowing up from coast to coast. (I bet if Sprint and Nextel operators could have tracked the cell-phone records of those people who subscribe to the NBA League Pass, they would have thought it was midnight on New Year's Eve.) "Dude, did you hear Kobe?" "Did he really say that?" Followed by the inevitable, "Yo, can we get him? What would we have to give up?" The basketball universe was spinning off its axis. Text-messages were being fired off at a record rate. Microsoft Outlook inboxes in cubicles across America were inundated with all sorts of trade proposals. Kobe sounded like he had made up his mind. His days in LA were done. What was going to happen next? Alas, it only lasted a few hours. Before you knew it, before we even had a chance to think about the possibility of him landing in Boston or Chicago, Kobe was on Dan Patrick back-peddling faster than Carmelo Anthony in Madison Square Garden. "I just hope and hope that something can be resolved. Something can be figured out. Just something so I can stay here and be in this city and be with the team I love," Kobe told Dan Patrick. Bryant explained that Phil Jackson had reached out to him and assuaged his fears. (Why do I have a strange feeling that his agent placed a call as well?) Next on the make-up tour was AM 570 KLAC, where KB24 continued to profess his undying love for the Lakers organization. What a shame, couldn't he have at least waited a day before they kissed and making up? Give writers, fans, bloggers, and talk-radio hosts at least 24 hours to dissect trades that would never happen. What a drag - I had a beauty that would have landed Kobe in a Knicks uniform (Curry, Crawford, and Frye for Bryant - yes, the salaries match-up).... Nope, it just wasn't meant to be. Did Kobe really want to be traded, or did he just want to have his ego massaged? By 6 pm, Kobe was back in the good graces of the Laker family. The lovers quarrel had been amicably settled. The irreconcilable differences had been resolved. Kobe was ready to say "I do" all over again. And to think, Jerry Buss didn't even have to buy him a $4 million ring?!?! Kobe should have held out for more, he could at least have gotten Buss and Kupchak to use the full mid-level exception this summer... Tommy Beer is a senior writer and NBA analyst for Basketball News, which powers Hoopsworld.com and SWISH magazine. He has appeared as a guest on ESPN Radio and SIRIUS Satellite's NBA Radio - Channel 127. Gotta Response? E-mail It Here San Antonio Spurs tickets New Jersey Nets tickets NBA Scores & Matchups has the best prices on: NBA Basketball tickets and NBA All Star game tickets your #1 source for New York Knicks Tickets
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/6868094&cid=1116812502&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ FOX Sports on MSN - MLB - Baseball should be thanking A-Rod &#187; JT The Brick &#187; Shawn P. Roarke &#187; Michael David Smith &#187; FOX NFL Sunday &#187; BDSSP Las Vegas Insider Baseball should be thanking A-Rod Posted: 3 hours ago Thank god for A-Rod, or, as he has now been rechristened, Stray-Rod. What would this dismal Yankee season be without him? Think the A-Rod scandal is bad? doesn't. He says it's good for a laugh and good for the pitiful Yankees. What do you think? The big city tabloid may be an antiquated form of journalism, but it endures, in part, as a purveyor of guilty pleasures. And so I set out for my local newsstand, another institution perilously close to obsolescence, and gave the guy two bucks plus tax for the national edition of the That boldly hyphenated construction &#151; the aforementioned "Stray-Rod" &#151; spoke of a headline writer at the top of his (or her) game. The front page promised that highest form of tabloid life, a mystery blonde. Unlike Buttafuocos or Trumps, the mystery blonde does not fall from fashion &#151; and this particular one was good as advertised. Not only did the shade of her locks approach platinum, but she seemed very well nourished in the thoracic region. Every tale has its ideal medium, and no doubt this was best suited for print. A story like this warrants getting your fingers a little grimy. According to the Rodriguez &#151; married father of a 2-year-old daughter &#151; and the mystery blonde went to a Toronto strip club called "The Brass Rail." They stayed there for an hour or so, then returned to the Four Seasons, where they were last seen getting into the same elevator. There is no official word yet whether the mystery blonde has been improperly enhanced by an artificial substance. Though buxom blondes are part of, shall we say, the fabric of the game, they are not subject to routine testing. Still, before you dismiss this mystery blonde as a mere bimbo, consider that she may yet be to the A-Rod allegory what Bernard Malamud's temptress was to The Natural. says this is just the sort of distraction the Yankees need. Even in the halcyon halls of FOXSports.com the news has met with some resistance. Some of my colleagues don't think it's a story at all. Well, we might argue about propriety or taste. My own notion of decorum causes me to refrain from judging the third baseman, as that task belongs to Mrs. A-Rod. Let him pay for his sins, whatever they might be, in couples therapy. That should be deterrent enough. Let me also admit that the front page injures my argument that A-Rod is a warm and cuddly alternative to Barry Bonds. But please, don't tell me it's not a story. I mean, how invincibly stupid is this guy? Besides, this is all very funny. You know it is. If you can't chuckle holding that newspaper, you don't have a pulse. And by that measure, baseball owes a debt of gratitude to Alex Rodriguez. He did what he could for his team, knocking all those homers in April. Still, at this writing, the $200 million Yankees are 14 1/2 games behind the Red Sox. This is bad for the game. It's not just Yankee fans who need the Yankees to be good. It's the rest of the country, too. The Yankees should be worthy of contempt, not pity. But news of their latest failure seems to lead the nightly highlight shows. Pathetic. Those tight shots of Joe Torre &#151; forced to explain yet another loss &#151; make him seem downright Nixonian. Then there's Brian Cashman, as dour as Kissinger in the Final Days. Even Steinbrenner fails to entertain. He is quoted as saying something about winning and competing, and it recalls the end of the "Wizard of Oz." I fear someone will pull back the curtain in the Tampa headquarters and find that Steinbrenner is long gone, replaced by his megaphone-wielding publicist, Howard Rubenstein. It's sad is what it is. So let's treat this scoop with the perspective it deserves. A-Rod does not yet rank in the pantheon of Yankee heroes, with legendary debauchers like Ruth, DiMaggio and Mantle. But at least he offers some respite from a relentlessly dreary Yankee season. Besides, as everybody knows, when a team is slumping you need to change things up. Shuffle the order, as it were. That said, maybe Joe Torre should get a mystery blonde of his own. Mark Kriegel is a national columnist for FOXSports.com. He is the author of Pistol: The Life of Pete Maravich , both New York Times bestsellers. He also was an award-winning sports columnist at the New York Post and the New York Daily News. Baseball should be thanking A-Rod Spurs teach Playoff Basketball 101 No fooling around: Spurs oust Jazz with rout Kobe asks for trade, then backs off his demand Hewitt rallies at French Open Pahlsson's goal gives Ducks 2-0 lead on Sens Bobcats hire Warriors' Higgins to be GM Blue Jays call A-Rod play "bush league" Derby winner Street Sense skipping Belmont Wie withdraws from Ginn after 16 holes Recent Articles by Mark Kriegel Baseball should be thanking A-Rod On the Mark: The Kobe Rules Selig should take his cue from Goodell Baseball should be thanking A-Rod Easy to explain why Russell rates Stats 101: What makes the Sox tick? Blue Jays call A-Rod play "bush league" Cashman denies Torre rift Big Unit bests Moyer in return from injury Cards snap Rockies' seven-game win streak Smoltz fine after throwing Bonds mum on HRs Blue Jays activate Halladay for start Thursday Twins walk way to sweep Dibble and Kennedy talk AL Skip and Dibs talk NL Shop for more MLB fan gear Join Our Opinion Panel Other Fox Sites >> &copy; 2007 Fox Sports Interactive Media, LLC. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.cbc.ca/cp/hockey/070528/h052817A.html&cid=1116768880&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Gary Bettman "intrigued" with idea of NHL returning to Winnipeg Gary Bettman "intrigued" with idea of NHL returning to Winnipeg Published: Monday, May 28, 2007 | 8:06 PM ET Canadian Press: PIERRE LEBRUN ANAHEIM, Calif. (CP) - NHL commissioner Gary Bettman gave his strongest indication yet Monday that having a team return to Winnipeg could happen one day. Bettman, in his state-of-the union address to the media before Game 1 of the Stanley Cup final, referred to an editorial in a Canadian newspaper he read this week which suggested that if the NHL did add another Canadian team it should go back to Winnipeg first because they have a new building and the NHL owes it to them. "I'm not opining on whether or not that's an opinion that I agree with, but it is an interesting and intriguing thought," Bettman said in a comment that raised eyebrows. While he stressed that there really hadn't been that much thought put into it at this point and that he had no plans for any current NHL teams to re-locate or for the league to expand, he does see the chance for Winnipeg to get a team back one day. "When we had the chance to go back to Minnesota, we did. Because it made sense, the right ownership, the right building situation," said Bettman. "The market was strong and vibrant. We haven't studied Quebec City or Winnipeg or anywhere else in Canada, but the notion that if it could work to put a franchise back in a place where one was lost, feels good - provided we don't wind up in a situation where we've created a prescription for another failing franchise. "So am I intrigued? It's obviously something I've thought about in terms of trying to make right something that one point in our history went wrong." The Jets left Winnipeg for Phoenix after the 1995-96 season. Bettman believes the salary cap and revenue sharing facets of the new collective bargaining agreement provides a chance for a market like Winnipeg to make a go of it. But another team in Toronto? Bettman is not a fan of that idea, despite the fact there are three clubs in the New York/New Jersey area and two teams here in Southern California. "It's not something I've given any thought to," Bettman said of having another team in Toronto. "... I frankly think, and I live in the New York/New Jersey metropolitan area, it's tough for all the clubs to get media attention, particularly when they're having tough years on the ice. "There's some real downside to having multiple teams in one market." The message seems clear from the commissioner: if Jim Balsillie wants to move the Nashville Predators, the NHL would rather have them move to Winnipeg than Waterloo, Ont., the home of the Research In Motion CEO. But Bettman also said too many people are wrongly assuming the Predators will move. "I met with Mr. Balsillie last week and I specifically asked him whether or not he had specific plans or intentions with respect to moving this franchise and he told me that he did not," said Bettman. "So I think there's been entirely too much speculation in terms of what comes next." Balsillie's purchase of the Predators still needs owners' approval, a vote that could come later in June. -Rick Tocchet, who last Friday in New Jersey pleaded guilty to promoting gambling and conspiracy to promote gambling in a plea deal. He has been suspended by the NHL from his job as Phoenix Coyotes assistant coach since the investigation opened in February 2006. The NHL is also still doing its own investigation. "I'm not really in a position to say what's going to happen until there's a complete disposition of his case and until our independent investigator has had an opportunity to interview him, finish interviewing some other people, and then present his report," said Bettman. "At that point I'll be able to make a determination in terms of what his status should or should not be."