http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-4&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/30/AR2007053002527.html&cid=1116377593&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Racetracks Will Keep Better Data On Horse Injuries - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Racetracks Will Keep Better Data On Horse Injuries Thursday, May 31, 2007; Page E02 A pilot program to create comprehensive statistics for on-track breakdowns of thoroughbreds will begin tomorrow, the Jockey Club announced. Thirty-two North American tracks, including Laurel Park and Pimlico, are set to participate in the program, developed by , a veterinarian working at Calder Race Course and Gulfstream Park in Florida. The project will standardize the reporting of racing injuries, creating a centralized database that will help identify patterns in where horses break down most frequently, which injuries are most common, in what conditions and other parameters. storms from behind to catch Street Sense at the wire to win the 132nd Preakness Stakes. &raquo; Despite his lack of experience and a stumble out of the gate, Curlin submits a brilliant, stunning performance. is calm and cool after earlier admitting he was "heartbroken" at Street Sense's defeat. Mending Fences suffers a fracture and has to be euthanized. Dan Steinberg loses his shirt at the Preakness. looks to ride Derby runner-up Hard Spun to a Preakness victory. wins a thrilling Black-Eyed Susan Stakes. A year later, memories of still resonate at the Preakness. roars from next-to-last in a 20-horse field to win the 133rd Kentucky Derby. Again, the Crown Doesn't Fit Street Sense is the third straight Kentucky Derby champion not to win the Preakness. Six of the past 11, and 10 since Affirmed in 1978, had a shot at becoming the 12th Triple Crown winner. How the last 11 Derby winners fared in Baltimore: (in order of post position) King of the Roxy triumphed at last year's Preakness but his victory was marred by the injury suffered by Derby winner Barbaro. Save & Share Article "There is no such thing as an acceptable rate of injury, but until we are able to document injury rates, trends and outcomes -- and figure out where we are -- it is hard to figure out how to get to where we want to be," Scollay said in a news release yesterday. The program was developed last fall at the Grayson-Jockey Club Research Foundation-backed Welfare and Safety of the Racehorse Summit. The breakdown of Kentucky Derby winner in the Preakness Stakes last May, and the subsequent public anguish over the fatal injury, drove the program forward. "When that happened, the industry was at a loss to be able to answer the question, 'How frequent are injuries?' " , president of the Grayson-Jockey Club Research Foundation, told the Associated Press. "A lot of people took it as kind of an embarrassment that this industry can't answer that simple question." The information will be released only to state veterinarians to share with racetrack executives. "It is not my intention to allow this database to be used to point fingers and say, 'Your track is bad, your track is good, your track is worse than someone else,' " Scollay told the AP. "That's not constructive." The Maryland Jockey Club, which operates Laurel Park and Pimlico, initially was not reported to be among those involved with the program, but the Maryland tracks have signed on, said racing secretary "It's going to give us a lot of stats on what kind of injuries on what kinds of tracks, how often the horses ran -- the form has every little detail on it," Hale said. "I e-mailed [Scollay] today and said, 'Look, I assumed we were in on this and we're not on the list.' She wrote back, 'No problem,' so we're good." Before the advent of the new program, Maryland Racing Commission veterinarian compiled his own records and then shared them with the state tracks at the end of the year. Serena caught napping again before easing t