http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-4&fd=R&url=http://www.sportinglife.com/others/news/story_get.cgi%3FSTORY_NAME%3Dothers/07/05/31/manual_084000.html&cid=1116539054&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ SAN ANTONIO EASE THROUGH TO FINALS: Sporting Life | MotoGP, World Rally Championship, World Superbikes, Athletics, Swimming, Rallying, Sports News, Live Scores, Betting and More Carlos Boozer and Tim Duncan in action. SAN ANTONIO EASE THROUGH TO FINALS Subscribe to RSS Feed The San Antonio Spurs clinched a spot in the NBA Finals with a 109-84 drubbing of the Utah Jazz, to win the Western Conference finals series 4-1. San Antonio - who led by 29 at one stage in the game - never trailed in the game, and thanks to a first quarter in which they pounded the Jazz 34-15, they always looked comfortable. "Our first quarter was unbelievable," said Spurs star Tony Parker, "I can't remember, since I've been with the Spurs, shooting the ball like that. Our offense was great, our defense was great. You can't ask for a better start." Parker and Tim Duncan scored 21 points each in the victory, while Manu Ginobili was once again the star from the bench, netting 12. The Spurs defence showed their own kind of spirit, limiting Utah's Carlos Boozer to just nine points, and strike partner Deron Williams to a mere 11. Boozer, however, did manage to get in double figures in the rebounds department with 12. Andrei Kirilenko was Utah's top scorer with 13 points, while Matt Harpring also put up 11. "They came at us really hard," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. "They destroyed our will to want to play. That was the whole thing. We abandoned our offense right away. And we never could get back into it the rest of the night. They put us where they wanted us all night long." The first game of the NBA Finals begins next Thursday in San Antonio. Click here to send us your sporting feedback Latest Other Sports Stories AUSSIE COACH TO DISCUSS BRITISH ROLE PRESSURE GROWS AT TT - McGUINNESS BARLOWORLD GETS TO