http://www.mercurynews.com/sportsheadlines/ci_6024850&cid San Jose Mercury News - Fans rant, but Zito quiets Mets' bats and the Giants win san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals Fans rant, but Zito quiets Mets' bats and the Giants win Article Launched: 05/30/2007 09:35:51 PM PDT Giants fan blog: Zito pitches great, but wasn't it great to see someone else close out a game? NEW YORK - Barry Zito was the highest profile free agent pitcher on the market this winter, the New York Mets had a glaring need in their rotation, and their fans are used to getting spendy gifts at Christmas. Maybe that's why Mets fans showered Zito with colorful language while the Giants left-hander warmed up in the Shea Stadium bullpen Wednesday night. "It's always great coming to New York," Zito said. "You get all those trash talkers saying everything they can think of. That's what makes this place special." Zito showed them what they're missing. He held the high-powered Mets lineup scoreless over seven innings and struck out a season-high seven batters in a 3-0 victory at Flushing Meadows. The Mets hadn't been shut out this season. It was an important bounce-back victory for the Giants, who lost in 12 innings Tuesday night when Armando Benitez had a balk-a-thon on the mound. Brad Hennessey became the closer Wednesday because Benitez had an inflamed right knee. It was an important prove-it start for Zito, especially after anonymous Mets officials chirped about his tame fastball and decried the &#36;126 million the Giants showered upon him. "You know, I don't really want to pitch with any kind of vendetta against people," Zito said. "For me, it's just about being aggressive, throwing strikes and hoping for the best." Zito's 84 mph fastball worked just fine because he spotted it on the corners and dropped in both varieties of his breaking ball for strikes. He walked only one batter and he gave the Giants innings on a day they needed to go light on their bullpen. Since walking seven in his May 18 loss at Oakland, Zito is 2-0 and has issued just three walks over 14 innings. "A lot was said about him pitching here, but we needed it," Giants Manager Bruce Bochy said. "He can pitch. He'll throw a lot of great back-to-back games. That's why we got him. He showed what he's about tonight." Zito had a good support network behind him. Pedro Feliz hit a two-out, two-run single off Tom Glavine in the first inning and lined an RBI triple in the third. Bengie Molina worked an eight-pitch walk in the first to extend the rally; Molina also singled on a lengthy at-bat ahead of Feliz's triple. Shortstop Omar Vizquel was 0 for 4 but contributed an assortment of highlight plays, including bare-handed pickups to throw out Endy Chavez in the first and Damion Easley in the fourth. And Rich Aurilia broke out of a 5-for-51 slump by tying his career high with four hits. Aurilia, whose stiff neck is coming around, said he made adjustments after teammates noticed a flaw in his approach. Barry Bonds singled and scored in the first inning but otherwise had a quiet 1-for-3 night with an intentional walk. Bonds was just as nondescript before the game, when he relented to the New York media throng and repeated his non-thoughts on the home run record, Bud Selig and Hank Aaron. After the game, the cameras and reporters awaited the other Barry. New York might be special, but it's not easy being a visible baseball star here. You needed only to look at the cover of Wednesday's New York Post, which splashed photos of Yankees star Alex Rodriguez getting into a hotel elevator with a blond woman who wasn't his wife. The headlines were "Stray-Rod" and "A-Rod's A Yankee Doodle Randy." The fans in the outfield at Shea weren't nearly as clever. "Nah, not creative at all," Zito said. "Just blatant expletives right at me." Contact Andrew Baggarly at abaggarly@mercurynews.com The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Sorry, no items are currently available. Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/wires/ap/sports/7751472.html&cid=1116821771&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ NASCAR Might Relax Testing Policy | AP | 05/30/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Thursday, May 31, 2007 Posted on Wed, May. 30, 2007 NASCAR Might Relax Testing Policy Casey Mears leads a group during the Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR Nextel Cup Series auto race at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., Sunday, May 27, 2007. (AP Photo/Terry Renna) CHARLOTTE, N.C. - NASCAR is considering opening up its restrictive testing policy, which several teams already have skirted this season. Currently, rules limit teams to seven tests on Nextel Cup-sanctioned tracks, and crew chiefs help NASCAR decide the venues and dates. NASCAR adopted that policy two years ago to help underfunded teams keep up with big-budget organizations, who could afford to test anytime. But as the Car of Tomorrow was rolled into competition, the top teams found ways to test it outside of the rules. "It appears that we've got teams that want to test more and teams that want to test less, and teams that test on tires that are not made by our tire supplier," Robin Pemberton, NASCAR vice president of competition, told The Associated Press on Wednesday. "So we're going to start looking at a lot of different things, from eventually lifting the test ban completely, or get as restrictive as we cannot let teams test anywhere at any time, or land somewhere in between." NASCAR most likely will relax the restrictions, because it's having a hard time policing teams. More than 20 teams tested Tuesday and Wednesday at Virginia International Raceway, a road course where they could simulate the June 24 race in Sonoma, Calif. Because VIR is not a sanctioned track, any team can go there and still be within NASCAR's guidelines. But teams can't use current Goodyear tires because of a leasing agreement intended to prevent extracurricular testing. To circumvent the lack of available tires, teams have started using other manufacturers for test sessions. They also snapped up much of Goodyear's inventory from 2005 and earlier. Goodyear officials declined a request from The Associated Press for comment Wednesday, and NASCAR said the teams have not technically broken the rules. Hendrick Motorsports, winners of nine of the first 12 races this season, is believed to have lapped the field in testing this year. Team officials said they've used a variety of test drivers about 30 times this year, and rival car owner Jack Roush said that's unfair. He said his own five-car team is behind the competition, because he didn't purchase tires from Hoosier or B.F. Goodrich for tests. "The teams that have been successful ... they've gone to tracks outside NASCAR's control with tires that were not from Goodyear," Roush said. "Right now, Goodyear is sitting on millions of dollars worth of tires that are growing obsolete and hard in their warehouses. Teams have gotten around NASCAR's policy by buying other people's tires and testing at tracks that aren't on the Nextel Cup schedule. "I got behind on that. I didn't do that." But using tires other than what Goodyear provides on race day is a crapshoot, many crew chiefs said. "Relaxing the testing policy only makes sense if we can use current Goodyears," said Mike Ford, crew chief for Denny Hamlin. "You can really end up going pretty far down the wrong road that way, but you have no choice because everyone is doing it." Hamlin tested at VIR on "some really old Goodyears," but Ford said it was only the second time this season the No. 11 team has gone outside a NASCAR-sanctioned test. Joe Gibbs Racing's research and development team has tested cars at various times independent of Hamlin's team this year. Ford said he believes NASCAR's prohibitive policy created the testing problems. "They are forcing teams to spend money with other tire manufacturers instead of with Goodyear, the company NASCAR supports," he said. "One way or the other, everybody is going to test." Updated 12:00 PM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Time served, deportation for groping on a plane Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' At adult recess, workers kick up heels and bond Don&#0039;t have a cow over the calves; he&#0039;s a burner Eagles&#0039; Abiamiri a confident pick Updated 12:00 PM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' Monica Yant Kinney | Haddonfield teens going to extremes N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers At adult recess, workers kick up heels and bond Latest Stories in this Section Sorenstam's Back - Literally This Time NFL Veterans Seek Help for Dementia 'Stray-Rod?' Tabloid Pounces on A-Rod Kobe Demands, Retracts Trade Request Is Mickelson Ready to Challenge Woods? Report: Vick Linked to Dogfighting Michelle Wie Withdraws From Ginn Tribute Lakers' Bryant Backs Off Trade Request 05/30/2007 11:18 PM EDT 'Stray-Rod?' Tabloid Pounces on A-Rod 05/30/2007 10:13 PM EDT Milwaukee Mile Sentimental to Hornish 05/30/2007 08:05 PM EDT Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
