 date 5-27-07 Saving Fuel by Changing Attitudes, first air date 5-20-07 Take a U.P. Vacation, first air date 5-13-07 Invest in the U.P. (Local Products), first air date 5-6-07 Single Business Tax, first air date 4-30-07 Replacing the Single Business Tax, first air date 4-29-07 Roadside Garbage, first air date 4-22-07 The State of the State, first air date 4-15-07 Guest Editorial, first air date 4-8-07 Associated Press - May 31, 2007 11:33 AM ET NEW YORK (AP) - Ticket scalping may soon be fully legal in New York state. A bill to toss out most rules against re-selling tickets is moving through the legislature, and could be signed by Governor Eliot Spitzer as early as tomorrow. Under the bill, average fans could scalp tickets on the Internet for whatever the market will bear. They could also sell at the venue, but not within certain distances. The change in attitude in New York and other states has been driven by the explosion in Internet ticket sales, and the realization of some sports and entertainment companies that they could profit as well. Russ Haven of the New York Public Interest Research Group worries that large-volume brokers will snap up available seats, then jack up prices. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Employee of the Month Pride Of The U.P. Photos All content &copy; Copyright 2000 - 2007 WorldNow and WLUC, a All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/wires/ap/need_to_map/7756732.html&cid=1116827440&ei=j_1eRoSRLouUrgO3usjSDQ Zito Outpitches Glavine As Giants Win | AP | 05/30/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Thursday, May 31, 2007 Posted on Wed, May. 30, 2007 Zito Outpitches Glavine As Giants Win San Francisco Giants pitcher Barry Zito delivers against the New York Mets during the first inning in Major League Baseball action Wednesday, May 30, 2007 at Shea Stadium in New York. (AP Photo/Julie Jacobson) NEW YORK - Barry Zito outpitched Tom Glavine over seven sharp innings and the San Francisco Giants beat the New York Mets 3-0 Wednesday night to snap a four-game losing streak. Pedro Feliz drove in three runs and Rich Aurilia tied a career high with four hits for the Giants, who bounced back from a difficult loss in the series opener against New York. The Mets won 5-4 in 12 innings Tuesday night when Armando Benitez balked in the tying run and surrendered a game-ending homer to Carlos Delgado. Paul Lo Duca had two hits for New York, which had won four straight. Glavine went seven innings but was denied in his second attempt at career win No. 296. Lo Duca led off the seventh with a double for his 1,000th career hit but Zito retired the next three batters, striking out pinch-hitter Julio Franco to end the inning. Zito (5-5) turned in his second consecutive strong outing after struggling in back-to-back starts earlier this month. He gave up 13 runs and 12 hits in 10 innings in outings at Colorado and Oakland, then allowed one run in seven innings in a win over Houston in his last start. He struck out a season-high seven against the Mets, holding them to six hits and one walk. Jack Taschner tossed a perfect eighth and Brad Hennessey got three outs for his second save. Barry Bonds returned to the lineup for the Giants, went 1-for-3 with a walk and remains 10 shy of breaking Hank Aaron's career record of 755 homers. He was booed lustily each time he came to the plate. Bonds entered with a .329 batting average and four homers in 100 career plate appearances against Glavine, according to the Elias Sports Bureau. He hit a two-out single to center against him in the first inning to put runners on first and second. After Bengie Molina walked, Feliz grounded a two-run single into left field. Bonds bounced into a double play in the third before Molina singled to right to extend his hitting streak to 11 games. Feliz then tripled off the wall in right-center to make it 3-0. Glavine (5-3) intentionally walked Bonds in the fifth and got him to groundout to first to end the seventh on his 122nd and final pitch of the game. He allowed nine hits, walked two and struck out four. Mets reliever Guillermo Mota was activated after serving the 50th and final day of his suspension for testing positive for a performance-enhancing substance. He relieved Glavine to start the eighth and received a mixed reaction of boos and cheers from the home crowd. Notes:@ Giants SS Omar Vizquel made two slick, barehanded plays in the first four innings. ... The Mets optioned RHP Ambiorix Burgos to Triple-A New Orleans to make room for Mota on the roster. Updated 4:00 AM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Time served, deportation for groping on a plane Eagles&#0039; Abiamiri a confident pick Two: Had drinks, woke being raped N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers Updated 4:00 AM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers Monica Yant Kinney | Haddonfield teens going to extremes Teamsters still foaming over ejection by brewer Yuengling Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' Latest Stories in this Section A-Rod, 