http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-2&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/05/sports/basketball/05donovan.html%3Fref%3Dsports&cid=1116633459&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Donovan Has Second Thoughts About Leaving Florida - New York Times Donovan Has Second Thoughts About Leaving Florida Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: June 5, 2007 Billy Donovan, who left the last week and agreed to a five-year, $27.5 million deal to coach the , is having second thoughts about the move, the Magic said in a statement Monday. Skip to next paragraph Magic officials went to Gainesville, Fla., to try to persuade Donovan to honor his commitment, but it appeared that a breakup was inevitable just three days after he decided to jump to the N.B.A. “While Central Florida, the Orlando Magic and Billy were energized with the announcement of his contract signing on Friday, we know there was a different feeling in Gainesville and people have been tugging at him since that time,” the Magic statement said. “Billy is conflicted with those emotions and the opportunity he has ahead in Orlando and in the NBA.” Florida’s athletic director, Jeremy Foley, declined to comment to The Orlando Sentinel on Monday morning at a University Athletic Association meeting. Foley flew to Richmond, Va., on Saturday to meet with Virginia Commonwealth Coach Anthony Grant about becoming Donovan’s successor. Grant, a former assistant coach under Donovan, was the leading candidate for the job and was expected to make a seamless transition. Many of Florida’s recruits said they would stick with their commitments to the program because Grant, who left Florida about a year ago, had helped recruit them there. But Grant released a statement Sunday night saying that he had not had any “in-person” contact with Florida. Foley never made it to meet him because he learned that Donovan was having second thoughts. first reported the story Sunday night. coach Stan Van Gundy is expected to be the Magic’s next choice if Donovan does back out of his contract; Van Gundy was the only other candidate the Magic had considered seriously. Donovan was close to signing on long-term deal worth more than $3 million a year with Florida before deciding to go to the Magic last week. He won a second consecutive national championship with the Gators in April. It remains unclear how easily the Magic will let Donovan back out of his contract. “We’ve had numerous conversations and a personal visit in Gainesville with Billy over the last 48 hours and we have a commitment from him that the dialogue between us will continue,” the Magic’s statement said. Next Article in Sports (2 of 26) &#x00bb; Gain access to The Archive - get it now with TimesSelect To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Florida&#8217;s Donovan Is Leaving for the N.B.A. SPORTS OF THE TIMES; For Now, Donovan Has a Haven BASKETBALL; Donovan Remains at Florida, But His Stars Enter the Draft N.C.A.A. TOURNAMENT; Season Ends, but Donovan Has One More Play to Call Next Article in Sports (2 of 26) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Trams in the Fog - 2005 Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-5&fd=R&url=http://www.sheboygan-press.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/SHE02/706040546/1882/SHEsports&cid=1116826874&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ The Sheboygan Press - Local racing: Texas rider starts own streak at Road America Search over 1.5 million better jobs! Career Tips and Tricks: More on this topic Local racing: EWSC Saturday program shortened because of fog Frank Rigas on Local Motorsport Falls rider glad to be operating on racetrack again Posted June 4, 2007 Local racing: Texas rider starts own streak at Road America ELKHART LAKE — Mat Mladin's four-race winning streak at Road America was snapped Sunday by the same rider who snapped the Australian star's three-year streak of AMA Superbike series championships. Ben Spies — Mladin's teammate at Yoshimura Suzuki. Spies, of Texas, won the second race of the AMA Suzuki Superbike Doubleheader at the Elkhart Lake racetrack in the rain and regained the points lead. The defending series champion finished 11.794 seconds ahead of Jamie Hacking (Kawasaki). Mladin, who won Saturday's race — his seventh victory at Road America — was third. "I have to thank my team for doing such a great job, staying up until 1 in the morning to rebuild the bike I crashed in practice (Saturday)," said Spies, who won at RA for the first time in the Superbike series. "My Suzuki was so good in the rain today. I was afraid the track was going to dry out. We needed this win, for sure." Sunday's race, which began in a downpour, was red-flagged on lap two of 16 because of lighting. When it resumed, Spies quickly moved into the lead and led the rest of the way. Spies also won Sunday's AMA Superstock race. Other winners from the weekend were: Aaron Gobert (Honda) in the AMA Supersport Championship series and Joshua Hayes (Honda) in the AMA Formula Xtreme series. This article does not have any comments associated with it pbs:newslist ado=1 lastdate category=% profile=1004 count=10 leadin=0 prio