http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-3&fd=R&url=http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/chronicle/archive/2007/06/03/SPGBQQ6SQM1.DTL&cid=1116923679&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ U.S. has easy time with China / Bradley's team enjoys a rout in his official debut as head coach Bradley's team enjoys a rout in his official debut as head coach" /> U.S. has easy time with China Bradley's team enjoys a rout in his official debut as head coach Dan Giesin, Chronicle Staff Writer Sunday, June 3, 2007 Using a collection of experienced European-based players and some promising youngsters, Bob Bradley got his first victory as official U.S. national team coach, guiding the Americans to a 4-1 thrashing of China in an international friendly Saturday at San Jose's Spartan Stadium. "I'm very pleased with the effort," said Bradley, who until May 16 was the team's interim coach for five months. "We got a lot out of our effort." Bradley, who started five players with fewer than six international appearances, was particularly pleased with the performance of Benny Feilhaber, who had a goal and an assist in his third game with the national team. "Benny thus far has shown he can play the center of the field," Bradley said of the 22-year-old midfielder. "He showed his ability in seeing the right pass and in coming forward. It was a good game for Benny." "I felt pretty good in the middle today," he said. For much of Saturday's game, witnessed by a relatively placid 20,821 heavily pro-American spectators, the U.S. team was feeling much the same way. Although there were some letdowns, the Americans generally kept the Chinese team well out of harm's reach. "We did well to compete for 90 minutes," said defender Oguchi Onyewu, one of the team's greybeards with 19 international appearances. DaMarcus Beasley, the most experienced player among the starting 11 with 63 international appearances, got the Americans' first goal in the 10th minute. The speedy midfielder, easily the fastest man on the field, showed his heels to the Chinese defense after taking a long pass from Michael Bradley, the coach's son, just inside the half line and raced toward the goal with just keeper Chen Dong between him and the net. Chen came off the line in an attempt to cut down Beasley's angle, but the American midfielder had room to maneuver. So Chen did the most expedient thing -- he arm tackled Beasley near the top of the penalty area. Referee Hugo Guajardo quickly ran into the box, his hand pointing at the penalty spot. He then issued a yellow card to Chen. After Chen was booked, Beasley casually put the penalty kick beyond the reach of a sprawling Chen into the left side of the net for his 13th career goal with the national team. China got the goal back five minutes later when the American defense decided to watch something besides the ball. With the Chinese banging the ball around the penalty area and the U.S. team in some disarray, forward Wang Peng, situated between two American defenders who were facing the net, redirected a cross back out to an unmarked Zhang Yaokun. The defender took a couple of steps into the box and then unleashed a wicked 20-yard shot that eluded goalie Tim Howard. "We allowed China to push us into our end," Bob Bradley said, "and we didn't do a good job of getting the ball back into our end. But after they scored, we responded." And in the 28th minute midfielder Sacha Kljestan made his national team debut one to remember when he sent a pass over and through the Chinese defense to Feilhaber near the right corner of the penalty area. Feilhaber took several steps into the box before chipping the ball over the on-rushing Chen for a 2-1 U.S. lead. The Americans, who came into the game with just one loss in seven previous matches against the Chinese, secured their fifth victory over China in the 75th minute on a beautiful set piece. Feilhaber lofted a corner kick into the goalie area and Clint Dempsey ripped a header past a flat-footed Chen. Four minutes later, Onyewu got his second career goal, heading in Beasley's 30-yard free-kick from point-blank range. E-mail Dan Giesin at This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Garbage truck backs up, kills Sausalito restaurant employee Familiar name back on city payroll with new job Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... No explanation yet for why Southwest jet&#x27;s landing gear collapsed 2 hospitalized in SoMa stabbing Paris Hilton Checks Into L.A. Jail THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... THE NIGHTMARE OF GETTING THERE Surge in applications has created a... ON THE JOB Quitters sometimes win: Jumping ship in order to clean them Southwest flight&#x27;s gear collapses on landing at Oakland airport SAN FRANCISCO Woman hit and killed in crosswalk on 19th Ave. IN JOHN MUIR&#x27;S FOOTSTEPS Santa Cruz couple retrace famed naturalist&#x27;s 1868... Familiar name back on city payroll with new job THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members &#x27;No intention of resigning,&#x27; vows S.F. Supervisor Ed Jew Guantanamo Judge Dismisses Terror Case Polish Girl&#x27;s Holocaust Diary Unveiled Indiana Kangaroo Dies After Capture Deputies arrest man after Dana Point knife attacks E. coli fear spurs ground beef recall at Albertsons, Save-A-Lot See more from this dealer View All Top Autos &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19034162/&cid Canucks re-sign forward Taylor Pyatt - Wire Services - Hockey - MSNBC.com Canucks re-sign forward Taylor Pyatt VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -The Vancouver Canucks re-signed forward Taylor Pyatt to a two-year, $3 million contract on Monday. The 25-year-old Pyatt set career highs with 23 goals and 37 points in 76 games while making $700,000 last season and could have become an unrestricted free agent on July 1. Acquired from Buffalo last summer for a fourth-round draft pick, Pyatt benefited from playing large parts of the season on the Canucks' top line with twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin. The 6-foot-4, 220-pound wing also scored two goals in the playoffs, including an overtime winner in the first round against Dallas, and added two assists in 12 postseason games. Pyatt, originally a first-round draft pick by the New York Islanders in 1999, has 65 goals, 135 points and 212 penalty minutes in 384 career NHL games. Â© 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Congressman indicted on 16 counts Al-Qaida group: Abducted GIs slain Putin offers warning on U.S. plan Charges nixed for Gitmo detainee Democrats debate in N.H. Miss USA on boos and the fall 69-year-old climber reaches Mt. Everest peak TODAY to broadcast from Cuba Prevent cancer by pumping up on vitamin D Medal of Honor tributes More on the NHL Stanley Cup finals headquarters Message boards: Sound off Clement: Two-man race for Conn Smythe Expert: Senators won't be able to duck Ducks Clement: Emery's come long way in short time Opinion: Hockey still captivates, thrills Sid the Kid: A look at Crosby, past phenoms Expert: Brodeur over Crosby for MVP Lombardi signs 3-year deal with Flames Going for the Throat Congressman indicted in bribery investigation Al-Qaida group says 3 abducted GIs were slain Putin: â€˜We will have to have new targetsâ€™ Most viewed on MSNBC.com Would-Be Suicide Bomber Di