http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-1&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores107/107155/MLB733176.htm&cid=1116889647&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ USATODAY.com - Baseball - Chicago Cubs vs. Milwaukee How do I find it? 06/03/2007 - 11:28 PM - Click reload often for latest version begins at: 8:05 PM ET The Chicago Cubs realize winning is the best way to put a tumultuous week behind them. They try to follow up one of their biggest victories of the season with another when they open a three-game series with the Milwaukee Brewers on Monday at Miller Park. Chicago (23-31) snapped a season-high six-game losing streak Sunday with a 10-1 victory over the Atlanta Braves in the finale of a three-game set. The Cubs tied their largest margin of victory this season and scored their most runs since May 19. Mark DeRosa hit a grand slam while Alfonso Soriano and Derrek Lee added solo homers for Chicago, which had been outscored 38-16 during its skid. The win also came at a vital time for a club dealing with turmoil. In Friday's 8-5 defeat, Cubs pitcher Carlos Zambrano and catcher Michael Barrett had a confrontation in the dugout which continued into the clubhouse, and resulted in Barrett getting six stitches in his lower lip and a bruise below his left eye. Both players were fined Saturday, but later that day manager Lou Piniella got into some trouble of his own. After Angel Pagan got thrown out stealing third during a 5-3 loss, Piniella threw his cap, kicked dirt on third-base umpire Mark Wegner and earned his first ejection this season. He was suspended indefinitely Sunday and fined an undisclosed amount by Major League Baseball, which said the manager made contact with Wegner during the outburst. Piniella will find out the length of his punishment Monday after a meeting with John McHale Jr., the MLB executive vice president for administration. ''Obviously, you don't see a fight everyday in the dugout, so there were questions with the attention that brings,'' said Lee, who is batting an NL-leading .361. ''The ejection? We knew that was coming sooner or later, so it wasn't too big of a deal. Our main concern was just the way we've been playing.'' Lee has been playing well versus the NL Central-leading Brewers (32-25) this season, going 16-for-28 with a homer, seven doubles and seven RBIs. The teams have split six meetings, with each winning a series on the road. Despite the Cubs' struggles, Milwaukee isn't looking past its NL Central rival. ''The Cubs obviously have a good enough team to snap out of it and rattle off a lot of wins,'' center fielder Bill Hall told the Brewers' official Web site. ''We're not in a state to take anybody for granted, anyway. Look at that Cubs lineup, and you can't afford to do that.'' Milwaukee appears to be finally rebounding from its own slide, taking three of four games from the Florida Marlins over the weekend after losing six straight series. Ben Sheets pitched six strong innings Sunday and Francisco Cordero had a perfect ninth for his 21st save as the Brewers won 3-0. Dave Bush (3-5, 5.64 ERA) tries to follow up Sheets' effort and build on one of his best starts of the season when he takes the ball for Milwaukee. The right-hander held Atlanta to one run and six hits over seven innings on Wednesday, but didn't earn a decision after the bullpen game up eight runs over the final two innings of a 9-3 defeat. Bush, who is 1-3 with a 3.89 ERA in six career starts versus the Cubs, gave up six runs and eight hits over six innings in a 9-3 loss to them on April 6. Chicago counters with Jason Marquis (5-2, 2.93), who is trying to regain his early season form. The right-hander went 5-1 with a 1.70 ERA in his first seven starts while holding opponents to a .175 batting average, but is 0-1 with a 5.48 ERA in his last four outings. He gave up gave up five runs - four earned - and eight hits over five innings in a 9-4 defeat to Florida on Tuesday. Marquis is 4-6 with a 4.43 ERA in 13 career games versus the Bre