http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-4&fd=R&url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/Sports/Hockey/2007/06/04/4232569-sun.html&cid=1116235930&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ edmontonsun.com - Hockey - NHL head cases Check out what's keeping Ann Marie McQueen busy this week in her Trends column. Check out what's keeping Ann Marie McQueen busy this week in her Trends column. Find last week's Trends column here. Mon, June 4, 2007 Yes, injuries should count when the NHL assesses discipline OTTAWA -- NHL lord of discipline Colin Campbell must have Anaheim Ducks defenceman Chris Pronger on speed dial by now. Every reporter covering the Stanley Cup final should do the same with Anaheim GM Brian Burke. Thanks to a shot of adrenalin for the Senators and two shots to the head in Game 3 of the Stanley Cup final, a series has broken out. What started out as a boring sweep in suburban California has turned into a nasty bit of business in Canada's capital with elbows and accusations flying. Pronger was suspended for the second time in these playoffs and will miss Game 4 tonight for his elbow to the head of Senators forward Dean McAmmond in Game 3. After losing Pronger, Burke tried to turn the tables, calling a hit by Ottawa's Chris Neil on Ducks forward Andy McDonald "reprehensible." Normally, you would say that's just Burke. You know his strategy, and that of most executives in this kind of situation: Your guy is the villain, a repeat offender, no less, so you deflect, right? But you know what? Burke's got a bit of a case. In the second period Saturday night, Neil took five big strides from the Ducks blue line and collided with McDonald by the hash marks. Neil's left elbow caught McDonald in the side of the head. Luckily for the little McDonald, he saw Neil coming and twisted out of the way, mitigating the effects of the hit. He went down, got up and skated away. Neil wasn't penalized, but it could have been a charging or an elbowing penalty. If McDonald was hurt, maybe Neil would have been on the carpet yesterday, too. "The most dangerous play in the game (Saturday) night was not Chris Pronger's hit on Dean McAmmond. It was Neil's hit on Andy McDonald," said Burke, who does bluster well. "That's the troubling part for us. We'll take our one game. That's Colin's job and it's a tough one and we'll take it. But the fact there was one hearing (yesterday) is just mind-boggling to me." McAmmond wasn't as lucky as McDonald. So, two hits to the head, neither penalized by the referees. One guy gets up, the other doesn't. One guy gets suspended, the other doesn't. "I don't think this act warranted supplemental discipline if it didn't cause this player to be knocked out," Campbell said of the Pronger hit. Both Burke and McDonald took the head-shot argument - the issue that's been head-and-shoulders above the rest this year - into the grey area of intent. They've got a point. Not many guys get hit in the face with an elbow by accident. An elbow to the head is an elbow to the head for the guy on the receiving end. Burke, who used to have Campbell's job, doesn't think a suspension should only be handed out in the case of injury. When he brought up the Neil hit to Campbell, Burke said, "(Campbell) said the player wasn't injured, so mind my own business," said Burke. "Obviously, I didn't share that view." The league's general managers will be meeting today and Burke said he thinks head shots will be discussed. Trying to differentiate between Pronger's hit and Neil's is a little self-serving for Burke. Looking at the replay of the Neil hit on McDonald, it looks like Neil intends to hit him with his arm and shoulder. When McDonald ducks, Neil lunges so as not to miss and gets him with more elbow as he's delivering the blow. So, what was Neil's intent? He wanted to hit McDonald. Pronger wanted to hit McAmmond. Players need to be responsible. If they cause an injury with an elbow, the consequences should be greater. Neil just said 'hi!' to Niedermayer Day-old Hailey gets game puck from dad Senators aim to build on big win Two sides of Pronger Giguere done as a Duck? Is the practice of bump drafting a fair tactic in NASCAR? Voice your opinion at Fan Fare, Sports Department, The Toronto Sun, 333 King St. E Toronto, M5A 3X5, or by calling (416) 947-2268 or e-mail For today's Fan Fare, - London Free Press - 24 Hours Toronto - 24 Hours Vancouver - 24 Heures Montreal - Brockville Recorder & Times - Fort McMurray Today - Grande Prairie Daily Herald-Trib. - Kenora Daily Miner & News - Portage la Prairie Daily Graphic - St. Thomas Times Journal - Stratford Beacon Herald - Jobboom Career Connection This site is updated by 4:00 a.m. MST each day and includes stories and columns from the day's print edition of The Edmonton Sun. Send a Letter to the Editor home | We welcome your
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-0&fd=R&url=http://www.superbikeplanet.com/2007/Jun/e/n070603q.htm&cid=1116826874&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Soup :: Mladin Nand Hacking Comment On Elkhart Superbike Race :: 06-03-2007 Mladin And Hacking Comment On Elkhart Superbike Race Sunday, June 03, 2007 Mat Mladin (#66 Yoshimura Suzuki, third place): Q Mat, on the first start you were way back, but you made a big change for the second start. What did you change on your bike, if anything, or in your riding, that you were able to start so much better the second time? A I didn't get a good start in the first one, but there was that much water on the track that I couldn't see where I was going. I decided pretty early on that I wasn't going to do anything silly without being able to see where I'm going. Fortunately it got red-flagged. The conditions in the second one were just a little bit more sane. The track was slippery, but visibility was okay. But the first one was a little bit crazy. Q It looked early on like you might be able to contend for the win, but as the race progressed, Ben got by, and then Jamie got by. How were they able to put a margin on you? A They just rode better than me today. A couple of things I seen, both of them, just the first couple of laps with Ben, and then when Jamie came by, I seen a couple things that I can improve on. Certainly one area that I'm lacking in the rain. But again, some of the things that I do that hurt me in the rain, don't hurt me in the dry. The unfortunate thing for people that are good in the rain, is most days are sunny. Q Mat, in the last couple of press conferences, you pretty boldly declared you're not concerned about the championship this year. And you said about the rain, "I'll be throwing it away trying to be a hero if it's wet." So I was curious if there was anything that altered that outlook. MLADIN: Well, I said that I may go down the road if it's wet, of course. I tried hard to win that race. I obviously am not just going to deliberately decide that if I can't win, I'm going to toss the thing down the road. So I think that was a silly question. Jamie Hacking (#2 Kawasaki Racing, second place): Q Jamie, it seems like you guys have been struggling with the Superbike much of the year, but you turned this thing around in a wet race. Is this going to help spur your team on, do you think - give them a little incentive as the rest of the season goes on? A We'd like to think that, but the reality is that we're struggling with the bike, and it's not going to turn around any time soon. We just keep being patient and wait for things that I need to make the bike work. The rain setup is more suited to the bike. It's a softer setup, which is something that I've got on the bike right now, and I can't ride it in the dry, soft like that. So definitely this is a confidence booster for the team, but reality sets back in when we go back to a dry track, and we're back to struggling again. But we're trying. It's not like we're not trying. I came in after the race the other day and told those guys that I won the race. I mean, I rode the bike as hard as I could. It's hard, but frustrating. Today, coming out with the podium definitely makes the weekend go by a little easier, but back in my head I know the reality. Q Tell us about chasing down the leaders. Were you gaining confidence as the race was going on? There were a couple of laps there, halfway, three-quarters of the way through, that you were running the fastest laps of the race. A I started from the third row, which is where I've been every weekend. It kind of makes it tough. Like Mat said, the rain was so strong at the beginning of the race I couldn't even see where I was going. My shield, the mist would stay on it, but it wouldn't roll off for some reason. I had a rag in the dash and kept wiping it every now and then, and managed to reel in those guys one by one. A couple of guys slowed me up there at the beginning. Just put in some comfortable lap times and managed to run those guys down. The bike was really good on the brakes. I could square up the corners really nice and drive. I had plenty of grip. That's what got me up here. Post this story to: &copy; 1997 - 2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-1&fd=R&url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp%3Fymd%3D20070604%26content_id%3D2004516%26vkey%3Drecap%26fext%3D.jsp%26c_id%3Dmlb&cid=1116970892&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News MLB.TV: Live and On-Demand MLB.TV Mosaic Help Blog Player News and Notes Home Run Beat the Streak Staples Easy Fantasy Report Fantasy News and Notes Text Messaging – Alerts & More Manage Services – Mobile Dashboard MLB 2007 Mobile Game DHL Delivery of the Day 06/04/2007 4:17 PM ET Klesko, Zito lead Giants past Phillies Five-run fifth inning lifts San Francisco to series split in Philly By Chris Haft / MLB.com Piniella suspended four games by MLB Klesko, Zito lead Giants past Phillies Lefty Price may be right for Rays in Draft Jackie's work didn't end with playing days Reds' Hamilton to be activated from DL Complete coverage: June 7-8 Draft Latin American history comes to life in DVD Peek at the Week: Big-time matchups Giants notes: Close wins on Bochy's mind PHILADELPHIA -- Barry Zito continued his resurgence with six effective innings, while Ryan Klesko's three-run homer highlighted a 15-hit collection Monday afternoon as the San Francisco Giants thrashed the Philadelphia Phillies, 8-1. Zito (6-5) allowed a fifth-inning unearned run and six hits to win his third consecutive start. The left-hander, who owns a 0.45 ERA in that span, put the first two runners on base in the first, third, fifth and sixth innings, yet prevented the Phillies from sustaining each rally. Philadelphia went 1-for-13 with runners in scoring position against Zito, who quickly ran up his pitch count while working out of each jam, thus explaining his relatively early exit. The Giants shattered a scoreless tie with five runs in the fifth as they sent 11 batters to the plate. With two on and two outs, Klesko hammered the first pitch he saw from Phillies starter Jon Lieber (2-4) off an advertising panel hanging from the second deck in right field. It was Klesko's second homer of the season. The uprising continued as the Giants loaded the bases on Barry Bonds' walk, Ray Durham's double and Bengie Molina's intentional walk. Pedro Feliz and Kevin Frandsen added RBI singles. With one out in the seventh, the Giants widened their lead to 6-1 on Molina's double, Feliz's single and Frandsen's RBI single. Durham clobbered a two-run homer in the eighth. The Giants emerged with a split of the four-game series after losing six consecutive games at Citizens Bank Park from 2005-06. is a reporter for MLB.com. This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs. Register | Log In Help | Contact Us &copy; 2001-2007 MLB Advanced Media, L.P. All rights reserved. The following are trademarks or service marks of Major League Baseball entities and may be used only with permission of Major League Baseball Properties, Inc. or the relevant Major League Baseball entity: Major League, Major League Baseball, MLB, the silhouetted batter logo, World Series, National League, American League, Division Series, League Championship Series, All-Star Game, and the names, nicknames, logos, uniform designs, color combinations, and slogans designating the Major League Baseball clubs and entities, and their respective mascots, events and exhibitions. Use of the Website signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy (updated 03.22.05)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-3&fd=R&url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp%3Fymd%3D20070603%26content_id%3D2003216%26vkey%3Dnews_mlb%26fext%3D.jsp%26c_id%3Dmlb&cid=1116861088&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News MLB.TV: Live and On-Demand MLB.TV Mosaic Help Blog Player News and Notes Home Run Beat the Streak Staples Easy Fantasy Report Fantasy News and Notes Text Messaging – Alerts & More Manage Services – Mobile Dashboard MLB 2007 Mobile Game DHL Delivery of the Day 06/03/2007 7:00 PM ET Sheets reasserts himself as ace Milwaukee right-hander gaining control of curveball By Adam McCalvy / MLB.com Milwaukee right-hander Ben Sheets has a team-high nine quality starts this season. (Morry Gash/AP) Piniella suspended four games by MLB Klesko, Zito lead Giants past Phillies Lefty Price may be right for Rays in Draft Jackie's work didn't end with playing days Reds' Hamilton to be activated from DL Complete coverage: June 7-8 Draft Latin American history comes to life in DVD Peek at the Week: Big-time matchups &#149; Sheets strikes out seven Sheets delivers for Brewers in series finale Shop for Ben Sheets gear Listen on Gameday Audio MILWAUKEE -- Ben Sheets has quietly reemerged as the Brewers' stopper. He just won't tell anybody exactly how he did it. The right-hander pitched six shutout innings at steamy Miller Park on Sunday, scattering seven hits in a 3-0 win over the Marlins that sealed the Brewers' first series win in nearly a month. It was Sheets' seventh straight quality start, and his fifth win in his last six decisions. Each of Sheets' last four wins has come after the Brewers lost the previous day. "Benny has always been that guy," manager Ned Yost said. "He's our No. 1 guy. You know what he's capable of doing when he gets it rolling, and he's rolling." There have been bumps along the way. Sheets' only loss since April 15 came May 22 at Los Angeles, when he had to leave after 6 1/3 innings because of a blister. On Sunday, Sheets threw 69 of his 99 pitches for strikes and might have pitched past the sixth inning, but with the roof and outfield panels closed because of a mid-game rainstorm, Miller Park turned into a "sauna," Sheets said, and the heat and humidity sapped his strength. Still, it has been a very good last month for Sheets, and the key was harnessing his curveball. Pitching coach Mike Maddux noticed in earlier starts that Sheets was releasing pitches too early, so they worked on an adjustment before his May 1 win over the Cardinals at Miller Park. Sheets made another mechanical fix for his May 12 win in New York that improved the "snap" on his signature curveball. Sheets featured one of his better benders on Sunday. Three of the four Marlins who struck out in the first two innings swung at curveballs in the dirt. How exactly did he fix that pitch? The answer will stay with Sheets. "I can't tell you that," he sang. "Then [opponents] are going to know. The first one made the location on everything good, and the second one just sharpened up my breaking ball." Whatever he did, it seems to have worked. Back in that May 1 start, Sheets surrendered two Cardinals runs before he recorded the first out of the third inning. But then he retired 12 of the final 13 hitters he faced. Sheets' strikeout numbers have increased since the first fix. He struck out 13 batters in his first 32 1/3 innings of the season, including the first 2 1/2 innings of the May 1 start, then he whiffed 35 batters in his next 42 innings through Sunday. Sheets has more than doubled his strikeouts per nine innings, from 3.6 over the first span to 7.3 in the latter. "They're not dominating innings, but they're good innings," Sheets said. And those good innings have brought back the bounce in his step. Yost has said often that you can tell how Sheets has pitched of late by watching his body language in the clubhouse. "I was frustrated early because I didn't have my curveball going for an extended period of time," Sheets said. "It ain't that I care about striking people out. What I was frustrated with early was the fact that I want to be able to get it when I want it. "I want to be able to step on the accelerator and get that big strikeout if I need it, and now I feel like I'm there. I know I can make pitches, so I'm happy with that." If he sounds hard on himself, get used to it. "There's always room to get better," Sheets said. "To say I'm not happy would be untrue, because I'm very happy. But even when I'm going through my best, I'm still looking for that edge. When you're giving up two runs, you want to give up no runs or one run. "When you start throwing perfect games, then you've figured it out," he said. "That's the bottom line." That line made his pitching coach chuckle. "That's a pipe dream," Maddux said. "But mentally, I suppose that's how you go about it. You figure that somewhere along the way you're going to give up some hits and runs, but it's always good to set your standards very high." Sheets has been working to regain his "ace" status since August 2005, when he suffered a major injury in a game at Miller Park against the Braves. Sheets tore the "lat" muscle behind his right shoulder in his 22nd start of the season, and that led to lingering shoulder troubles throughout the 2006 season that limited him to 17 starts. Before those two injury-interrupted years, Sheets had made 34 starts in three consecutive seasons and was the workhorse of the Milwaukee pitching staff. In 2004, he put together a Cy Young Award-caliber season, posting a 2.70 ERA in 237 innings with a franchise-record 264 strikeouts. He is not back to that level yet, but at least Sheets is headed in the right direction, according to Maddux. "He's getting in a rhythm again," Maddux said. is a reporter for MLB.com. This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs. Register | Log In Help | Contact Us &copy; 2001-2007 MLB Advanced Media, L.P. All rights reserved. The following are trademarks or service marks of Major League Baseball entities and may be used only with permission of Major League Baseball Properties, Inc. or the relevant Major League Baseball entity: Major League, Major League Baseball, MLB, the silhouetted batter logo, World Series, National League, American League, Division Series, League Championship Series, All-Star Game, and the names, nicknames, logos, uniform designs, color combinations, and slogans designating the Major League Baseball clubs and entities, and their respective mascots, events and exhibitions. Use of the Website signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy (updated 03.22.05)
