inals Germany to keep faith with misfiring Klose Sharapova displays iron will to stage fightback Williams, Federer advance at French Open 3 killed, 300 injured as quake rocks Yunnan Most stocks will be traded normally China rejects US warning on toothpaste Putin warns on US missiles in Europe FMs of China, S.Korea, Japan meeting in Jeju Most Commented/Read Stories in 48 Hours
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-5&fd=R&url=http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/chronicle/archive/2007/06/04/SPGLQQ6UKV1.DTL&cid=1116235930&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Eric Stephens, Los Angeles Times Monday, June 4, 2007 (06-04) 04:00 PDT Ottawa -- It was not even three weeks ago when Chris Pronger was suspended for Game 4 of the Western Conference finals and the Anaheim Ducks, down 2-1 in that series against the Detroit Red Wings, were called to rally around his absence. The Ducks won that game 5-3 and did not lose again in taking the Red Wings in six games. But who would have guessed they would be called to that task again? It is now deja vu for the Ducks after Pronger was suspended Sunday by the NHL for Game 4 of the Stanley Cup Finals -- the result of a hit with his forearm that knocked out Ottawa's Dean McAmmond in the Senators' 5-3 victory Saturday night. It is the second time that Pronger has been disciplined in these playoffs because of a blow to the head and the seventh suspension overall in his 13-year career. He will sit out tonight's game but will be able to return for Game 5 in Anaheim on Wednesday. "We accept the league's decision," Ducks coach Randy Carlyle said. "Obviously, we feel that the player did not intentionally try to hurt Dean McAmmond. It was unfortunately one of those things that happened. "We have to live by the league's action. It's the rules we play under, and you accept it and move on." Pronger was suspended in the Detroit series because of a blow he delivered to the head of Red Wings forward Tomas Holmstrom in the second period of Game 3. On Saturday, the Ducks' defenseman knocked McAmmond to the ice with his left arm after the Ottawa winger attempted a shot in the third period. Late in the second period, McAmmond had scored the eventual game-winning goal with a centering pass that deflected off Pronger's stick into the net. No penalty was assessed on the ice for Pronger's hit but Colin Campbell, the NHL's director of hockey operations, determined that discipline was warranted. "Mr. Pronger used his forearm to deliver a forceful hit to the head of his opponent," Campbell said in a conference call. "Also, his actions caused injury to his opponent." Early Sunday, Pronger had a hearing with Campbell over the telephone with Ducks general manager Brian Burke also present. Campbell said he did consider additional discipline because Pronger is a repeat offender. "We all know how precious it is to chase for the Stanley Cup and to be at this point," Campbell said. "And it's a tough decision to make. We don't take these things lightly at any time. Particularly now. "But on the other hand a player did get knocked out. And that player may not be playing (tonight), too. We're not sure." As he sat on the podium alongside Burke, Pronger said there was no malicious intent. "It was a reaction play," Pronger said. "I stepped up to make the hit and got him with my forearm. And, obviously, you've got to suffer the consequences of what's come down." McAmmond did not skate Sunday, but in a statement released by the Senators, he said he agreed with the ruling. "I think it should have been a suspension because it was a blow to the head," said McAmmond, a 13-year NHL veteran. "It wasn't incidental. It's not like that couldn't have been avoided." Said Ottawa general manager John Muckler: "It's no doubt that he did this on purpose," referring to Pronger. Muckler also said that McAmmond has a concussion. Ducks lead series 2-1 All games 5 p.m. Channel: 11 Channel: 3 Channel: 8 Game 1: Ducks 3, Senators 2 Game 2: Ducks 1, Senators 0 Game 3: Senators 5, Ducks 3 June 11: at Anaheim* This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Garbage truck backs up, kills Sausalito restaurant employee Familiar name back on city payroll with new job Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... No explanation yet for why Southwest jet&#x27;s landin