http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-duckrep5jun05,0,985324.story%3Fcoll%3Dla-home-sports&cid Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation - Los Angeles Times 2:16 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 Buy, Sell & More Deals at Local Stores Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation With the defenseman suspended for game 4, center Pahlsson says every player will have to step up if they're to have any chance at winning. By Lonnie White, Times Staff Writer 1:06 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 OTTAWA -- After getting roughed up by Ottawa in Game 3, the Ducks probably wouldn't have needed any more incentive for Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals. But they found more anyway with the one-game suspension of defenseman , who will sit out his second game of these playoffs for his hit to the head of Senators forward "I wish I could say that I was surprised with the suspension, but I can't," Ducks forward said. "It's unfortunate, but we're going to use it as motivation. That's something you can never have too much of." With the Senators getting a lift from their crowd on Saturday, the Ducks realize that they have to play with more composure if they want to take a 3-1 lead back to Anaheim for Wednesday's Game 5. "It's going to be a game where everyone is going to have to help, not just the guys who are going to play minutes" in Pronger's place, Ducks center said. "We know that we're going to have to play our best game." told reporters Monday morning that the Ducks have been down this road before. "It's a piece of adversity that we've talked about &#91;how&#93; we've dealt with it historically," Carlyle said, referring to an early season stretch when because of various injuries, the Ducks played without goaltender "Key players out of our lineup for almost up to the All Star break. And those are the things that your team learns in the regular season, but, obviously, in the playoffs, it's a little different." McAmmond, who did not return after suffering a head injury as a result of Pronger's hit, skated with his teammates Monday morning and will be a game-time decision. "I actually feel pretty good considering," said McAmmond, who took a shot to the chin courtesy of Pronger. "As far as if I'm going to play tonight, I'm just going to continue on with my day and see how I feel later." said he's not sure whether McAmmond will be ready. "Obviously, we have to talk to the doctors before we let him play, but he's trying," Murray said. "He'd like to play. But in talking to him, he's certainly not 100% at this moment." McAmmond, a key player on the Senators' speed line and penalty kill who scored his first goal of the finals in Game 3, said he's not going to force himself into the lineup if he doesn't feel right. "The headache seems to be going away," McAmmond said. "The neck seems to be loosening up with movement. That's pretty good, but there's other things, too. Just sometimes, if you ever got clunked in the head, you go along, some things you just know aren't right. "If I get out on the ice and I don't feel quite right, then I don't feel like I should be in a situation trying to help this team win. If I'm out there killing a penalty and I don't feel confident that I can compete 100%, then I would not put myself in that situation, or the team. "Again, if I feel confident that I can compete at 100%, then I think everything is a go." That would not shock Carlyle, who said: "Nothing would surprise me. It's playoffs. It's what happens. People make huge strides in their recovery after suspensions. It's amazing." Carlyle also talked about Ducks winger , who suffered an abdominal bruise in a collision in Game 3. "You never risk a player's health or well-being," Carlyle said of Kunitz, who had just returned after sitting out seven games with a broken hand. "Every player will tell you he's ready. This is the Stanley Cup final. Sometimes you have to make a decision that the player doesn't agree with but you don't want to jeopardize a player's chances to come back at a later date." If Kunitz does not play, rookie , who played the first two games of the finals, is expected to take his spot in the lineup. By Andrew and Brian Kamenetzky Blue Notes -- A Dodgers Blog By Andrew and Brian Kamenetzky LeBron vs. Kobe: a new round of fighting words Former NASCAR chief Bill France Jr. dies Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation Copyright 2007 Los Angeles Times FSBO (For Sale By Owner) Boodle.com for Grocery Coupons Recycler for Free Classifieds
