http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/wires/ap/need_to_map/7829687.html&cid=1116970892&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Zito, Klesko Lead Giants Past Phillies | AP | 06/04/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Monday, Jun 4, 2007 Posted on Mon, Jun. 04, 2007 Zito, Klesko Lead Giants Past Phillies San Francisco Giants' Ryan Klesko hit a three-run home run off Philadelphia Phillies Jon Lieber in the 5th inning of their baseball game Monday, June 4, 2007 in Philadelphia.(AP Photo/Rusty Kennedy) PHILADELPHIA - Barry Zito allowed only an unearned run over six innings and Ryan Klesko hit a three-run homer to lead the San Francisco Giants over the Philadelphia Phillies 8-1 Monday. Zito (6-5) pitched out of trouble throughout the afternoon to win his third straight start. Barry Bonds was 0-for-4 with two strikeouts and a walk to remain at 746 career homers, 10 shy of breaking Hank Aaron's record. After homering 11 times in his first 76 at-bats, the Giants slugger has only one home run in 61 at-bats since connecting May 8. Ray Durham hit a two-run shot and Randy Winn, Bengie Molina and Kevin Frandsen each had three hits for the Giants, who have won just three of their last 10 games. Zito allowed six hits, walked four and struck out five. The left-hander has an 0.45 ERA in his last three outings after giving up 13 runs combined in consecutive starts. Jon Lieber (2-4) allowed five runs and 10 hits in five-plus innings. He's allowed 14 runs and 29 hits in three starts after posting a 2.50 ERA in his first six. The Phillies had plenty of chances against Zito, but couldn't get a clutch hit. They were 1-for-14 with runners in scoring position and stranded 12 runners. Philadelphia lost five of seven on its homestand after sweeping a three-game series in Atlanta to move a season-best two games over .500. The Phillies are eight games behind the NL East-leading Mets going into a three-game series in New York. The Giants scored five runs off Lieber with two outs in the fifth to take a 5-0 lead. Frandsen led off the inning with a single and Winn had an infield single that put runners at the corners with one out. Fred Lewis followed with a grounder to first baseman Ryan Howard, who was a few feet off the bag. Instead of going to second and trying for an inning-ending double play, Howard hesitated before throwing home to get Frandsen. Klesko hit the next pitch off a billboard on the facing of the second deck in right field to give the Giants a 3-0 lead. A high follow-through on his swing made Klesko's bat flip look exaggerated as he admired his second homer of the season. The Phillies didn't appear to be offended. Bonds followed with a walk, Durham doubled and Molina was intentionally walked to load the bases. Pedro Feliz drove in a run with a single to right and Frandsen's infield single to third made it 5-0. The Phillies had a chance for a big inning in the bottom of the fifth, but only produced a run. Singles by Jimmy Rollins and Chase Utley sandwiched around second baseman Durham's error on Shane Victorino's grounder loaded the bases. But Howard flied out to shallow left. After Rollins scored on Jayson Werth's groundout to cut it to 5-1, Aaron Rowand fouled out to end the inning. With the bases loaded and one out in the first, Werth popped out to shallow right and Rowand hit a bouncer to Zito to end the inning. After the first two batters reached in the third, Utley struck out looking, Howard fanned swinging and Werth flied out. The Phillies again put runners on first and second with no outs in the sixth, but pinch-hitter Pat Burrell, Rollins and Victorino all grounded out. Notes:@ Giants RHP Russ Ortiz pitched two-thirds of an inning, before leaving with an apparent injury in the eighth. ... The Phillies are 6-15 against left-handed starters. ... Klesko is batting .405 (17-for-42) with five homers and 18 RBIs lifetime against Lieber. ... Zito is 89-4 when he receives four runs or more. Updated 4:00 PM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Mistake or not, Young vows to learn from it Phillies Notes | Gillick laughs off Mariners rumor McNabb talks draft-booing and Mom with WIP&#0146;s morning lair Eagles&#0039; Gaither taking the bad with the good On the NBA | So Kobe wants a trade. Well, all right, what if . . .? Updated 4:00 PM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM What if our mercenaries turn on us? Can do - craft-beer makers kicking glass, going metal Man Beats World Hot Dog Eating Record City's foie gras foes put heat on chefs More rain, old sewers make for nasty story Latest Stories in this Section A-Rod's Blast Lifts Yankees Over Red Sox Guerrero's Homer Gives Angels Comeback Win Cubs End Tumultuous Week With a Win Angels Top Orioles on Vlad's Walk-Off 06/03/2007 08:56 PM EDT 5-Run 4th Inning Lifts M's Over Rangers 06/03/2007 08:53 PM EDT A's Catch Johan Santana on Rare Off Day 06/03/2007 08:02 PM EDT Atkins, Rockies Rally Past Reds in 10 06/03/2007 07:08 PM EDT Vlad Hits 2-Run Shot As Angels Top Birds 06/03/2007 06:17 PM EDT Jays Send Reeling White Sox to 4-3 Loss 06/03/2007 05:59 PM EDT Victorino's Walk Off Homer Lifts Phils 06/03/2007 05:25 PM EDT Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
