http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1i-0&fd=R&url=http://story.scout.com/a.z%3Fs%3D107%26p%3D2%26c%3D648747&cid=1116633459&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Scout.com: Is He Coming Back? This story originally published on Is He Coming Back? Posted Jun 3, 2007 After having what he called a difficult 24 hours, Billy Donovan has had an even more difficult 48 hours. ESPN's Andy Katz reported on Sunday night that the former Gator head coach is thinking of returning to Florida if the Orlando Magic allow him to do so. On Thursday night, FightinGators.com reported that Donovan had agreed to take the job only if his former assistant and now head coach of Virginia Commonwealth Anthony Grant agreed to become the Gators new head coach. Before Donovan agreed to terms with the Magic, he was confident that Grant would take the position if athletic director Jeremy Foley offered it to him. Donovan was concerned with his commitment to both the current players and the incoming recruits. After a long weekend of back-and-forth discussions between Florida and Grant, the two appear to be no closer to an agreement than when discussions originally began. With Grant's uncertainty, Donovan is now reconsidering his jump to the Magic. According to Katz, the ball is now in Orlando's court as they hold the key to Donovan's future. The team can allow Donovan to get out of the five-year $27.5 million contract he inked on Friday and return to Florida, or they can hold him to the new deal. A final decision is expected on Monday. Grant Expected to be Named New Head Coach REPORT: Billy is Back! Subscribe today and get , our team magazine absolutely free! So donâ€™t wait ... Copyright &copy; TigerRag.com and . All rights reserved. This website is an unofficial and independent source of news and information, and is not affiliated with any school, team or league.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-2&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/sports/NA-SPT-CAR-NASCAR-Obit-France.php&cid=1116968844&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Former NASCAR chairman Bill France Jr. dies - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Former NASCAR chairman Bill France Jr. dies Published: June 4, 2007 Bill France Jr., who transformed NASCAR from a regional American auto racing circuit into a billion-dollar conglomerate during his 31 years as chairman, died Monday. He was 74. He died at his home in Daytona Beach, Florida, NASCAR spokesman Ramsey Poston said. France had been in poor health for much of the last decade &#8212; he was diagnosed with cancer in 1999. Although he was in remission, the extensive treatments took a toll. He never regained his full strength, often had difficulty breathing and had taken to using a motorized scooter to get around. Officials at Dover International Speedway in Dover, Delaware, where the Nextel Cup series was racing Monday afternoon, lowered the flag to half-staff in his memory. A shrewd businessman who was fiercely protective of his family-owned company, France always acted in the best interests of the National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing &#8212; or NASCAR. His decisions often riled car owners, drivers, sponsors and fans, but France never backed down. French Open: Moya advances in &#x27;old-timers&#x27; battle Cycling: Di Luca gives Italy a champion NBA: James savors the moment "Part of leadership is having the guts to make a decision and then having the guts to stand by it and making it work," driver Jeff Burton said in April. "That&#039;s what he did on a lot of occasions. He did it in a way that let you know who the boss was and also did it in a way that you respected him. And I&#039;ve said it all along, I think that is the cornerstone in our sport." France became chairman in 1972 when he replaced his father, NASCAR founder William Henry Getty France, who retired 25 years after forming NASCAR. He had prepped for the job by doing a little bit of everything during his rise through the grass roots ranks of racing. When he finally took over NASCAR, he inherited a circuit that was ingrained in the tradition of the Southeastern United States but mostly unknown everywhere else in the country. "Other than the founding of NASCAR itself, Bill Jr.&#039;s appointment to leadership is probably the most significant event in the history of the sanctioning body," the International Motorsports Hall of Fame said about the transition. "His role in the impact of the sport has been huge," Burton said. "His personality came at a time when it was what our sport needed. I think he did an incredible job of basing his opinion on what he believed the facts to be and then having the courage to make that decision and see it through. "He ain&#039;t a waffler. ... He&#039;s just going to go do it." Over the span of three remarkable decades, France oversaw the expansion of the sport, parlaying the loyal fan base of the Deep South into sold-out tracks in New England, California, Texas and the Midwest. He also moved the season-ending awards banquet to New York City in an effort to court the Madison Avenue money. In 1999, NASCAR finally packaged the entire circuit together in a $2.4 billion (&#8364;1.78 billion) contract that awarded races to the Fox and NBC television networks and the TNT cable channel that began in 2001. France, who had a mild heart attack in 1997, relinquished his role as NASCAR president to Mike Helton in 2003. He handed off chairman duties to son Brian in 2003. France took the role of vice chairman, reporting to headquarters daily, but moved into a different office a bit removed from the action as he left much of the decision-making to Brian. "I&#039;ve got total confidence in what Brian can do," France Jr. said. "He&#039;s loaded with street smarts." AP Auto Racing Writer Mike Harris contributed to this report. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
