http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-3&fd=R&url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2007/news/story%3Fid%3D2892720&cid=1116235930&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ ESPN - McAmmond still iffy for Game 4 after Pronger hit Skip to the content 2006 Hockey Hall of Fame McAmmond still feeling effects of Pronger's hit Updated: June 4, 2007, 2:24 PM ET OTTAWA -- For a moment, there is some intrigue about whether will play in Game 4 on Monday night. That intrigue will dissipate as soon as the puck drops on the game, regardless of whether the fourth-line center plays. The natural course of events will dictate that a role player, no matter whether that role player is having a wonderful spring -- as McAmmond is -- is relegated to sidebar status. Ross Dettman for ESPN The Magazine Chris Pronger received a one-game suspension for his hit on Dean McAmmond in Game 3 of the Cup finals. It's something McAmmond had better get used to. There are sometimes parallels between the hockey world and the criminal justice system, especially when it comes to victims. The focus is mostly on the perpetrators. They evoke the strongest emotions and often are simply the most interesting characters. The victims? Often they fade into the background. McAmmond, the victim of the latest violent outburst, exists in that strange limbo world between pursing a boyhood dream of playing in the Stanley Cup finals and becoming irrelevant. McAmmond was knocked unconscious with a flying Pronger elbow early in the third period of Game 3 on Saturday night. He skated for the first time since the hit Monday morning, but it's unknown whether he'll play in Game 4. He acknowledged that he could ride an exercise bike for only four or five minutes Sunday and didn't feel quite right. He skated and did a little more Monday morning, but although the headaches are receding and the stiffness in the neck seems to have subsided, there's still something in his head that isn't where it needs to be. "I rode today. I didn't have as much discomfort. But because of the kind of the whiplash, for lack of a better term, maybe that's the exact term, I have a lot of stiffness in my neck and whatnot," McAmmond said in his first public comments about the hit (he did make a comment via news release after Pronger's suspension was announced Sunday). "The headache seems to be going away," McAmmond said. "The neck seems to be loosening up with movement. That's pretty good, but there's other things, too. Just sometimes, if you ever got clunked in the head, you go along. Some things you just know aren't right. It just doesn't feel right." Ottawa coach Bryan Murray was likewise uncertain as to McAmmond's availability. "He's taking a light skate. We'll see how he feels afterwards," Murray said. "Obviously, we have to talk to the doctors before we let him play, but he's trying. He'd like to play. But in talking to him, he's certainly not 100 percent at this moment." Anaheim coach Randy Carlyle was asked whether he would be surprised if McAmmond played Monday and answered quite cattily that "People make huge strides in their recovery after suspensions. It's amazing." The implication, of course, is that McAmmond somehow embellished being knocked unconscious by 6-foot-6 Pronger, who is sitting out a league-imposed suspension for the seventh time in his career. Here's the thing, though. Sometimes, players don't come back right away. Sometimes, they don't play that night or the next night or the night after that. McAmmond recalled being in Calgary and seeing teammate take an elbow in a playoff game from . The blow left Lombardi unable to play for weeks. "I feel like I seem to be back on that track [to recovery], so I'd like to be in the lineup tonight. And there's a chance. It's just a matter of if you rush it too quick, you maybe set yourself back again," McAmmond said. McAmmond said that he has seen the replay and that it has helped him fill in some of what were blurry gaps in the evening. "Actually, after watching the play, I kind of faintly remember getting that loose puck [shortly before the hit]," McAmmond said. "But up until that point, I couldn't remember much past being in the dressing room in the second intermission and then up to where they got me back to the dressing room after the hit." The 33-year-old native of Grand Cache, Alberta, said he harbors no ill will toward Pronger. "I'm really not that way. I wouldn't want anything bad to happen to him in return or anything like that," McAmmond said. Regardless of when he might return to action, as early as Monday or sometime down the road, soft-spoken McAmmond hasn't lost his sense of humor. Asked whether he had any discomfort while shooting, he said, "Yeah, for about 16 years now." Scott Burnside is the NHL writer for ESPN.com. "McAmmond still feeling effects of Pronger's hit" Ducks' Pronger suspended for Game 4 of finals Burnside: Pronger regresses with second suspension of playoffs Chris Pronger's previous suspensions Experts: Was Pronger's suspension the right call? Sabres GM Regier confident he'll return with Ruff Canucks re-sign Pyatt to two-year deal worth $3M Crosby says he's cleared to resume workouts Wild goaltenders honored amid uncertain future Most U.S. newspapers freezing out Stanley Cup Newly crowned captain Sidney Crosby chatted with E.J. Hradek about the playoffs, that nagging foot injury and what he'll do to lead Pittsburgh to the Cup. Sidney Crosby is only 19, but the Pittsburgh Penguins -- and the league -- can expect to gain a lot from the experience of him being team captain. Ottawa got physical and, thanks to its depth, found a way to fight back against the Ducks -- who had one guy get a little too physical. Again. Ottawa trails Anaheim in the Stanley Cup finals and needs someone to send a jolt through the team. Hey, Jason Spezza: Are you ready to lead the charge? What does the Cup finals mean to Sens fans? Scott Burnside and E.J. Hradek debate all things Stanley Cup from Ottawa.
http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/49-06042007-1357242.html&cid New car rests on slippery slope (phillyBurbs.com) | Auto Racing Relationships w/ Wayne & Tamara New car rests on slippery slope DOVER, Del. — The “Monster Mile” can be daunting. It could be doubly uncomfortable today for Nextel Cup drivers if their new Car of Tomorrow doesn't cooperate on the demanding Dover concrete oval. Few have a clue how the series' latest chassis modification will adapt on the multi-grooved track. The Car of Tomorrow was designed to improve safety and competition and reduce costs, but many drivers have complained about the handling of the car in the turns. Dover figures to be the most demanding test yet for the Car of Tomorrow, especially considering that the drivers go into the Autism Speaks 400 without a full test session at the track. The Autism Speaks 400 was postponed by rain Sunday until noon today. That gave drivers another day to weigh uncertainty. Most don't have a baseline on how the boxy, balky car will negotiate the high banks and heavy traffic of Dover. A previously scheduled May 14-15 test session at Dover for the Car of Tomorrow was cancelled due to rain the previous weekend that pushed back the Darlington race. Instead, the test scheduled for Dover was run at Virginia International Raceway, and Kyle Busch didn't learn much. “I wish we were able to come here and test because it is so much different than what we had before,” Busch said. “We are lifting five, eight car lengths sooner than we used to, and it is really, really loose for me getting into the corner.” “Dover is a tough place because you always want to drive hard,” said Kurt Busch. “Thebanking invites you to drive into the corners hard and fast, but you're going to abuse your right front tires.” Jimmie Johnson, second in the Nextel Cup point standings, will start way back in 27th. With three Dover wins in 10 tries, he'll lean on his experience and his crew's ability to adjust in order to navigate his way from the back “I think that this track is really difficult to drive,” Johnson said. “If your set-up is not right it is really, really challenging, so in terms of more inexperienced teams and drivers, I think that gap will show more here than other places.” Led by pole-sitter Ryan Newman, Dodge owns four of the top 10 qualifying spots. “This is one of my favorite racetracks,” said Newman, who has finished on the lead lap in 80 percent of his Dover races — the best percentage of any active driver. Chevrolet has won 11 of the first 12 Nextel Cup races this season. That's the best start by a manufacturer since Chevy won the first seven events in '95, and nine of the first 11...Ford has won the last three Cup races at Dover. There are only three Ford drivers among the top 12 qualifiers — Carl Edwards (fifth), Jamie McMurray (eighth) and Greg Biffle (10th). ... Tony Stewart's average Dover finish of 8.9 is the best among active drivers. In the two Dover events last year, however, Stewart finished 25th and 33rd. ... Six different drivers have won the last six Dover races. ... Last year's winners, Matt Kenseth and Jeff Burton, both started 19th. ... While Hendrick Motorsports has won all five Car of Tomorrow races, Gibbs Racing has led the most laps in those events employing the new-styled Nextel Cup car. Stewart and teammate Denny Hamlin have led 973 C of T laps. Hendrick drivers have led 615. ... The combined margin of victory in the five COT races has been 2.527 seconds — an average of 0.505. Dan Dunkin can be reached at 215-949-4210 or June 4, 2007 4:40 AM ©2007 Copyright Calkins Media, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/06/04/ap3785478.html&cid Nadal Beats Hewitt to Reach French Final - Forbes.com Nadal Beats Hewitt to Reach French Final 06.04.07, 12:49 PM ET Rafael Nadal strokes are always accompanied by lots of grunting, so the French Open must be more difficult than he makes it look. Still unbeaten at Roland Garros, Nadal completed the men's quarterfinal field Monday by sweeping Lleyton Hewitt 6-3, 6-1, 7-6 (5). The two-time defending champion is 18-0 lifetime in the tournament, which seems to be getting easier for him: For the first time, he reached the final eight without losing a set. A potential showdown looms Sunday between the No. 2-seeded Nadal and top-ranked Roger Federer, who seeks his first French Open title to complete a career Grand Slam. Nadal's opponent Wednesday will be fellow Spaniard Carlos Moya, the 1998 champion. "I prefer to lose against him than against any other player, because he is a great friend," Nadal said. "He did a lot of things for me when I arrived on the men's circuit." Moya declined to take credit for Nadal's dominance. "I don't think he learned anything from me," Moya said. "And if he did, he did it much better than me." The other quarterfinal Wednesday will be between No. 125-ranked Igor Andreev and No. 6-seeded Novak Djokovic. Andreev, who eliminated No. 3-seeded Andy Roddick in the opening round, advanced to his first major quarterfinal by rallying past No. 16 Marcos Baghdatis 2-6, 6-1, 6-3, 6-4. Djokovic swept unseeded Fernando Verdasco 6-3, 6-3, 7-6 (1) to reach the final eight for the second consecutive year. "Last year, I honestly didn't expect to be in the quarterfinals," said Djokovic, 20. "I was pretty much satisfied with my achievement. This year is much different." The marquee pairing in the women's quarterfinals Tuesday features two-time defending champion Justine Henin against eight-time Grand Slam champion Serena Williams. It's a rematch of their contentious 2003 semifinal at Roland Garros. Hewitt had beaten Nadal in four of their six previous meetings, but on clay the matchup of baseliners was a mismatch from the outset. Nadal won 16 of the first 20 points. The No. 14-seeded Hewitt led for most of the third set and held advantages of 4-2 and 5-4 in the tiebreaker. But he blew an easy forehand to make it 5-all, then netted another easy forehand on the final point. Nadal displayed racket wizardry even between points, when he drew applause for an over-the-shoulder catch on the strings of a ball lobbed from the other end of the court. He's bidding to become the first man to win a third consecutive French Open title since Bjorn Borg was champion in 1978-81. Moya overcame his relative inexperience to beat Jonas Bjorkman. A Roland Garros perennial, Moya was nonetheless the younger player Monday, and he swept the 35-year-old Bjorkman 7-6 (5), 6-2, 7-5. Wearing a sleeveless shirt and his cap backward, the 30-year-old Moya hardly looked like an old-timer. But he became the oldest man to reach the final eight at the French Open since Andre Agassi in 2003. Moya has won two of his previous five matches against Nadal. "It's going to be a beautiful match to play," Moya said, "and very tough for both of us." Once ranked No. 1, Moya is playing in the tournament for the 12th year in a row. "Now I'm the oldest guy in the field," he said. "I still remember when I was the youngest guy in the draw, and now I became the oldest. Time passed so fast. ... "When you're younger, maybe you don't value things as I do now. I enjoy more now." Bjorkman, the oldest man in the 128-player draw, overcame deficits of two sets to none in the first two rounds. But this time he was the one squandering leads. The unseeded Swede was ahead 5-2 in the opening set but lost the next four games. He broke serve for 6-all and led 5-3 in the tiebreaker before Moya swept the final four points, the last with a net cord winner. Bjorkman began to show signs of wear after losing the second set, when he needed a shoulder massage from a trainer. "You know, I'm 35," Bjorkman said. "My shoulder just got more tired than it normally does. ... This is a great day. I obviously surprised myself to make the fourth round." He lost serve in the final game, pushing a tired backhand into the net on match point. The No. 23-seeded Moya, long known for his Popeye-size right biceps, hit 21 forehand winners to three for Bjorkman, and the disparity helped the Spaniard save 11 of the 14 break points he faced. Like Moya, the No. 6-seeded Djokovic benefited from a lucky bounce on an important point. It came in the tiebreaker, when his backhand kissed the net cord before dropping for a winner. Djokovic crossed himself in gratitude. Verdasco retrieved the ball and put it in his courtside bag, prompting laughter from the crowd. Verdasco shanked a forehand on match point, a fitting finish. The big-swinging Spaniard committed 50 unforced errors. By the middle of the second set, when Djokovic led 4-0, he had a frustrated Verdasco talking to himself. "I was stepping in more, and I was being aggressive," Djokovic said. "I played the best tennis in the important moments." He'll next face Andreev, who had a 19-6 edge in forehand winners against Baghdatis and punctuated his latest victory with a triumphant leap and uppercut. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://www.nbcsports.com/5thround/1591905/detail.html&cid=1116948476&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Golf - 5th Round Sunday Night Spotting Board Tampa Bay Devil Rays Hat Parade at Derby Matt Serra: UFC Champ On the Nationwide Tour Watch Poker After Dark Be the Ball - Fantasy Golf Sandbox on USA Today Golf - 5th Round Choi beams after winning Nicklaus' tournament When Jack Nicklaus wrote the instructional book "Golf My Way" with Ken Bowden in 1974, he probably couldn't have imagined his words reaching around the world to make an impression on a young man in Wando, South Korea. What were the odds that the teenager, Kyoung-Ju Choi, would someday win Jack's own tournament, the Memorial presented by Morgan Stanley, at the Muirfield Village Golf Club in Dublin, Ohio? A billion to one? "I can only think that this was meant to be," a beaming Choi said Sunday after he saved par on four of the final five holes, shot a brilliant 65 and won his idol's tournament by one stroke over hard-charging Ryan Moore. K.J. Choi came back from five strokes to win his fifth PGA Tour tournament. Such is the beauty of golf, which has exploded globally since Nicklaus was a young Golden Bear. The possibilities include a Korean boy giving up weightlifting to concentrate on a new sport and 20 years later standing next to his hero, clutching a trophy and a check for $1,080,000. "Definitely, it's very meaningful," Choi said of his fifth victory on the PGA Tour. "It's hard to describe how meaningful it is. I just feel very honored and very happy to be living in the same age, same period, same time as Jack is living." Choi, 37, began the final round on the rain-softened course five strokes behind leader Rod Pampling but ran off four consecutive birdies on Nos. 6-9 to take the lead. On the back nine, seemingly oblivious to the pressure, he made clutch par-saving putts of 4, 7, 15 and 5 feet. "It's my fifth time winning on Tour so I felt very comfortable," he said. "No pressure, really. The fact that it's Jack's tournament made me feel really comfortable." Choi needed a bit of help and he got it from Pampling, who bogeyed No. 17 from behind the green, and Adam Scott, who birdied Nos. 15 and 16 to pull within one but gave both strokes back with bogeys on Nos. 17 and 18. Pampling shot a 72 and tied for third and Scott shot a 70 and tied for fifth. Moore birdied Nos. 13-17 but couldn't make it six in a row on No. 18. He finished at 16-under and waited for Choi. "I felt helpless, for sure," Moore said. "I left it in his hands. I mean, he had control of the tournament. It was up to him and he played well obviously all week and all day … I'm just glad I posted a number and made him have to think about it a little bit." On the par-4 18th, Choi hit his approach into the left greenside bunker, the same one from which Paul Azinger holed out to win the 1993 Memorial. Choi blasted 5 feet past the hole and his par putt caught the ride side of the cup and tumbled in. "That was a very difficult putt," Nicklaus said. Choi's 65 tied the tournament's low final-round score by a winner and he jumped from 36th to eighth place on the FedEx Cup points list. He has the most victories by an Asian-born player on the PGA Tour (followed by Shigeki Maruyama of Japan with three). And it all started when a physical education teacher put a Korean-translated copy of "Golf My Way" into Choi's hands and told him he could succeed as a professional golfer if he studied Nicklaus' swing. "My physical education teacher at that time gave me the book as a present," Choi explained in his post-round news conference. "It just basically showed you how to grip, how to do the backswing and follow-through. Just the very basic fundamentals of golf. That's how I really got into golf is by reading that book." Nicklaus, sitting beside Choi, said: "You're entirely welcome. My pleasure." The status of Phil Mickelson's left wrist will be story going into the U.S. Open at Oakmont Country Club next week. Mickelson withdrew after 11 holes in the first round at Muirfield Village. He aggravated a sore left wrist when he hit a wedge shot out of a divot in the 11th fairway. He said he might have initially hurt the wrist last weekend while hitting chip shots out of the deep rough at Oakmont during one of his marathon practice sessions for the Open. It's a tough blow for Mickelson, whose 72nd-hole debacle cost him the 2006 U.S. Open title. He had been on a roll with his victory at The Players following a pair of third-place finishes. He said he hoped to be able to play in the Stanford St. Jude Championship this week. As of Monday morning he was still in the field. Johnny Benjamin, an orthopedic surgeon who has helped NBA star Allen Iverson and boxer Antonio Tarver overcome wrist injuries, said it was possible for Mickelson to be pain-free by the U.S. Open, depending on the severity of the soft-tissue injury. "The treatment usually is rest," Benjamin said. "It may require anti-inflammatories and maybe a cortisone injection. It's certainly likely he could be pain-free by the Open. When you're playing in something at that level and you're playing well, the adrenaline kicks in and the body's natural pain-relieving endorphins actually help ease the pain. It's funny, but if you're playing poorly it actually hurts more." Kenny Perry isn't ready for golf's scrap heap just yet. Perry, who endured a long drought in which he failed to post a top-10 finish in nearly two years, shot a 63 -- the lowest final-round score in the history of the Memorial --- and tied for third place. The 46-year-old golfer with the unorthodox swing missed just two fairways in what he described as a "magical" round. He holed out from the fairway for an eagle on the par-4 sixth and was 6-under after seven holes. "It was just a great day for me," he said. Perry underwent surgery on his right knee on March 13, 2006, and has struggled to regain the form that made him one of the top players on the PGA Tour. From 1987 to 2005, he won nine tournaments, including the Memorial twice, and finished among the top 30 on the money list eight times. "I couldn't make a cut two months ago," he said. "I haven't had a top 10 in almost two years now so ever since the knee surgery and all, I've really gotten behind. My golf swing, I was compensating for it and I really got in a lot of bad habits." In his tune-up for the U.S. Open, Tiger Woods salvaged a tie for 15th place with a 67. However, it was his worst finish at the Memorial since 2002 and he was never a factor in the tournament he won three years in succession (1999-2001). "I feel like I progressed nicely this week, which is what I wanted to do," said Woods, who was headed to Oakmont for a practice round Monday. CBS analyst Nick Faldo had one of the wittiest lines of the week -- and that's tough to do going head-to-head with David Feherty -- during the third round. In the broadcast booth, Nicklaus was asked if he had ever met Elvis Presley and said he hadn't. During the ensuing discussion, it was mentioned that Gary Player claimed to have given golf lessons to Presley. "Elvis probably taught Gary his hip movements, too," Faldo quipped. Mark Wilson posted seven consecutive birdies (Nos. 3-9) in the third round and shot a 29 on the front nine, matching the tournament record set by John Huston in the second round in 1996. The Stanford St. Jude Championship at the 7,244-yard, par-70 TPC Southwind course in Memphis. The final tune-up for the U.S. Open features a strong field including Sergio Garcia, Sean O'Hair, Geoff Ogilvy and Vijay Singh. Woods has finished outside the top 10 in his last two starts. The last time that happened was at the 2006 Bay Hill Invitational (T-20) and Players Championship (T-22). Gary D'Amato covers golf for the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel. Coming Up on NBC The Ducks are in Ottawa for Game 4. French Open action this weekend. K.J. Choi won by one stroke on the course that Jack built. Ladies of the links Some golfers do pretty well off the course, too. gang on Annika Sorenstam being a factor again. Phil Mickelson says his swing improved as TPC wore on. Clarke, McGinley fail to secure Open spot Castrale, Ochoa ready for major Choi's late clutch shots win Memorial Castrale goes OT to win Ginn Tribute Nicklaus lessons pay off for Choi Roberts soars to Boeing Championship MRI shows no break in Mickelson's wrist Leonard, Azinger, Clarke commit to Buick Castrale beats Ochoa in Ginn Tribute playoff 5 Things You Didn't Know ... Memorial Tournament Final Round at the Memorial Early Nicklaus lessons pay off for Choi Nicklaus: World is gaining on U.S. golfers Perry Gets His Game Back Pampling takes lead at Memorial O'Hair birdies into TPC lead 2007 Golf on NBC telecast schedule Nicklaus lessons pay off for Choi Castrale goes OT to win Ginn Tribute European win sends Hansen to U.S. Open Castrale, Ochoa ready for major >> More most popular Tiger retains FedExCup points lead Phil Mickelson may be O.K. Ernie Els one shot back at Memorial Wie injured and withdraws from Ginn Fujikawa fails in U.S. Open sectional bid Sabbatini moves up in rankings Hansen wins the BMW PGA Championship &copy; 2007 NBC Universal. All rights reserved. Any use reproduction, modification, distribution, display or performance of this material without NBC Universal's prior written consent is prohibited. WE HAVE UPDATED OUR PRIVACY POLICY FOR THIS SITE AS OF 02/01/2007. PLEASE CLICK TO VIEW OUR NEW PRIVACY POLICY. BY USING THIS WEB SITE, YOU ARE AGREEING TO BE BOUND BY OUR
