http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-1&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/scorecard/nbanews.asp%3FarticleID%3D203698&cid=1116547509&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Skip ads and navigation Monday, June 04, 2007 Keys to victory in the NBA Finals By Warren Blatt, Sports Network NBA Editor (Sports Network) - The San Antonio Spurs are back in the NBA Finals for the fourth time in nine years, while the Cleveland Cavaliers are getting their first taste of the championship round. There is plenty of star power in this best-of-seven series. It took just four years for superstar LeBron James to lead Cleveland to the top of the Eastern Conference. Forward Drew Gooden and center Zydrunas Ilgauskas will need to make an impact down low if the Cavaliers want to keep up with the physical Spurs, while rookie Daniel Gibson has to continue his hot shooting from the outside. The veteran Spurs will not be overwhelmed by the atmosphere of the finals. All-Stars Tim Duncan, who leads the Spurs in scoring (23.2 ppg) and rebounding (11.4 rpg) in the playoffs, and Tony Parker are primed to help the San Antonio franchise earn its fourth championship trophy. Thirty-six-year-old forward Robert Horry, who already has six championship rings, is always ready to knock down the big shot, while Bruce Bowen and Manu Ginobili will do whatever it takes to help their squad win the hardware. San Antonio head coach Gregg Popovich has been the general for all three of the Spurs' championship runs, while Cleveland's Mike Brown, who earned a ring as an assistant with San Antonio in 2003, has guided the Cavaliers to the playoffs in both seasons he has been on their bench. Popovich will try and figure out how to stop James, and Brown must keep his team composed and hope his superstar forward gets a lot of help from his teammates. Both clubs will try and take advantage of any weakness that the opposition reveals. Defensive strategies, matchups, offensive execution and tough, hard- nosed play will have a major impact on this series. CAVALIERS KEYS TO VICTORY -------------------------- 1. HELP LEBRON - Cleveland will not be able to beat the Spurs with a one-man show. As good as the 22-year-old James is, San Antonio is too physical and plays great team defense. The Spurs will try and make LeBron pick up his dribble early and will close the middle when he goes to penetrate. Larry Hughes, Donyell Marshall and Gibson have to step up. If they can hit their shots early from the outside it will open the floor for James and allow the big men to get on track in the low post. The Spurs will have to adjust defensively if LeBron, who is averaging 25.8 points, 8.3 boards and 8.3 assists in the playoffs, gets good support from his teammates. Cleveland's superstar forward will get his points, and if his supporting cast comes through the Cavaliers may have a chance. 2. ILGAUSKAS AND GOODEN HAVE TO SCORE - The Cavaliers need to establish a low- post game if they hope to beat the Spurs in a best-of-seven series. The 7-3 Ilgauskas is averaging 13.8 points and team-best 9.5 rebounds in the postseason, while Gooden has posted 11.1 points and 7.9 boards per game. Ilgauskas and Gooden were solid in the Eastern Conference playoffs, but they need to do more against Duncan and company in the finals. Cleveland won't beat the Spurs four times with threes and 20-foot jumpers. It may work for one game, but not in a long series. The Cavaliers need Ilgauskas and Gooden to make a very high percentage of their shots from around the basket. 3. CONTROL THE BOARDS - Physical play down low is going to be a major factor in this set. Any advantage the Cavaliers can get will be extremely beneficial, and controlling the boards is a great place to start for the Eastern Conference champions. Gooden, Ilgauskas and Anderson Varejao, who is averaging 6.1 rebounds in the postseason, have a tough job ahead of them. They will try to keep San Antonio from getting good looks close to the hoop, and have to keep the Spurs from picking up garbage points off of offensive rebounds. One and done will be the theme of Cleveland's work on the defensive glass, while the Cavaliers will look to push Duncan and the rest of the Spurs big men out so they can grab some offense rebounds which lead to easy points. Outrebounding the Spurs on both ends of the court will be huge for the Cavaliers. SPURS KEYS TO VICTORY ---------------------- 1. MAKE LEBRON EARN HIS POINTS FROM THE OUTSIDE - Team defense is the way to stop James. Every time LeBron has the ball, the Spurs will look to double and even triple team him. Bowen, Michael Finley and Ginobili will all get their chance to matchup with the phenom, and all three will need help as guarding him one-on-one with the way he is playing is simply too much to ask of anyone. Against Detroit in the East finals, LeBron was very effective moving towards the basket. The Spurs need to force him to pick up his dribble and settle for long jumpers. If they can do that, James will have to either dish the ball or take a tough shot. Limiting James' penetration is going to put the pressure on Cleveland's other players. 2. DON'T ALLOW CLEVELAND TO GET OUT IN TRANSITION - Not allowing the Cavaliers to run is a must for San Antonio. Once again, it all comes back to LeBron. If Cleveland is running and getting easy points in transition, that means the Spurs are getting outrebounded and are not playing their brand of basketball. By keeping the East champs from getting out in transition, the Spurs will take away a major part of James' game. Duncan and friends have to control the tempo and make the game a half-court contest. San Antonio has the experience and intelligence to keep the games at its pace. 3. GIVE PARKER ROOM TO CREATE AND WATCH DUNCAN DO HIS THING - Parker, who is averaging 19.8 points and a club-high 6.4 assists in the postseason, should be able to do whatever he wants against Cleveland, while Duncan is playing like a man on a mission and has been a force for the Spurs. Parker's speed is a big asset for San Antonio and will help his teammates get open shots. The 6-2 Parker and Duncan are arguably the top inside-outside combination in the league. Duncan has a soft touch around the basket and from 15-to-18 feet away, while Parker can penetrate, drain the long jumper and has excellent play-making ability. The Cavaliers will have a tough time keeping up with Parker, and the Spurs' point guard could be a shining star in this set. Popovich will game plan offensively around on how Duncan and Parker can exploit Cleveland's defense. Climbing Mount St. Helens Day of Week Records Ray Allen: Lewis, Durant would mesh just fine Pre-Draft Notebook: Sonics turn attention to second round LeBron's big game took its toll For Donovan, pieces all came together Column: Will King James be coronated? Source: Donovan wants out of Magic deal Donovan wants out of deal with Magic LeBron graduates to NBA superstardom James takes Cavs to their 1st NBA finals Day of Week Records P-I staff blog on the NBA GM search apparently down to two Thursday from Orlando -- Hawes sighting Wednesday morning in Orlando Group claims captured troops were killed Rep. Jefferson indicted in bribery probe Bush opens Europe trip on jarring note Guantanamo judge dismisses terror case Group denies link to NYC terror plot Radio bra contest fined in Singapore 8 sets of twins to graduate high school Teens spared in impotent ostrich case 1,683 guitarists play 'Smoke on Water' Indiana kangaroo dies after capture After a half-century in the skies, pilot made mistake No. 1 Microsoft strikes another Linux deal Software Notebook: Is Microsoft turning into a hardware company? As 'Sopranos' end nears, so does Tony's Supreme Court reinstates death sentence for man convicted in carjacking, rape, murder After a half-century in the skies, pilot made mistake No. 1 Workplace Coach: Don't underestimate emotional intelligence Ann's Organic Garden: Do you know what's really in that hose? Schools s