http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-6&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601100%26sid%3DaLoQlHTXS0vE%26refer%3Dgermany&cid=1116936543&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ , Jun 04 17:17 , Jun 04 22:17 , Jun 05 06:17 Australia & New Zealand Nadal, Moya Win to Reach French Open Quarterfinals (Update3) By Ravi Ubha and James Cone June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Rafael Nadal eased past Lleyton Hewitt at the French Open to set up a quarterfinal against his tennis mentor, Carlos Moya. Novak Djokovic and Igor Andreev also advanced. Nadal won 6-3, 6-1, 7-6 (7-5) today at the lone clay-court major in Paris, a month after Hewitt stretched him to the maximum three sets in the semifinals of the Hamburg Masters. Like top-seed Roger Federer, Nadal hasn&#39;t dropped a set in four matches. ``I played 10 times better today than the last days, no?&#39;&#39; Nadal said in his post-match news conference. ``I am very much in the tournament right now. I&#39;m more confident.&#39;&#39; Nadal, the No. 2 seed from Spain, is trying to become the first man since Bjorn Borg 27 years ago to win three straight titles in Paris. Federer needs the title to complete his Grand Slam collection. The 30-year-old Moya, the 1998 winner, won 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, 7-5 over Jonas Bjorkman to become the oldest man to reach the quarterfinals since Andre Agassi in 2003, when he was 33. Bjorkman, a 35-year-old Swede, was aiming to become the third player his age or older to make the quarterfinals in Paris. ``I&#39;m proud to be the oldest guy left,&#39;&#39; Moya said in his post-match news conference. ``I remember when I was the youngest guy. The time passes so fast, and you don&#39;t realize it.&#39;&#39; Djokovic, the sixth-seeded Serb, defeated Fernando Verdasco of Spain 6-3, 6-3, 7-6 (7-1) to secure a spot in the last eight for the second straight year. Serbia&#39;s Jelena Jankovic and Ana Ivanovic earlier reached the last eight in the women&#39;s draw. Djokovic next meets Andreev, who beat 2006 Australian Open runner-up Marcos Baghdatis of Cyprus 2-6, 6-1, 6-3, 6-4 to reach his first Grand Slam quarterfinal. Andreev began the tournament by eliminating third-seeded Andy Roddick of the U.S. Nadal, who turned 21 yesterday, moved Hewitt, a former No. 1-ranked player and two-time Grand Slam champion, around the baseline and built a 5-1 lead within about 20 minutes. In the first six games, he lost just four points on his serve. Nadal continued to dominate from the back of the court, and Hewitt became so frustrated that at one point when his shot hit the top of the net, he yelled, ``Get over.&#39;&#39; The shot did, though it landed out. In the second set, Nadal went up 3-1, then saved his only break point of the set in the next game. He broke at 5-5 in the third to serve for the match. With the crowd at Philippe Chatrier Court behind him, Hewitt broke Nadal to force the tiebreak and led 4-2. Up 5-4, the Australian&#39;s first serve forced Nadal into a weak return, giving Hewitt a short ball and an open court. Hewitt&#39;s forehand shot found the net. Nadal won the next point at the net and closed it out on another forehand error by Hewitt. ``I went for a little too much,&#39;&#39; Hewitt said. ``But that&#39;s what he makes you do.&#39;&#39; Moya said his friendship with Nadal would be put aside in their quarterfinal. ``Rafa will be a rival,&#39;&#39; he said. ``When you are on the court, you want to win the match, whatever the manner.&#39;&#39; Bjorkman said he knew he would struggle against Moya after their match was scheduled on Suzanne Lenglen Court, not the main one, because it&#39;s slower. Bjorkman was up 5-3 in the opening set before letting the lead slip away and losing in the tie-break, which he led 5-3. ``It was just unfortunate I couldn&#39;t take the first set,&#39;&#39; said Bjorkman, who last reached the fourth round in Paris in 1996. ``At least it would have put some pressure on him.&#39;&#39; Bjorkman, also in the doubles draw, received treatment to his right shoulder to start the third set, when he was broken in the final game. The 20-year-old Djokovic, the youngest player remaining in the draw, beat Verdasco for the first time in three meetings to match his best Grand Slam performance. It was his first match against a player inside the top 120 at Roland Garros this year after beating a qualifier, a player invited as a wild-card entry and a qualifying round loser who made the field when a player dropped out. His previous match, against Frenchman Olivier Patience, went to five sets and lasted five hours. ``Against Olivier it was probably much more difficult because I wasn&#39;t playing my game, and I was playing against 10,000 fans,&#39;&#39; Djokovic said. ``Today I was playing really solid and it showed on court.&#39;&#39; He got the decisive break in the fourth game of the opening set and started the second with another break to cruise to a two-set lead against Verdasco, a left-hander known for his forehand and unpredictability. The third set went with serve to force a tie-break. Djokovic won the first two points and never trailed, virtually clinching it at 3-1 when his backhand hit the top of the net and trickled over. Djokovic apologized, and Verdasco let out a big smile. The match ended on a Verdasco mishit. Baghdatis, playing his first major with a new coach, won the final six games to take the first set. Andreev&#39;s forehand took over, and the unseeded Russian won nine of the next 10 games. One break separated them in the fourth. ``He hurt me quite a lot with his forehand,&#39;&#39; Baghdatis, seeded 16th, said. ``I have a feeling it&#39;s even more powerful than that of Nadal.&#39;&#39; To contact the reporters on this story: James Cone at Roland Garros through the London office at +44- ; Ravi Ubha at Roland Garros through the London office at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 14:23 EDT German Stocks Beat Europe, Emerging Markets, Emulating &#39;60s Earnings Gains DAX Index Slides, Led by E.ON, Deutsche Bank, Siemens; ThyssenKrupp Rises European Stocks Drop, Paced by Banks on Downgrade; Deutsche Bank, BNP Fall
http://www.theage.com.au/news/motorsport/stoner-gets-a-break-to-grab-pole-position/2007/06/03/1180809340013.html&cid Stoner gets a break to grab pole position - Motorsport - Sport - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. Stoner gets a break to grab pole position Mat Mladin (No. 66) is on route for his sixth win this year as he heads Ben Spies in Saturday's AMA superbike race in Wisconsin. The Doctor makes it six in a row Vermeulen shines on wet track Rossi pans tyres as Vermeulen wins in wet MOTOGP championship leader Casey Stoner made the most of a rain-affected qualifying session to claim pole position for the Italian grand prix run overnight (Melbourne time). The 21-year-old Australian, who has won three of this season's five races, took advantage of a brief respite in the rain to lap the 5.245-kilometre circuit at Mugello in two minutes 0.359 seconds, 1.022 seconds ahead of the Suzuki of compatriot Chris Vermeulen. The sun came out for the last 10 minutes of the session, drying the track and allowing seven-times world champion Valentino Rossi to grab the third place on the front row, 1.336 seconds behind Stoner. Stoner admitted he had not foreseen the deluge that ended rivals' hopes of bettering his time. "I put down the lap that gave me pole, then it seemed to be getting drier, so I came in to get new tyres," he said. "Two minutes later, it poured down. I just crossed my fingers that it would continue. I think at the end, the conditions were almost there for the other riders to beat my lap time, but luckily the track didn't dry out fast enough." Rossi was relieved the rain had stopped long enough for him to avoid starting on the third row of the grid. "It's the worst conditions for qualifying practice. First wet, then dry. At first, I was only eighth (fastest)," said the Italian, who is second in the championship race and aiming to notch up his sixth MotoGP win in six years here. There was no joy, however, for champion Nicky Hayden. The American could manage only 13th on his Honda, nearly four seconds adrift of Stoner. &#9632;Australia's Mat Mladin moved to outright leader of the American Motorcyclist Association series when he defeated Ben Spies on the Lake Elkhart circuit in Wisconsin. Mladin defeated his Yoshimura Suzuki teammate to record his sixth win this season and his fourth in a row. The superbike win was the 57th of Mladin's career. It extended his championship lead over Spies to six points, 276 to 270, after eight of the 19 races. &#9632; Australia's Marcos Ambrose has earned his best NASCAR Busch Series finish with a sixth in the Dover 200 at Dover International Speedway, Delaware, on Saturday. Ambrose drove a superb race in his Ford at the challenging 1.6-kilometre concrete speedway known as "The Monster Mile" to better his previous best finish in the second-tier Busch Series, an eighth on the Mexico City road course. The finish won Ambrose his fourth, and second in succession, rookie of the race award. Ambrose, 30, rose to eighth in the series points standings and is the equal leader of the rookie of the year standings. &#9632; Finland's Marcus Gronholm has avoided major mishaps to maintain his lead in the Acropolis Rally, the eighth round of the 16-race world championship, as Australia's Chris Atkinson slipped from third to sixth. Gronholm was leading by 43.3 seconds from three-time reigning world champion Sebastien Loeb of France and one minute 7.6 seconds in front of Norway's Petter Solberg. Atkinson, who won the event's first two stages, fell from third overnight to be 5:25 behind Gronholm. A puncture and driveshaft failure soured what had been a bright start for the Australian. AGENCIES When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! The Doctor makes it six in a row Vermeulen shines on wet track Rossi pans tyres as Vermeulen wins in wet Stoner gets a break to grab pole position Mat Mladin (No. 66) is on route f