http://www.mercurynews.com/sportsheadlines/ci_6051327&cid San Jose Mercury News - U.S. steps over China in exhibition san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) Southwest jet skids after landing gear collapses in Oakland Parents of TB patient are 'in hell' Informant helped bust alleged JFK plot Roadshow: Value of carpool lanes in dispute, but more on way Kawakami: Blame must fall on Giants' G.M. Sabean, and it's time to go Better times bring worse traffic U.S. steps over China in exhibition Square field sharpens team Article Launched: 06/03/2007 01:46:12 AM PDT USA soccer beats China, 4-1, at Spartan Stadium in San Jose on June 2 Fresh faces from faraway places Players were missing and the field wasn't wide enough, but the U.S. national soccer team had little problem dismantling China 4-1 Saturday at Spartan Stadium in front of 20,821 fans in its final tuneup for its regional championships. With its Gold Cup opener against Guatemala only five days away, Team USA handed Bob Bradley his fourth victory - and first without an interim tag attached to his title - on goals by DaMarcus Beasley, Benny Feilhaber, Clint Dempsey and Oguchi Onyewu. Missing from Bradley's lineup were the domestically based players whose Major League Soccer teams had games this weekend, including former Earthquakes forward Landon Donovan. But more problematic for the United States was the field. Listed at an already-narrow 70 yards wide but probably closer to being 65, the postage-stamp-sized playing surface allowed China to clog the midfield and disrupt the flow of the game. "Spartan's a hard place to play because it's so narrow," U.S. midfielder Sacha Kljestan said. "It's like an indoor game." But the United States needed only 10 minutes to go ahead, as coach's son Michael Bradley slid a ball behind the Chinese back line to a streaking Beasley, who was tripped in the penalty box by goalkeeper Chen Dong. Beasley buried the resulting penalty kick. But the game that seemed to be on its way to a blowout took a sudden turn. With the Chinese flooding the center and the field too narrow to play the ball down the flanks, the United States lost its rhythm. China started to move forward and tied the score at 1-1 in the 15th minute when Zhang Yaokun hammered in a loose ball near the top of the penalty box. The Chinese nearly went ahead in the 19th minute when captain Shao Jiayi bent a free kick to the left goal post that was pushed out by diving goalkeeper Tim Howard. "If you stop moving as well or if you don't go a good job of moving up your lines, in a five- or 10-minute segment you can step backwards" at Spartan, said Bradley, the coach. But Feilhaber, a 22-year-old midfielder who plays for Hamburg SV of Germany, fired the United States back ahead. Feilhaber ran onto a ball from Sacha Kljestan and flicked it over an onrushing Chen. Zhang tried to clear the bouncing ball but failed to change its trajectory, resulting in a 2-1 lead for the United States. "We allowed them to get back in the game but we reacted well," Onyewu said. Dempsey increased the United States' advantage to 3-1 in the 75th minute by nodding home a corner kick by Feilhaber. The shot was Dempsey's third at point-back range in the half; he blew one-on-ones with Chen in the 65th and 73rd minutes. "I had two good chances I could've put away," Dempsey said. "It was good to the get the monkey off my back." Another header, this one by Onyewu on the end of a free kick by Beasley in the 79th minute, accounted for the final U.S. goal. Whatever problems the field posed, Bob Bradley thought they would benefit his team in the long run. "Any time you play in San Jose on this field, the fact that it's small, it sharpens up a lot of things," he said. Kamani Hill of Berkeley, a 21-year-old forward who plays for Vfl Wolfsburg of Germany, made his international debut as a 74th-minute substitute for Kljestan. Hill's parents and younger brother were in the stands. "I grew up watching games here," Hill said. Also playing in their first games for the United States were Kljestan, forward Charlie Davies and wing Lee Nguyen. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Sorry, no items are currently available. Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
