http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-2&fd=R&url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-duckrep5jun05,0,985324.story%3Fcoll%3Dla-home-sports&cid=1116235930&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation - Los Angeles Times 2:17 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 Buy, Sell & More Deals at Local Stores Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation With the defenseman suspended for game 4, center Pahlsson says every player will have to step up if they're to have any chance at winning. By Lonnie White, Times Staff Writer 1:06 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 OTTAWA -- After getting roughed up by Ottawa in Game 3, the Ducks probably wouldn't have needed any more incentive for Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals. But they found more anyway with the one-game suspension of defenseman , who will sit out his second game of these playoffs for his hit to the head of Senators forward "I wish I could say that I was surprised with the suspension, but I can't," Ducks forward said. "It's unfortunate, but we're going to use it as motivation. That's something you can never have too much of." With the Senators getting a lift from their crowd on Saturday, the Ducks realize that they have to play with more composure if they want to take a 3-1 lead back to Anaheim for Wednesday's Game 5. "It's going to be a game where everyone is going to have to help, not just the guys who are going to play minutes" in Pronger's place, Ducks center said. "We know that we're going to have to play our best game." told reporters Monday morning that the Ducks have been down this road before. "It's a piece of adversity that we've talked about &#91;how&#93; we've dealt with it historically," Carlyle said, referring to an early season stretch when because of various injuries, the Ducks played without goaltender "Key players out of our lineup for almost up to the All Star break. And those are the things that your team learns in the regular season, but, obviously, in the playoffs, it's a little different." McAmmond, who did not return after suffering a head injury as a result of Pronger's hit, skated with his teammates Monday morning and will be a game-time decision. "I actually feel pretty good considering," said McAmmond, who took a shot to the chin courtesy of Pronger. "As far as if I'm going to play tonight, I'm just going to continue on with my day and see how I feel later." said he's not sure whether McAmmond will be ready. "Obviously, we have to talk to the doctors before we let him play, but he's trying," Murray said. "He'd like to play. But in talking to him, he's certainly not 100% at this moment." McAmmond, a key player on the Senators' speed line and penalty kill who scored his first goal of the finals in Game 3, said he's not going to force himself into the lineup if he doesn't feel right. "The headache seems to be going away," McAmmond said. "The neck seems to be loosening up with movement. That's pretty good, but there's other things, too. Just sometimes, if you ever got clunked in the head, you go along, some things you just know aren't right. "If I get out on the ice and I don't feel quite right, then I don't feel like I should be in a situation trying to help this team win. If I'm out there killing a penalty and I don't feel confident that I can compete 100%, then I would not put myself in that situation, or the team. "Again, if I feel confident that I can compete at 100%, then I think everything is a go." That would not shock Carlyle, who said: "Nothing would surprise me. It's playoffs. It's what happens. People make huge strides in their recovery after suspensions. It's amazing." Carlyle also talked about Ducks winger , who suffered an abdominal bruise in a collision in Game 3. "You never risk a player's health or well-being," Carlyle said of Kunitz, who had just returned after sitting out seven games with a broken hand. "Every player will tell you he's ready. This is the Stanley Cup final. Sometimes you have to make a decision that the player doesn't agree with but you don't want to jeopardize a player's chances to come back at a later date." If Kunitz does not play, rookie , who played the first two games of the finals, is expected to take his spot in the lineup. By Andrew and Brian Kamenetzky Blue Notes -- A Dodgers Blog By Andrew and Brian Kamenetzky LeBron vs. Kobe: a new round of fighting words Former NASCAR chief Bill France Jr. dies Ducks see Pronger's absence as motivation Copyright 2007 Los Angeles Times FSBO (For Sale By Owner) Boodle.com for Grocery Coupons Recycler for Free Classifieds
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-1&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html%3Fid%3D53ab3206-14f7-48ec-abed-da0bd4f1be0f%26k%3D47115&cid=1116235930&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ McAmmond's status in air heading into game (11:21 am) canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter canada.com where perspectives connect in The Vancouver Sun Jobs in Vancouver working.com 10 year archive in FPinfomart See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter Road to 2010 Olympics Find a job at working.com Find a car at driving.ca Find an apartment at renting.ca Find real estate at homes Find great stuff at shopping Selling? Place an ad Meet a match at Connecting Headlines marked with a are exclusive to subscribers. Update credit card information Send us a news tip Apologies could cost, feds warned OTTAWA -- The Harper government has been warned it may be opening the door to a ... Eastern European 'pirates' find some Internet booty on BC Ferries website Compost sites get low rating Butcher describes how pigs were slaughtered Judge slams Crown in Basi, Virk trial (12:33 pm) McAmmond's status in air heading into game (11:21 am) Cam Cole, Vancouver Sun Published:Â Monday, June 04, 2007 Ottawa The only thing missing from the picture that appeared in today's Vancouver Sun - of Ottawa Senators centre Dean McAmmond being helped off the ice by teammates Saturday night - was a flock of cartoon birds circling his head going tweet-tweet. And as you were perusing that photo, he was already thinking about playing Game 4 of the Stanley Cup playoffs last night. Senators coach Bryan Murray said it would be a doctor's decision first, and then a coach's game-time decision if he were to be cleared medically. Email to a friend "Nothing would surprise me," Anaheim Ducks coach Randy Carlyle said, when he heard the news. "It's playoffs. It's what happens. People make huge strides in their recovery after suspensions. It's amazing." McAmmond, whose head was emptied of all thought or sense of time and place by Chris Pronger's elbow in the third period of Game 3 - a crime for which the Anaheim defenceman was handed a one-game suspension - made the victim's statement of impact Monday morning, and his words brought home how frighteningly close every NHL player is to having his career derailed or ended in a moment of recklessness by an opposing player. "It's different having a head injury like this," said the 34-year-old journeyman from Grande Cache, Alta. "I got knocked out in Calgary a few years ago. At that time, it was like a mandatory seven-day period of rest that you had to have if you lost consciousness." That was then. This is playoffs. As NHL general managers met in a nearby hotel, with the subject of head blows on the agenda, the length of Pronger's suspension, his second in three weeks, was kicked around a good deal by both teams. "I think when you have an elbow, a punch, something that really puts a guy in jeopardy, I think we have to address that," said Sens coach Bryan Murray. "And the player in all likelihood should be eliminated from the game immediately - five and a game, and then the hockey department rule, whether it be a one-game suspension, they have to determine the seriousness of it. And maybe the whole issue was if the [victim] is out for five games, [the perpetrator] sits five games. I don't know if that's the solution or not, but it's a thought." McAmmond doesn't remember the second intermission of Game 3 or the events leading up to the hit. He does remember when a teammate in Calgary, Matthew Lombardi, took a Derian Hatcher elbow in the head during the 2004 playoffs and had to go through 11 months of forced inactivity with post-concussion syndrome. "I think he was still having repercussions of it when I saw him in the minors almost a year later," said McAmmond. "There was no suspension, and again, same type of incident." But McAmmond doesn't think the length of the suspension should be tied to the amount of time the victim is out. "It depends on the person, how they react to the incident," he said. "I think you should kind of look at the hit and judge it by the flagrancy there, and not matter if the guy is up the next minute or a whole year. In my opinion, just go by the foul or the incident alone, and make it strict enough that it will keep guys from raising their elbows. "I know [with the new rules on] hooking and holding, sometimes I don't even want to bring my stick on the ice it's called so much. So we'll see how that helps." McAmmond rode the stationary bike for several minutes Monday morning and skated lightly. "I didn't have as much discomfort. But because of the kind of the whiplash, I have a lot of stiffness in my neck and whatnot. So it's kind of tough to differentiate the pain." "On the ice, shooting the puck, do you feel discomfort now?" a reporter asked. "For about 16 years now," he said. KUNITZ TBA - Chris Kunitz, the Ducks' first-line winger who came back from a broken hand only to suffer what the team is calling an abdominal bruise in the first period of Game 3, is available to play tonight but Carlyle never reveals roster choices until the official lineup sheet is filled out a few minutes before game time ... Sixth defenceman Joe DiPenta, who played most of the first three rounds of the playoffs but has sat out since Ric Jackman returned from a back injury, will take Pronger's place on the roster. Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in Montreal... Mexican crime won't stop Canadians Canadians took more trips abroad... Go topless this summer A sure sign of spring is the sight... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
