http://www.mercurynews.com/sports/ci_6055851&cid San Jose Mercury News - Column: Will King James be coronated? san jose / valley start / stop paper Mercury News Sports Blogs (From the last 24 hours) Southwest jet skids after landing gear collapses in Oakland Parents of TB patient are 'in hell' Informant helped bust alleged JFK plot Roadshow: Value of carpool lanes in dispute, but more on way Kawakami: Blame must fall on Giants' G.M. Sabean, and it's time to go Better times bring worse traffic Column: Will King James be coronated? By JIM LITKE AP Sports Columnist Article Launched: 06/04/2007 12:49:19 AM PDT Click photo to enlarge Cleveland Cavaliers' LeBron James hoists the trophy after the Cavaliers beat the Detroit Pistons, 98-82, to win the NBA Eastern Conference championship Saturday, June 2, 2007, in Cleveland. Four years after skipping college for the pros, James completed his degree in superstardom with four straight clutch performances over the Detroit Pistons to earn the Cavaliers their first trip to the NBA finals. Four days later, people are still debating where LeBron James' 25 straight points to end Game 5 ranks on the NBA's list of all-time best finishes. The only point worth adding is this: Whoever has James' ear between now and Thursday can serve the King best by reminding him that better be just the beginning. James better have a few more games like that in him, and we're not talking during the course of his career, but over the next two weeks. Otherwise, this will be remembered as the NBA finals that he got close enough to see his reflection in the Larry O'Brien Trophy&mdash;and not much else. It's easy to forget how tricky it can be for even the brightest young star to trace a learning curve that reaches the top without a single dip, maybe because Miami's Dwyane Wade did it only last year. James, to his credit, didn't need reminding. He recently described climbing over the Pistons and out of the Eastern Conference in just his second try as "another chapter in my book, I guess." But James also understands he won't write that happy ending without help. The tough part will be deciding how much to accept. "If I get double-teamed and the game is close, I'm going to pass it again," James said, despite catching flak for doing just that at the start of the Detroit series. "If we make the shot, I'm on top of the world. If not, then I'm under a lot of trees and leaves. It's fine with me. I'll take the criticism that comes with it. There's a nice bit of symmetry in having the Spurs stand between James and that shiny piece of hardware he wants so much. The Cavaliers have modeled themselves as the Spurs of the East, and two of their chief decision-makers, coach Mike Brown and GM Danny Ferry, actually did their management training in San Antonio. But the sharing arrangement, not to mention a real resemblance, pretty much ends there. The only coronation the Spurs plan on attending anytime soon is their own. They can grab their fourth championship since 1999, a run of titles that might finally garner San Antonio and reluctant superstar Tim Duncan the respect and recognition that has so far consistently lagged behind their accomplishments. The Spurs last appearance in the finals, against Detroit in 2005, was almost the opposite situation from what James and the Cavs will be facing this time around. It was framed as a referendum on whether Duncan was truly a great player, or just a very good one lucky enough to land in San Antonio when the Spurs boasted a deep and better-than-average supporting cast. As that series stretched out toward Game 7, the NBA's promotional tagline for the series, "Where Legends Are Born," began to sound like a dare. Duncan responded with 25 points, 11 rebounds, two blocks and three assists. Nearly all the numbers flowed easily from the Spurs game plan, except for a stretch late in the third quarter when Duncan scored nearly half his total and grabbed the game by the throat. In a hallway afterward, former teammate David Robinson savored the win and that third-quarter as much as any of Duncan's then-teammates. "Some people talked about Tim like a dog. The way that man has performed over the years, I don't understand that," said Robinson, who partnered Duncan for two of San Antonio's titles. "For him to dig down tonight and show everybody what he's made of is just awesome, unbelievable. He settled it the best way." Unfortunately, James doesn't have Robinson, Manu Ginobili, Tony Parker or even Robert Horry to take over the show long enough to catch his breath. And unlike Wade, Shaquille O'Neal won't be there to cover his back. If James is going to win a championship this year, he's going to have to do it the same way he just sent Detroit packing: largely on his own. The 25 points in a row that closed out Game 5 was part of a 48-point night that got most of the attention. But James' performances on either side of that game were almost as good. He averaged 33 points, 11 rebounds and eight assists. James can't afford much slippage if Cleveland is going to have a chance. So Spurs coach Gregg Popovich wasn't exaggerating when he said, "Pick a problem, we have it, with LeBron. He's fantastic in every way so, pick any aspect of the game, he's a problem." But more telling was something that Duncan said a little later. "You have to respect someone like that and focus a little more of the attention toward him. "But they're going to need a team to beat us," he added, "LeBron's not going to do it by himself." Jim Litke is a national sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Little League tries strong-arm tactics with mandated pitch counts James, Cavaliers taking Cleveland to rare heights French Open: Sharapova survives; Federer ties record; a rivalry is renewed UCLA ousts Long Beach St. Motor sports: Maddening Milwaukee Ports strike late to beat S.J. Giants Abbott vaults Lady Vols into softball series finals Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007542686&cid AHN | Denver Signs DT Sam Adams, Vet Solidifies Defensive Line | June 4, 2007 global news for the digital world Denver Signs DT Sam Adams, Vet Solidifies Defensive Line June 4, 2007 3:01 p.m. EST Matt Aug - AHN Sports Writer Denver, CO (AHN) - Sam Adams will put some "crush" back into the Denver Broncos defensive line this season. Denver has signed the veteran tackle to a one-year deal in order to shore up the team's run defense. Financial terms of the deal weren't disclosed on the signing of the 33-year-old, who was released earlier this week by the Cincinnati Bengals. The remarkably durable player started in all 16 games for the Bengals in 2006, recording a pair of sacks. The 14-year veteran was an impressive run-stopper for a team that went 8-8 last season and is perhaps looking to get younger under coach Marvin Lewis. Adams, who has played in 195 games in his career with 166 starts, has registered 452 tackles, 44 sacks and six forced fumbles in stops that included Seattle, Baltimore, Oakland and Buffalo. Despite the Bengals concern about his age, Adams has been virtually injury free in his career, missing just 13 games. His immense size, 6-foot-3, 350 pounds, makes him a force to be reckoned with on the line and is very difficult to move out of position when teams try to run his direction. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-6&fd=R&url=http://www.ohio.com/mld/beaconjournal/sports/basketball/17321166.htm&cid=1116948476&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Beacon Journal | 06/04/2007 | Choi thanks his hero Monday, Jun 04, 2007 Posted on Mon, Jun. 04, 2007 reprint or license this Choi thanks his hero Nicklaus inspiration for Memorial champion When K.J. Choi was 16 years old, his high school physical education teacher in South Korea gave him a now-priceless gift. It was a pictorial instruction book by Jack Nicklaus, probably The teacher told Choi he might find a good future as a professional in the sport and directed him to faithfully follow Nicklaus' teachings. ``My teacher kept emphasizing, `This is a book written by a very famous golfer, so keep reading it,' '' Choi said. ``As I started, I could understand why he was such a great golfer because all the things really started to make sense.'' Twenty-one years later, Choi got an opportunity to say, ``Thank you, Jack'' for the book that inspired his career. Choi fired a 7-under-par 65 Sunday at Muirfield Village Golf Club and his 17-under 271 total earned him a 1-stroke victory over Ryan Moore in the Memorial Tournament founded by Nicklaus. The famous author responded: ``You're entirely welcome. My pleasure.'' Choi, 37, used his masterful putting to record the biggest victory of his five on the PGA Tour. He birdied six holes on the front nine to grab the lead, added another birdie at No. 11, survived his only hiccup, a bogey at No. 13, and got that stroke back at the par-5 15th when he two-putted from 30 feet. But the key to claiming the $1.08 million first-place prize were his par-saves, including a 5-foot putt on No. 18 after he landed in the greenside ``Azinger'' bunker. He made six one-putts on the back nine, five to save par. ``It's hard to describe in words how meaningful it is,'' Choi said through an interpreter, Michael Yim. ``I feel very honored and very happy to be living in the same time as Jack and to win his tournament. I can only think that this was meant to be. God planned all this to happen and I just want to thank God for today.'' Two-time Memorial winner Kenny Perry returned to his 2003 form after months of misery with the day's low round of 63 and tied for third with Australia's Rod Pampling. Pampling, who started the day with a 3-stroke lead over Sean O'Hair and Adam Scott, got nothing going on the front nine and shot 72. His best opportunity came at the par-3 8th, where he stuck his tee shot within four feet of the pin, but he read a big break on the putt and missed. But he and Scott still trailed Choi by 1 shot when they came to 17. Both bogeyed, ending the drama. Pampling's second shot was long over the green and he found his ball in matted rough. Scott's second shot landed on the fringe of the green, well short of the pin. Moore (66), a four-time All-American at UNLV, shot a 31 on the back nine, including five consecutive birdies, and matched his best PGA Tour finish. Scott (70) tied for fifth at 14 under with Stewart Cink (69), Fredrik Jacobson (68) and Sean O'Hair (70). Three-time Memorial champion Tiger Woods turned in his low round of the tournament with a 5-under 67 and tied for 15th at 9 under. He said it was good preparation for the U.S. Open, which begins at Oakmont on June 14. ``I feel like I've progressed nicely this week,'' Woods said. ``Today I hit so many good putts. I drove it really well, started placing the ball on the correct side of the fairways and giving myself the angles I wanted into the greens.'' In 1999, Choi became the first Korean to earn a PGA Tour card and played in his first Memorial Tournament. At the trophy presentation, Choi and Nicklaus recalled playing together in the third round that year. Choi shot 76, but still valued the experience and ended up finishing tied for 24th. ``The night before I played with him, I was nervous, just the thought of playing with this legend,'' Choi said. ``But he gave me a lot of advice. He treated me like his son and I was able to become more comfortable during the round.'' Choi said it was about three years after he first read Nicklaus' book that he realized he might have a future as a professional golfer. He said it was two years before he acquired another Nicklaus offering. But Choi didn't break par until he was 21. He turned pro at 24. On Sunday, Choi reveled in the presence of Nicklaus, referring to his 5-yard high cut shot as ``Jack style.'' Nicklaus won his first of 18 professional majors at the U.S. Open at Oakmont in 1962 and knows plenty about the legendary Pennsylvania layout. He predicted Choi could be a factor there. ``K.J., this works very well at Oakmont,'' Nicklaus said, tracking Choi's fade with his hand. ``K.J. is a high-ball hitter, a left-to-right player and I think it favors both of those.'' Few knew if Choi understood what Nicklaus said. But Nicklaus could have provided Choi's inspiration once again. Marla Ridenour can be reached at About the Real Cities Network Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/Sports/article/221228&cid=1116948476&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ TheStar.com - Sports - Castrale cashes in against Ochoa Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - Sports - Castrale cashes in against Ochoa Castrale cashes in against Ochoa Fights her way back to defeat world's No. 1 player in a playoff Jun 04, 2007 04:30 AM Nicole Castrale rarely does things the easy way, and her first LPGA Tour victory was no different. Castrale chased down the world's No. 1 player, beating Lorena Ochoa with a par on the first playoff hole yesterday at the Ginn Tribute in Mount Pleasant, S.C. For her part, Castrale was well aware of her accomplishment. &#34;To beat Lorena, yeah, the odds weren't on my side,&#34; Castrale said. Castrale was six shots behind Ochoa with six holes left in Saturday's third round. But never did she think her breakthrough was out of reach. &#34;Never did I think I couldn't catch her,&#34; Castrale said. &#34;I knew I was playing well, too.&#34; Castrale continued that confidence yesterday. She closed with a one-under 71 to match Ochoa (74) at nine-under 279, then calmly made par after Ochoa drove her ball left in a marsh on the extra hole. She had never done better than a tie for third in last season's Honda LPGA Thailand event. The loss dropped Ochoa to 0-4 in playoffs. &#34;I need to learn to win in the tough ones,&#34; she said. Cristie Kerr closed with a 73 to finish third at six under, and Paula Creamer (71) and Sarah Lee (71) tied for fourth at five under. Annika Sorenstam, the tourney host, struggled to her highest round of the week, four-over 76, and tied for 36th. She hadn't played in two months as she recovered from a ruptured disk and bulging disk. Alena Sharp of Hamilton shot a four-over 74. She earned $9,645 (U.S.) for finishing in a tie for 45th at six over. PGA: Twenty years separated two images of Jack Nicklaus, both meaningful in their own way to K.J. Choi. Nicklaus was the champion who filled every page of a pictorial instruction book that Choi studied religiously as a teenager in South Korea, a gift from a physical education teacher who encouraged him to pursue a career in golf. &#34;As I started reading it, I could understand why Jack was such a great golfer, because all the things that were written really started to make sense,&#34; Choi said. &#34;That's how I really got into golf, by reading that book.&#34; Nicklaus was the tournament host at the Memorial who stood behind the 18th green yesterday with a proud smile and hearty handshake for Choi, who closed with a seven-under 65 for a one-shot victory over Ryan Moore in Dublin, Ohio. &#34;Thank you, Jack,&#34; Choi said to him. Rod Pampling had a three-shot lead going into the final round but wound up with a 72 and tied for third with Kenny Perry, who shot 63 and was among half-dozen players in a wild chase to the finish. EUROPEAN: Richard Sterne of South Africa made a seven-foot putt on the final hole to win the Wales Open after Bradley Dredge missed a five-footer that would have forced a playoff. Dredge birdied the 15th, 16th and 17th holes to be on the verge of becoming the first Welshman to win the tournament in its eight-year history, but he bogeyed the last after driving into a bunker. CHAMPIONS: Loren Roberts won The Boeing Championship for his first Champions Tour title of the year, closing with a six-under 65 for a three-stroke victory over Eduardo Romero in Destin, Fla. Niagara Falls' Rod Spittle (71) finished in a tie for 29th at three under. NATIONWIDE: John Riegger won the LaSalle Bank Open in Illinois yesterday for his first Nationwide Tour title, holing a 20-foot birdie putt on the final hole for a four-under 68 and a one-stroke victory over B.J. Staten. Horse, heiress and a hurdle Charities worthy of donations Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news Mood ugly for Game 4 Bill France Jr., 74: Made NASCAR huge Nadal beats Hewitt at French