http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-1&fd=R&url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/story/2007/06/04/johnson-nfl-suspension.html&cid=1116969971&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ NFL suspends Tank Johnson 8 games NFL suspends Tank Johnson 8 games Last Updated: Monday, June 4, 2007 | 4:34 PM ET Tank Johnson of the Chicago Bears was suspended for as many as eight games by the NFL on Monday, the third player to face the consequences of the league's new personal conduct policy. Commissioner Roger Goodell said that the 25-year-old Johnson could have the punishment reduced to six games if he complies with all conditions of the suspension, including undergoing counselling and avoiding issues with law enforcement. GoodellÂ held a meetingÂ with Johnson in New York last week. Johnson was arrested three times in just over a year and recently completed a 60-day sentence in a Cook County, Ill., jail. He was arrested for the third time in December after a search of his home uncovered six unregistered firearms, including two assault weapons, and more than 500 rounds of ammunition. The player's bodyguard, William Posey, was also charged. Just hours after issuing a public apology to fans and teammates, the six-foot-four, 300-pound Johnson was in a Chicago club when Posey was gunned down. Because he violated terms of his probation, Johnson needed permission from a judge to leave the state and suit up for the Bears in their Super Bowl game in Miami in February. Johnson recorded four tackles in Chicago's loss and shared credit with Mark Anderson for the team's only sack of Indianapolis Colts quarterback Peyton Manning. In April, Adam (Pacman) Jones of the Tennessee Titans was suspended for the 2007 NFL season and Chris Henry of the Cincinnati Bengals was suspended for eight games. Jones has been arrested several times, including in connection with an incident inside a Las Vegas strip club in February. A shooting outside the club later left a man paralyzed. Henry was arrested four times in a 14-month span. Goodell announcedÂ a move towardsÂ tougher disciplinary measures in February. In recent years, suspensions have usually been in connection with violations of the league's substance abuse policy. With files from the Associated Press Dickenson, Lions agree to new deal Dave Dickenson has pledged his future to the B.C. Lions after signing a contract extension with the CFL club. NFL suspends Tank Johnson 8 games Tank Johnson of the Chicago Bears was suspended for as many as eight games by the NFL on Monday, the third player to face the consequences of the league's new personal conduct policy. QB Johnson retires from Eskimos Backup quarterback Jason Johnson retired from the Edmonton Eskimos on Sunday, ending a three-year stint with the football club. Argos sign Anthony Dorsett Anthony Dorsett will attempt a football comeback in the CFL, with the safety signing with the Toronto Argonauts. Blue Bombers get Dorsey, Epp for Wilson The Winnipeg Blue Bombers dealt offensive tackle Eric Wilson to the Saskatchewan Roughriders for kick returner Dominique Dorsey and defensive end Dwan Epps on Wednesday. Senators beginning to feel it The Senators, trailing the Anaheim Ducks 2-1 in the Stanley Cup final, are looking to even their series in Game 4 Monday night at Scotiabank Place (CBC, 8 p.m. ET). Dickenson, Lions agree to new deal Dave Dickenson has pledged his future to the B.C. Lions after signing a contract extension with the CFL club. Nadal sweeps Hewitt at French Open Rafael Nadal continued his bid for a third straight French Open title, knocking off Lleyton Hewitt of Australia in straight sets on Monday to advance to the quarter-finals. Canucks reward Pyatt with new deal The Vancouver Canucks officially announced the re-signing of Taylor Pyatt on Monday, with the forward getting a two-year extension. Claudio Ranieri named coach of Juventus Claudio Ranieri has been appointed Juventus's new coach, the Turin club announced Monday. Defender heads home winner Roger