http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.autoracingdaily.com/article/former_nascar_ceo_and_chairman_bill_france_passes_away_at_age_of_74/&cid=1116968844&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Auto Racing Daily : Former NASCAR CEO and Chairman Bill France Passes Away at Age of 74 Former NASCAR CEO and Chairman Bill France Passes Away at Age of 74 Sports Car Club of America Champ Car World Series Former NASCAR CEO and Chairman Bill France Passes Away at Age of 74 NASCAR Vice Chairman William C. France, whose leadership helped turn a family-owned company into a national phenomenon, died today at his home in Daytona Beach, Fla. at the age of 74. France served as NASCAR&#8217;s president from 1972-2000, taking over from his father, NASCAR founder William H. G. &#8220;Big Bill&#8221; France. In 2000, France &#8211; known as &#8220;Bill Jr. &#8221; &#8211; became NASCAR&#8217;s CEO and the chairman of the newly created NASCAR Board of Directors. In October 2003, the torch was again passed, with France&#8217;s son Brian France taking over as Chairman and CEO. France became Vice Chairman at that time, whereupon his influence and input remained considerable &#8211; and valuable. &#8220;He had a remarkable career and an even-more remarkable life, &#8221; said Brian France. &#8220;Words cannot express how much he&#8217;ll be missed by myself and the rest of our family and by the NASCAR industry overall. &#8221; Mike Helton became NASCAR&#8217;s president in 2000. He was the third president in the sport&#8217;s history and the first not named France. &#8220;Coming in, I had two big pairs of shoes to fill, &#8221; Helton said, talking about Bill Sr. and Bill Jr. &#8220;I was more familiar with Bill Jr. &#8217;s way of doing business but that didn&#8217;t make it any easier. He blazed so many trails for our sport. He was determined to follow the vision of his father while also expanding on that vision. Over nearly four decades, he did a masterful job. &#8221; France is survived by his wife Betty Jane France, NASCAR&#8217;s assistant secretary; his son Brian; daughter Lesa France Kennedy, NASCAR&#8217;s vice president and assistant treasurer; his brother James C. France, NASCAR&#8217;s vice chairman and executive vice president; and three grandchildren. Funeral arrangements are pending. Page 1 of 1 pages for this article Comments on "Former NASCAR CEO and Chairman Bill France Passes Away at Age of 74" You must be a member to post a comment. Please login using the form below or Auto-login on future visits Show my name in the online users list Late Models & Stock Cars -- Late Model Racing -- Stock Car Racing -- Sports Car Racing -- Sports Car Club of America IRL & Champ Cars -- Indy Racing League -- Champ Car World Series -- Junior Formula Series -- World Rally Championship -- Sprint Car Racing -- Craftsman Truck Series -- NASCAR Busch Series -- NASCAR Nextel Cup -- Touring Car Racing -- Vintage Auto Racing -- Dirt Track Racing -- Women in Racing -- A1 Grand Prix -- Dale Earnhardt Inc. Get Auto Racing Daily in your Email Free. Unsubscribe at any time Tommy Baldwin Jr. Assumes The Role of Crew Chief For The No. 22 Caterpillar Racing Team Pit Road Penalties Not an Issue For Key Motorsports in NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series Three Days Until the NEXTEL Prelude to the Dream Carl Edwards on Winning NASCAR Busch Race at Dover: &#8220;There, We Did. We Screwed It Up&#8221; Jeff Gordon: &#8220;It&#8217;s Been A Long Time Since I&#8217;ve Raced at Eldora&#8221; Clarks helping to keep Marhefka competitive McMahan takes Outlaws win at Eldora Team Sahlen Captures 7th Place at Lime Rock Grand-Am Rolex Round Stevenson Corvette Drives To Top 10 Finish At Lime Rock Park A need for speed Danica Patrick: &#8220;When You Don&#8217;t Have Any Grip, You Don&#8217;t Have Any Speed&#8221; Mat Mladin: &#8220;Wet or Dry, You Have to Stay Focused And be Prepared&#8221; Marco Andretti: &#8220;A Good Car Will Bring You to The Front at This Place&#8221; Former 