http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-4&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/topics/sports/story.html%3Fid%3D1b4483a5-b880-4974-974e-14f4566f6123%26k%3D61105&cid=1116547509&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Current Pistons mere shadow of Bad Boys Jump to: canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio A Shopper's Secret Diary A Shopper's Secret Diary What's Hot and What's Not What's Hot and What's Not Ask a Shopping Question Ask a Shopping Question Unsure of how to feature? Click me to Current Pistons mere shadow of Bad Boys Cleveland Cavaliers' LeBron James hoists the trophy after the Cavaliers beat the Detroit Pistons, 98-82, to win the NBA Eastern Conference championship, Saturday, in Cleveland. Photograph by : Associated Press/Tony Dejak Bob Duff, CanWest News Service; Windsor Star Published: Monday, June 04, 2007 WINDSOR, Ont. - As finishes go, this one was more feeble than fantastic. It's all done now for the Detroit Pistons. The season, after a 98-82 drubbing by the Cleveland Cavaliers Saturday in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference final. And the legacy. Not to mention the comparisons. Ever since the Pistons won the 2003-'04 National Basketball Association title, as part of back-to-back runs to the NBA final, the debate has raged among supporters of the team. Which dynasty was better - the Bad Boys or the current edition of the team? It's safe to say that argument can now be shelved. It's the Bad Boys in a landslide. They won two straight titles, which in itself should end the parallels. But more importantly, they remembered the root cause of their success and never forgot what made them famous. While digesting the demise of the Pistons, chew on a couple of thoughts: - How many championship rings have the Pistons earned since Larry Brown exited as coach? - How many titles have they won since Ben Wallace took the money and ran to Chicago? The answer is as empty as the playoff hopes of the Pistons are today. Brown used to stress that winning was about playing the game the right way and no one can dispute that's exactly how the Pistons played under his leadership. Certainly, Brown's ego was as vast as his knowledge of the game, but does that make him any different than Scotty Bowman? The Detroit Red Wings knew what they were getting when they hired Bowman, but dealt with the difficulties, because it resulted in three Stanley Cups. Another reason why the Wings won? Strong leadership. Steve Yzerman ruled the ship and no one questioned his authority in the dressing room. Ben Wallace filed that role for the Pistons. They were a team built around his image, a group of misfits who together were formidable opponents. Does anyone actually think Cleveland's LeBron James goes for 48 points in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference final if Ben was present to provide help defence to his teammates? It was evident last season that Ben was clearly unhappy with the course the team was charting under new coach Flip Saunders, one that was taking them away from the strong emphasis on defensive play. Today, it's also evident that Wallace had a point. When Detroit won, the Pistons did it in such un-NBA like fashion. It was about everyone pulling the rope in the same direction. Absent their glue, as everything came apart against the Cavaliers, so did the Pistons. When collectiveness was most needed, instead, there was bickering. "The way our team is, it's always been one to point fingers at each other," Saunders suggested, seeking to put a happy face on Detroit's sad demise. "It's important for players to not be afraid to hold another player accountable." Saunders likes to say that the NBA is a player's league and in Detroit's case, instead of Ben Wallace's team, it's become a team built in Rasheed Wallace's image - still capable of greatness, but equally as likely to collapse into a sea of selfishness. "We're built as a five-man unit, so when one of our players breaks down in that five-man unit, either offensively or defensively, we can look really bad because we don't have the one guy that can bail you out," Saunders said. They certainly ended up looking very bad when it mattered most this season, which leads to another pertinent question. Perhaps it's time to sink this ship and chart a new course for the Pistons. Senators look to keep up pressure The Ottawa Senators have caught some breaks and now want to catch momentum. "The confidence level of... Citizen's Scanlan on Senators McAmmond, Kunitz still doubtful Senators dodge one bullet Gallery: Stanley Cup action Full NHL playoffs coverage LeBron, Cavaliers graduate to NBA finals As confetti danced in the electrified air around him and a feverish hometown crowd rocked and rolled... James has lived up to the hype Mere shadow of Bad Boys FIA clears McLaren team in Monaco investigation Formula One's governing body cleared the McLaren team of any wrongdoing Wednesday... CTV adds seven new shows CTV is adding seven new series to its fall schedule and taking three from a competitor... See CTV's new shows CanWest announces new shows See some of the new CanWest shows CBC unveils fall schedule Fall schedule good and bad for Canadian talent iPhone gets June 29 launch Apple Inc.'s highly anticipated iPhone will be available in the U.S. June 29, according... Gates, Jobs make rare joint appearance Apple delays launch of operating system Apple awe turns sour Visit Shopping on canada.com We've got the inside scoop on everything Shopping-related! Get in-the-know today! Read our Shopping Advice column Whatâ€™s Hot & Whatâ€™s Not? Shop Online for Great Stuff! Ask our experts a Shopping question! Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in Montreal... Mexican crime won't stop Canadians Canadians took more trips abroad... Go topless this summer A sure sign of spring is the sight... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republicatio