http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-3&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060300834.html&cid=1116945167&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Ray Again Can't Close the Deal for the Orioles - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Ray Again Can't Close the Deal for the Orioles Angels 4, Orioles 3 Washington Post Staff Writer Monday, June 4, 2007; Page E10 ANAHEIM, Calif., June 3 -- That Jeremy Guthrie had thrown 88 pitches and dominated the Los Angeles Angels for eight innings did not matter. What mattered is the Baltimore Orioles led by a run in the ninth inning, and Manager Sam Perlozzo believed he needed to do what such a situation dictates. "Our closer is supposed to come in and get you three outs," he said. "That's Chris Ray's job, to save that game for us." But Ray, in a stunningly swift bottom of the ninth, didn't do his job, and it remains open to speculation how much longer the job will be his. Vladimir Guerrero concluded the Orioles' crushing 4-3 loss Sunday by drilling a two-run homer to right-center field, giving Baltimore three straight losses and Ray his fourth blown save this season. Los Angeles' Vlad Guerrero connects on a 1-1 pitch to send the Orioles to their third straight loss. (Mark Avery - AP) again, as Vlad Guerrero's two-run homer in the ninth inning gives the Angels a 4-3 win on Sunday. Orioles second baseman Brian Roberts has stayed hot despite a hurt right hamstring. Box score: Angels 4, O's 3 | Enhancing a Legacy Save & Share Article The blast, which clattered around the rock pile behind the fence, nullified another outstanding start from Guthrie, who, teammate Kevin Millar said, has "turned into one of the most dominating pitchers going right now in the big leagues." Guthrie allowed three hits and one earned run, mixing in more curveballs than usual but still locating his 95-mph fastball with precision. Despite the performance, 88 pitches and eight innings were enough. "You don't want that kid to lose the game," Perlozzo said. "Somebody gets on, you got to let him go out and lose the ballgame. You can't go to your closer then, you're trying to stay out of trouble. You leave him, he's got to go in and pitch the whole way through that thing. That's the job of the closer. We got ourselves right where we wanted to be." While no blown save is a calm event, Ray's meltdowns have been particularly catastrophic, and all against high-profile opponents. Three have come on home runs. Ray's last implosion came in the infamous May 13 "Mother's Day Miracle" at Fenway Park, when the final five runs crossed the plate while Ray was on the mound. On that day, too, it was Guthrie who was victimized by a bullpen disaster. Perlozzo hinted he would contemplate replacing Ray, if only he had options. Danys Baez has experience as a closer, but his ineffectiveness already has earned him a demotion from the setup role. "We got to get a little more consistent about that," Perlozzo said. "We're taxing our other guys as it is. If your closer and your eighth-inning guy can't get anybody out, where do you go?" Still, the decision to turn to Ray on Sunday was easy. Guthrie ran into his first real trouble of the day in the eighth, hitting Erick Aybar in the shin and then allowing him to score on a blooped double by Casey Kotchman. Guthrie escaped with no further damage, then walked into the dugout. Perlozzo asked, "How do you feel?" Guthrie responded, "Who's coming up?" "That's not an answer I wanted to hear," Perlozzo said. Perlozzo and Guthrie chatted more. Finally, Guthrie told him, "Let's go with Chris." "We were playing baseball the way it's supposed to be played," Guthrie said. "That's the way you play. Play to get it there, and everyone does their job." Only Ray could not do his. He started Chone Figgins with two balls, finally threw a strike, then surrendered a single to left. Up came Guerrero, whom the Orioles had held to one hit in his previous 10 at-bats. But that still fostered little confidence, given Guerrero's frightening power and disregard for pressure. Ray began Guerrero with a low fastball for strike one, then tried to make him chase a slider for ball one. Ray then came back with another slider, but this was not in the dirt. He left the pitch hanging letter-high, and Guerrero unleashed perhaps the most violent swing in the league. Jay Payton gave chase to the warning track, then punched the outfield wall as he watched the ball sail over it. Angel Stadium exploded, the Orioles slowly walked off the field and the Angels poured out of their dugout. It was a scene Ray had lived before, but one his teammates trust he can discard. "One of the best things about Ray-Ray is he has a short-term memory," Millar said. "When you are in that role, you have to." "You just have to go out and play tomorrow," Ray said. "I don't feel good about it." And so the Orioles were left to swallow another one-run loss, their 13th this season against six wins. Melvin Mora, who hit a go-ahead solo home run in the fourth, shooed away reporters and said, "I don't want to talk about that . . . game." Perlozzo tried forgetting it, too, particularly the final pitch, which he vowed not to watch on videotape. "Once is enough," he said. Guerrero's Homer Gives Angels Comeback Win Vlad Hits 2-Run Shot As Angels Top Birds Saunders Steps Up As Angels Top Orioles Torre Gets Ejected; Yankees Beat Red Sox Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this site. Please review the governing commentaries and discussions. You a