http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-1&fd=R&url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php%3Ft%3D217666&cid=1116936247&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ SportingNews.com - NFL - Broncos sign DT Sam Adams Broncos sign DT Sam Adams Comments on this article Posted: June 4, 2007 DENVER -- Veteran defensive tackle Sam Adams, who played last season with Cincinnati, signed on Monday with Denver. The 335-pound Adams, a three-time Pro Bowler, previously played for Buffalo, Oakland, Baltimore and Seattle, winning a Super Bowl ring with the Ravens after the 2000 season and playing in the title game with Oakland two years later. He was a first-round pick of Seattle in 1994, the eighth overall choice in the draft.. Adams, who will turn 34 on June 13, is known as a run-stuffer, but has 44 career sacks, fourth among active defensive tackles. In 195 career regular-season games, he has started 166 times and recorded 463 tackles, including 326 solo; three interceptions for 62 yards; 37 pass breakups, 10 forced fumbles and five fumble recoveries. He has 10 postseason starts with 26 tackles (17 solo), two sacks for nine yards, four pass breakups, one forced fumble and one fumble recovery Adams started all 16 games for the Bengals last year with 25 tackles, two sacks for eight yards and one pass breakup. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. SPEAK OUT ON THIS ARTICLE Comments on this article Add your own comment to this article There have been no comments on this post Be the first to comment on this topic and get the conversation rolling. Remember to keep your comments clean and on topic. Attack the issue, not the writer or each other. Comment on this article All times are EST American City Business Journals, Inc. &copy; 2001, 2005 phpBB Group
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-4&fd=R&url=http://www.indystar.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/SPORTS0107/706040350/-1/LOCAL17&cid=1116947249&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Two sides of the story | IndyStar.com Letters to The Editor Charges dropped in juvenile center case Carmel tech firm to add 100 workers Guilty plea in cabbie's death Indiana kangaroo dies after capture Dem lawmaker returning to funeral biz Greenspan on Hoeppner: "We're concerned" Two sides of the story Patrick-Wheldon incident overshadows Kanaan's victory Penskes' rear-wing failures spark curiosity Sign up for Star Sports newsletter &#149; Have the late night sports news delivered to your inbox with IndyStar.com's latest newsletter. Stop in Today at Tom Wood Ford, and check out the all new Ford Edge, Ford Focus and much more! Lexus Certified Pre-Owned includes 3 Year or 100,000 Total Vehicle Mileage Warranty. Click Here! Coast to Coast Imports Quality Luxury Imports BMWs, Lexus, Mercedes only at Coast to Coast View all Top Car Deals WEST ALLIS, Wis. -- If Danica Patrick wants to get tough with Dan Wheldon, the former Indianapolis 500 winner is ready for it. Good job, pal: Indy Racing League race winner Tony Kanaan (left) is congratulated by third-place finisher Dan Wheldon. Wheldon and Danica Patrick made contact during the race, each blaming the other. "Maybe it's inexperience on her part," he said. - Greg Griffo / The Star Learjet 550 at Fort Worth, Texas 9:30 p.m. Saturday; ESPN2 coverage begins at 10 p.m. Patrick chastised Wheldon for contact between the two in Sunday's Indy-car race at the Milwaukee Mile. Patrick ended the post-race exchange on pit road by grabbing Wheldon's elbow and shoving him. The Patrick-Wheldon scuffle and ensuing war of words overshadowed Tony Kanaan's race victory. "If she wants to get feisty," Wheldon said afterward, "I'm a lot tougher than her on the track." Patrick blamed Wheldon for turning down on her entering the first turn of the 89th lap of the ABC Supply/A.J. Foyt 225. She had passed Wheldon and Indianapolis 500 winner Dario Franchitti in the previous corner, and they were in a three-wide sprint down the front straightaway for fourth place. Franchitti recognized the danger of the situation and pulled his car back from the potential mess. Knowing excess tire debris was in the high lane, Wheldon sought to avoid it, but Patrick's car was inside him. Patrick's right front tire banged into Wheldon's left rear tire, and the contact sent her sliding into the infield. She kept the car from wall contact, but a piece of her steering mechanism had to be replaced on pit road, costing her a lap to the leaders. Patrick scrambled back to finish eighth -- Wheldon ended up third -- but she felt she deserved more, and Wheldon was her target. "I don't know if he has tunnel vision, but this is racing and a pass is a pass," she said angrily. "Did anyone see the replay?" Patrick said she asked Wheldon about his move on several occasions but did not get much of an answer. That's what prompted the shove, she said. "I'm not sure what is lost in translation (with him)," she said. Patrick said she expected Indy Racing League officials to penalize Wheldon, but it could be Patrick who gets a reaction from competition director Brian Barnhart. This was the second time Patrick has made physical contact with a fellow competitor following a race. She shoved Jaques Lazier following their crash at California Speedway in 2005. Barnhart said Wheldon would not be penalized, and he will review Patrick's behavior on pit road. "It looked like one of those racing deals," Barnhart said. "(Wheldon) has to turn down and if it's two-wide, he's expecting (Patrick) to turn down, too. "This was a result of close competition, and I don't feel like that's worth a penalty on the racetrack. Dan didn't want to have contact." Patrick didn't let the issue drop. She said Wheldon was mad that she passed him during the 500, and she called him stubborn when she approached him Sunday. "If he thinks I'm not going to remember that . . . ," she said. Wheldon insisted Patrick wasn't alongside him entering the corner, and he said her reaction shows she's feeling the pressure of never having won a major race, including 36 in Indy cars. Patrick is the only driver on the Andretti Green Racing team without a victory. Wheldon, a Ganassi Racing driver who previously drove for AGR, has won 13 of his 69 IRL races, including the 2005 Indy 500 en route to the season championship. "I've been around long enough to know when someone's inside me," he said. "Maybe it's inexperience on her part." Patrick had been the star of the race prior to the contact, driving from 17th on the starting grid to fourth place with speed and timely moves. She had a pair of two-car passes in the same corner. The first was on Buddy Rice and Scott Dixon in the fourth turn on lap 64 to get her to sixth place. Kanaan led 37 of the 225 laps for a victory that was a nice consolation prize to last week's disappointing 12th-place finish at Indy. But there was too much action Sunday to allow him the spotlight. Helio Castroneves, who led 126 laps, crashed by himself off the fourth turn on lap 201 when his rear wing mount broke. Sam Hornish Jr. was chasing Kanaan with six laps to go when his rear wing bracket broke, too. Marco Andretti crashed for the third time in the past four races, a second-turn slap on lap 210. Franchitti, the Indy winner, finished second to take the points lead heading to Saturday night's race at Texas Motor Speedway. Call Star reporter Curt Cavin at (317) 444-6409. Send feedback about IndyStar.com Use of this site signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights , updated August, 2006. Copyright 2007 IndyStar.com. All rights reserved .Build 0: 0 ms (Misc) .Build 9: 31 ms (Content)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-2&fd=R&url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2007/06/04/2007-06-04_rocket_relaunch_now_likely_saturday-1.html&cid=1116805600&ei=iIBkRsmSMY6WrgOdh4DPBQ Rocket relaunch now likely Saturday Rocket relaunch now likely Saturday DAILY NEWS SPORTS WRITER Monday, June 4th 2007, 8:41 AM Roger Clemens in the dugout during a game he pitched for the Scranton Wilkes-Barre Yankees. BOSTON - Roger Clemens could make his Yankees debut on Saturday in the Bronx, but the Yankees aren't making anything official until they get the results of today's MRI on his groin. Clemens was examined yesterday in Tampa by Dr. Allen Miller. Miller decided an MRI was necessary to determine the extent of Clemens' "fatigued right groin," the injury that caused the Rocket to be scratched from tonight's start in Chicago. "(Miller) wants to get a feel for what we're dealing with and the only real way to do that is to get an MRI," GM Brian Cashman said. "Until we get the MRI, we'd just be guessing. I just know Roger is optimistic." Clemens feels he will be able to start for the Yankees on Saturday against the Pirates, a sentiment echoed by a hopeful Joe Torre before last night's game. "We're not scheduling, but we're tentatively looking at possibly next weekend," Torre said. "We certainly don't want him to say, 'I can pitch with this.' That's not something we want; it's too important that he goes out there every five days to just have one start, and then maybe we don't have him." "He feels that the sure thing is that instead of (today), he can slot in the next time," Cashman said. "He's optimistic about that, that's all I can communicate." The Yankees will give Matt DeSalvo the ball tonight in Clemens' place, recalling the 26-year-old in place of first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz, who is expected to be out six to eight weeks after his collision with Mike Lowell on Saturday. DeSalvo was 1-2 with a 5.40 ERA in five games, four of them starts, before being sent down to Triple-A on Friday. Cashman indicated that he has no plans to back out of Clemens' contract, which the Yankees could opt to do since it is a nonguaranteed, minor-league deal. There is no language in the prorated $28 million pact that requires the Yankees to call him up to the majors, but Cashman believes that Clemens can help his team make a run at the postseason. "I want to have a healthy Roger Clemens, when he's ready, to assist this team, because we still have a shot," Cashman said. "We're not out of it and we feel he can have a big impact." Despite the hype and buildup that accompanied Clemens' anticipated return tonight - including shifting the start time an hour back to 7 p.m. Eastern time to accomodate national television - Torre said he and his players have had more to concern themselves with this weekend than Clemens' status. "We've had a habit of never counting our chickens until they show up," Torre said. "Especially here in Boston, we're not looking forward to (today) when we have work to do here. We never got to the point of feeling he was here." A-Rod's blast is punchline Back spasm not dandy for Andy Damon's first thought becoming reality It's one hard fall for Doug Now that's Mo like it for Torre's Bombers Papel-bomb KO's Red Sox Sign up to receive daily newsletters Buy an Ad link Use of this website signifies your agreement to the &copy; Copyright 2007 NYDailyNews.com. All rights reserved.
