Cleveland an 86-71 bubble with 6:52 to play. As Cleveland made the finishing touches of their improbable playoffs run, the veteran Pistons improbably melted under pressure. Rasheed Wallace lost his temper and was ejected following two technical foul calls with 7:44 remaining and the Cavs cruising along toward their first ever trip to the NBA Finals since the franchise joined the league in 1971. I pick Detroit to win this series and advance to their third NBA Finals appearance in five years. It was an easy choice given Detroit’s experience and firepower. I have doubted Cleveland to make a serious run because I thought there was not enough talent around LeBron James. But how wrong I was. The Cavaliers demonstrated a cohesiveness that I thought they never had. They avoided Detroit’s traps wisely, they passed the ball around, and they showed a lot of toughness by out-rebounding Detroit 51-38. I already had a hotel reservation for my Finals trip supposedly to Detroit but last night I had to frantically cancel that reservation and scamper for a hotel room accommodation for one week somewhere in downtown Cleveland, where the Cavs will host the Spurs in Games 3, 4, and 5. When the 2006-2007 season began last November, I have consistently picked he Spurs to win it all. I am not about to change now. Even with LeBron’s greatness, Gibson’s coming out party, and the Cavs’ newfound confidence, I have unbridled faith in Tim Duncan and the mighty San Antonio Spurs. The Spurs will win the 2007 NBA Finals in six. With a game left to play, Green is a sure win WITH one more event left to play, the Green Team has virtually annexed the overall championship title after earning 155 points to lord over three other teams in the 2007 Sun.Star Cebu Sportsfest. After scoring 90 points in the opening day by winning the mixed volleyball and the men’s and women’s badminton events, the Green Team collected an additional 65 points to pull away from a tough competition with only the bowling event to 